<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--Secord     05-13 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Secord,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secord Says He Doesn't Need Pardon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Gen. Richard Secord,
accused of working as a middleman in the Iran-Contra affair, said
Thursday he neither expects nor wants a pardon from President
Reagan _ because one isn't necessary.
   ``I didn't break any laws, so why would there be any pardon?''
he told The Palm Beach Post before addressing the Young Republicans
of the Palm Beaches.
   ``I think we did the right thing. I'm not embarrassed about what
we did, how we did it,'' Secord said. ``I think we will prevail.''
   Secord and Iranian-born businessman Albert Hakim are accused of
helping set up the arms-for-hostages deal that prosecutors said was
orchestrated by former White House aides Oliver North and John
Poindexter.
   The four were indicted in March on charges of conspiring to
divert profits from the arms sales to Nicaragua's Contras at a time
when most aid to the rebels was prohibited.
</TEXT>
