<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Staley-Tate     05-13 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Staley-Tate,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tate & Lyle Announces Takeover of Staley</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British sugar refiner Tate & Lyle
PLC announced late Friday it has entered into a definitive $1.44
billion agreement to acquire Staley Continental Inc., a maker of
corn syrup and food-service supplies.
   The agreement was unanimously approved by Staley's board of
directors, Tate & Lyle said in a statement.
   Under the pact, Tate & Lyle's offer of $35 cash per common share
of Staley stock will be increased to $36.50, the British company
said.
   Staley spokesman David Satterfield could not be reached from
comment. Calls to his office went unanswered, and he did not return
messages left at his home.
   The tender offer is set to expire May 27 at midnight EDT. Tate &
Lyle's offer to buy Staley depository shares for $53.15 each and
preferred shares for $105 each would not change under Friday's
agreement.
   Staley is based in this northwest Chicago suburb. Tate & Lyle
covets its Decatur-based A.E. Staley Manufacturing Co. subsidiary,
the second-largest U.S. refiner of corn syrup.
   Staley also owns CFS Continental Inc., a major producer of
single-serving condiments and other food-service supplies, which
Tate & Lyle would probably sell.
   The agreement was announced after New York Stock Exchange had
closed. Staley closed at 36~ on the NYSE, down 1]. Analysts have
said Staley has a fair market value of about $40 per common share.
   Tate & Lyle publicly began its takeover bid for all shares of
Staley common stock April 8 at a price of $32 per share.
   Officials said Tate & Lyle held 4.9 percent of the approximately
30 million outstanding common shares of Staley stock when it began
takeover efforts and has since obtained an additional 1.03 million
shares.
   The British company has said it would move Staley's headquarters
back to Decatur, the central Illinois city that was the company's
home until 1985.
</TEXT>
