<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Peru-PopeViolence     05-13 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Pope Violence,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Firebomb Papal Press Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 60 leftist guerrillas on Friday
night stoned and firebombed the hotel where the papal press center
is headquartered, a day before Pope John Paul II arrives in the
capital, police and witnesses said.
   The rebels, many wearing hoods and chanting revolutionary
slogans, smashed three large front windows as they paraded past the
Hotel Crillon, guests and employees said.
   The bomb, described as a molotov cocktail by employees, exploded
against a window above the main entryway, destroying the window and
setting an inside curtain ablaze, witnesses told The Associated
Press.
   There were no injuries and the blaze was rapidly squelched with
a fire extinguisher, police said. The press center for the papal
visit is headquarted on the main floor of the plush hotel, one of
Lima's finest, and many foreign journalists and tourists are
staying in the seven-story building.
   The violence came amid a wave of guerrilla activity Friday and
followed a weeklong series of rebel attacks preceding the pope's
arrival Saturday afternoon.
   Also Friday, leftist guerrillas bombed a bank and strafed a
military installation with machine gun fire from a passing car,
police said. There were no injuries in either attack.
   Police said it was unclear which of Peru's main rebel bands
carried out Friday's violence.
   The Mao-inspired Shining Path began its insurgency eight years
ago. The pro-Cuba Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement has been
mounting attacks since 1984.
   The government said guerrillas violence was expected during the
visit, the pope's second to this Andean nation, and has deployed
3,500 special police and military troops as papal security and
ordered the capital's 50,000 police officers to remain on duty
serving rotating shifts throughout the visit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
