<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-PersianGulf     05-13 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Persian Gulf,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adams Says Senate Should Declare Stance On Persian Gulf Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate critic of President Reagan's year-old
Persian Gulf policy chided his colleagues for refusing to vote on
whether they stood behind the administration.
   ``For over a year, we have danced around the issue,'' Sen. Brock
Adams, D-Wash., said Thursday after the Senate voted 82-13 to table
his proposal to require a detailed report from Reagan outlining his
policy.
   Adams' plan, which he wanted to attach to a Pentagon budget
bill, would have given Congress 15 days to vote to disapprove that
policy. Support for Reagan's plan would be implicit if there was no
negative vote within that time.
   Neither the House nor the Senate has formally voted either
approval or disapproval of Reagan's policy of having the Navy
protect 11 reflagged Kuwaiti tankers.
   That policy expanded two weeks ago, when Reagan extended the
U.S. umbrella to protect neutral merchant ships if they come under
attack and seek Navy help in the war-torn region.
   There have been a number of military clashes between the Navy
and Iranian forces. The most recent occurred April 18, when Navy
ships and planes destroyed two Iranian oil platforms and sank or
damaged six Iranian vessels.
   Reagan has refused to invoke the War Powers Act, the 1973 law
that limits a president's authority to send U.S. military personnel
to situations of ``imminent danger.'' Reagan, as have his
predecessors, argues that the law is an unconstitutional
restriction on his authority.
   Adams has been defeated in several previous attempts to have the
Senate begin the process of invoking the War Powers law. He and 110
other legislators have sued to invoke the law, but a federal judge
rejected the suit and the legislators are appealing that rejection.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, criticized Reagan's policy as ``foolish
... stupid'' but he opposed Adams' plan. He said it might mean that
U.S. forces would be pulled out of the region.
   Glenn said, ``If we pull out and the Persian Gulf falls under
the domination of some other power, then it has become an
instrument for other nations.''
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., criticized Adams' idea because he
contended it ``would require the president to be a prophet. ... I'm
not sure the president can provide a plan, given the fluid nature
of events in that part of the world.''
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said the plan ``is another example
of what Congress is criticized for. ... You can't have 535
secretaries of state,'' referring to the total number of House and
Senate members.
   Another critic was Sen. John Warner, R-Va., a former secretary
of the Navy. He told Adams, ``I think it would be ill-advised for
the Congress to single out any particular military operation and
say, on an annual basis, that we're going to appropriate money for
that operation.''
</TEXT>
