<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaigns In California, Attacks Administration Drug
Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson was campaigning today in
California, where he hopes to make a final show of strength against
front-runner Michael Dukakis in the season-closing June 7 primary.
   Jackson arrived here Thursday night after three days of
campaigning in Oregon, which holds its primary on Tuesday. He was
visiting a drug-treatment center in Tarzana before heading for
northern California.
   Jackson's aides have said he will devote substantial time and
money to his effort in California, with its prize of 314 delegates.
   As he campaigned in Oregon on Thursday, Jackson criticized a
proposed deal between the Reagan administration and Panamanian
strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega, who is under indictment on drug
charges.
   ``It's not just Noriega. Others are dealing in drugs. We can't
indict them one day and exonerate them the next day. That is no
policy at all,'' Jackson said at a Portland news conference.
   At a rally at a Woodburn junior high school, Jackson reiterated
his criticism of the administration over Noriega.
   ``It's not enough to just say no out of one side of the White
House, then have drug dealers on the CIA payroll on the other side
of the White House,'' he said, adding: ``Our children's lives are
at stake.''
   He called for increased border patrols and for a summit with
Latin American leaders to find ways to stem the flow of drugs into
the United States.
   ``As president I will cut the supply of drugs,'' he said.
   In Halsey, Ore., Jackson joined about 300 striking workers and
their families at the James River Corp. mill, where the United
Paperworkers International Union has been on strike since April 15.
   ``You can't give up. When the going gets tough, embrace each
other and hold out until the morning comes. We've got to stay
together,'' Jackson told the strikers. ``Workers united will never
be defeated.''
