<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTL     05-13 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Sports Entrepreneur Considering Buying Most of PTL</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The failing PTL ministry is nearing
agreement on a plan to sell much of its Heritage USA theme park to
a Charlotte sports entrepreneur, The Charlotte Observer reported
Friday.
   For PTL, the plan promises a rescue from imminent liquidation of
the evangelical empire built by Jim and Tammy Bakker while allowing
the ministry to maintain control of its church activities, the
newspaper said.
   Under the plan, George Shinn would buy all or most of PTL's
1,700 acres, including a hotel and water park, and move his
Charlotte Knights minor league baseball team to a sports complex to
be built at the theme park near Fort Mill, S.C., the newspaper said.
   Shinn might also buy the ministry facilities, including the TV
studio, church and amphitheater, and lease them back to a
reorganized, tax-exempt ministry to be called Heritage Ministries,
the Observer said.
   The ministry would have an option to buy the facilities and
would have absolute control over its church functions.
   If the plan is approved, PTL trustee David Clark said Wednesday,
``It's going to be a wonderful turnaround in what's been a very
tragic situation.''
   The estimated $100 million plan is contingent on York County,
S.C., financing the $12 million sports complex, which would include
a 15,000-seat stadium and a training center for Shinn's Charlotte
Hornets, which joins the NBA next year.
   As part of the negotiations, Shinn wants state and county
officials to agree to build a six-lane road to connect the stadium
to Interstate 77 south of Charlotte, the Observer said.
   Any agreement with the county apparently is still days, if not
weeks, away, the Observer reported. The plan also is subject to
approval by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds, who already has
ordered PTL to start liquidating assets.
   ``As far as the ministry, my objective is not to take it over. I
just want to assist its recovery in any way I can,'' Shinn said.
``We would do the whole thing _ except for the ministry _ for
profit. And we would pay our taxes.''
   PTL is being reorganized in bankruptcy court with debts that
could total up to $130 million, including $82 million in back taxes
and penalties.
   Bakker criticized the deal, saying he would be ``terribly
disappointed if Heritage USA became a secular center.''
</TEXT>
