<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0139EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     05-13 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dance Festival Gets Its Biggest Hit Yet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York City Ballet, in the third week of
its three-week American Music Festival, is loaded with new ballets.
And Thursday night, a juxtaposition of dance styles in a ballet
created by Peter Martins was so stunning it became the favorite so
far.
   Martins, who shares heading the company with Jerome Robbins,
named his new ballet by the music, a practice also of the late
George Balanchine. ``Barber Violin Concerto'' is for two couples.
   Merrill Ashley and Adam Luders are principal dancers in the
company. They danced in neoclassic style _ classical ballet steps
put together with originality _ to Barber's lovely melody.
   Kate Johnson of the Paul Taylor Dance Company and David Parsons,
formerly of the Taylor company, danced as guest artists in a much
more modern style. When Kate was lifted, instead of prettily
pointing her feet, she would bicycle her legs.
   This juxtaposition of styles _ sometimes both couples danced at
the same time, to the same music, in very different ways _ was
interesting. The second movement became exciting and the third
movement highly amusing.
   Parsons danced with the ballerina in a style more modern than
neoclassic, but less modern than he had danced earlier. Then Luders
danced with Miss Johnson, who became a whirling perpetual motion
machine. Sometimes he wanted to walk away from her but she was
spinning around him, jumping on his back, waving her limbs. A long
ovation followed the ballet, with many curtain calls.
   Nadia Salerno Sonnenberg was violin soloist.
   Another premiere, ``Danbury Mix,'' to music by Charles Ives, was
the second premiere ballet of the evening in the New York State
Theater. Paul Taylor choreographed it for the 18 members of his
company and they performed it. One New York City Ballet dancer,
Peter Frame, had a jolly solo to Ives' ``Circus Band March.''
   In ``Danbury Mix,'' Taylor seems to have organized his own
version of chaos. There is much tumbling, rolling and crawling
about on the floor, grotesque, spastic and insect-like moves,
diving as though into water, to land on the hands and then flip
over, deliberate bumping into other dancers. Some of it surely is
satire.
   Applause indicated the audience liked ``Danbury Mix'' a lot. We
weren't thrilled by it, but the Taylor dancers performed the
composition with amazing energy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
