<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     05-13 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Takes On Dukakis As He Campaigns In California</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: First event at 1 p.m. EDT; may stand for PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush is painting Democratic
front-runner Michael Dukakis as ``an extremely liberal Democrat''
who is far to the left on military matters _ a portrait the vice
president hopes will help him win the West in November.
   At a high-tech defense plant in New Mexico and in
military-minded San Diego, Bush hit the Massachusetts governor on
defense, saying Dukakis would cause ``a radical swing'' in the
nation's military policies.
   Bush, the apparent Republican nominee, also tried to draw
attention away from a minor flap over President Reagan's
endorsement of his bid. Reagan's formal expression of support,
delivered Wednesday night, was judged lukewarm by some.
   ``This is what I call a piranha circling in the water over what
they think is a drop of blood. They're going to starve to death
because there is nothing there, nothing there,'' the vice president
said in Albuquerque, N.M. ``It's totally absurd.''
   By the end of the day, Bush was downplaying the endorsement from
the man he has loyally served for seven years.
   ``People thought all along the president was for me. So I don't
think the specific endorsment means something,'' Bush said. ``But I
think the Reagan record, or the Reagan-Bush record if you will, is
well-regarded. ''
   On a seven-day Western swing to states where he needs strong
support to win the general election, Bush talked as if the fall
campaign had already begun. Over and over again, he referred to
Dukakis and his remaining Democratic opponent Jesse Jackson as
extreme on defense.
   ``We are going to have a traditional campaign...of one extremely
liberal Democrat...against me,'' Bush told reporters in San Diego.
   He planned another high-tech plant visit and a San Diego air
show appearence today.
   Later Bush described Dukakis as ``over there somewhere _ and I'm
not just making charges _ between McGovern and Mondale, somewhere
there on defense.''
   George McGovern, the party's 1972 nominee, called for dramatic
cuts in defense spending, while Walter Mondale, the 1984 Democrtic
standard-bearer, opposed some Reagan military programs.
   In speeches in New Mexico and California, Bush aimed at
Democratic defense policies.
   ``We cannot afford a radical swing. We cannot afford president
who opposes every step we are taking to keep our defense at the
technological edge, who opposes the MX, who opposes the Midgetman,
who opposes testing of nuclear weapons, who opposes flight testing
of ballistic missiles, who opposes testing of anti-satellite
weapons, who opposes the building of a strategic defense, and who
flirts with the withdrawal of our troops from South Korea,'' he
told the Albuquerque Rotary Club after a defense-plant tour.
   At one point, Bush joked about the endorsement flap.
   ``You may have seen that the president endorsed me last night.
That was a relief,'' he said as the Rotary Club audience laughed.
``It's been tough for me trying to keep my charisma in check for
seven years.''
   Talking to reporters, Bush said Reagan's endorsement was ``just
great...I couldn't have been more pleased.''
   The White House, responding to reports describing the
endorsement as lukewarm, put out a follow-up statement on Thursday.
   ``I am enthusiastic....George has been a partner in all we have
accomplished and he should be elected. He has my full confidence
and my total support,'' Reagan said in the statement.
   On another topic, Bush refused to answer questions about a
reports of a U.S. offer to Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio
Noreiga that would involve dropping American drug trafficking
charges in exchange for Noriega's stepping down from power.
   ``I favor getting Noriega out,'' Bush told reporters as he
toured a Honeywell Defense Avionics plant in Albuquerque. ``I've
learned something from some experience in this _ when negotiations
are going on that are sensitive, you don't discuss them.''
</TEXT>
