<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Kissinger     05-13 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Kissinger,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veterinarian Fails To Save Kissinger's Dog</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veterinarian who treated Henry
Kissinger's dog for cancer says he was impressed with the devotion
that the former secretary of state showed to the dying animal.
   ``I was expecting Kissinger to be a little intimidating,
considering his stature in the world, But he was just a regular guy
who loved his dog,'' said Gregory MacEwen, a University of
Wisconsin veterinarian.
   MacEwen met Kissinger last month for a few hours when MacEwen
flew to New York to treat Kissinger's ailing yellow Labrador
retriever for cancer. The dog died last week, MacEwen said.
   ``He got right down on the floor with his dog in his three-piece
suit, talking to him, totally flat out, just telling Tyler (the
dog) how much he loved him,'' MacEwen said.
   The dog suffered from a form of bone cancer that spread to the
dog's spine and paralyzed it.
   MacEwen said an innovative liposome cancer treatment, which uses
the body's own immune system to attack the cancer, may have worked
had the disease not progressed to the spine.
   However, the dog lived out its life in less pain, he said.
   Kissinger went to the National Cancer Institute after learning
the dog had cancer. Kissinger wanted to avoid chemotherapy because
of the dog's ill health and age, MacEwen said.
   A former NCI official recommended that Kissinger contact MacEwen.
</TEXT>
