<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     05-13 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Price Drops Push Soviets Toward Barter Deals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department marketing expert
says the drop in world oil and gold prices in recent years has had
``a dramatic effect'' on the Soviet Union's trade with the United
States.
   As a consequence, the Soviet Union would much prefer having
barter arrangements with foreign trading partners instead of having
to spend its short supply of foreign currency for imports, such as
huge orders of U.S. wheat and corn.
   ``Foreign currency is tight for the Soviet government, which in
turn has decreased the Soviet Union's buying power significantly,''
said Thomas Hamby of the department's Foreign Agricultural Service.
   Hamby, now the agency's deputy director of marketing for dairy,
livestock and poultry, recently returned from Moscow after two and
a half years as U.S. agricultural attache. His remarks were
included Thursday in the June issue of the agency's Foreign
Agriculture magazine.
   Trade talks between Moscow and other countries are increasingly
turning into barter negotiations, he said. The Soviets make it
plain they are in a better position to exchange their products for
foreign goods than to pay in foreign currency.
   ``This is a difficult constraint on trade from the U.S.
standpoint,'' Hamby said. The Soviet Union simply does not have the
ability to supply the quantity or quality of either agricultural or
non-agricultural products which would make a barter arrangement
feasible.''
   Hamby said the United States imports only about $25 million
worth of Soviet agricultural products each year, while the Soviet
Union's imports of U.S. farm products averages around $2 billion
annually.
   ``This situation has led to continuing Soviet pressure to lift
U.S. import restrictions on Soviet furskins and other commodities,
and pressure for most-favored-nation (MFN) trade status, which
would give the Soviet Union preferential access to the U.S.
market,'' he said.
   Under the MFN principle, the United States would grant the
Soviet Union the same trading privileges that it offers most other
foreign trading partners. The MFN designation for the Soviet Union
has been held up for years because of Moscow's restrictive
emigration policies.
   These issues are likely to persist in any trade negotiation
between the Soviet Union and the United States, Hamby said.
Currently, negotiators are working on a successor to the five-year
grain agreement between the Soviet Union and the United States.
   That pact, which will expire on Sept. 30, commits the Soviet
Union to buy minimum quantities of U.S. wheat and corn each year.
   ``The Soviets' foreign currency deficit also has led to
trade-offs in what is imported,'' Hamby said. ``Agricultural
commodity imports have increasingly faced competing demands for
high-priority technology such as plant and equipment among Soviet
planners.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some new procedures have been designed by the
Agriculture Department to regulate the inspection of imported meat
and poultry, including the permanent marking of shipments that fail
to meet U.S. standards.
   Each consignment that fails to pass U.S. inspection would be
stamped ``U.S. Refused Entry'' on each carcass or packing
container, Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's
Food Safety and Inspection Service, said Thursday.
   ``This will help ensure that rejected meat and poultry does not
get into the human food supply in the United States,'' he said.
``It will also warn other countries where the products might be
subsequently shipped that the U.S. has rejected the items.''
   Products that are refused entry must be removed from the United
States, converted to animal food or destroyed. Previously, such
products were identified with temporary placards and had to be
closely monitored by USDA employees.
   The new regulation, which takes effect June 12, also will
eliminate a requirement that products refused entry be sealed
before being transported in the United States, since the permanent
markings will serve to identify them.
   Crawford said the new rule also reinstates the practice of
``controlled pre-stamping'' in which import inspectors can put
their ``passed'' mark on containers of imported products before the
inspection has been fully carried out.
   This procedure is especially useful at cold storage facilities,
so that meat and poultry can be stamped and samples taken for
testing and inspection. If there are no problems, the products
don't have to be handled again, he said. If the products fail
inspection, inspectors can remove the marks and stamp the products
indelibly as refused.
   In a related action, the agency announced a proposal to allow
imported meat and poultry to be inspected only at the port where
the products are unloaded. Currently, the products can be shipped
across the country to another port for checking by USDA inspectors.
   Crawford said the proposal, which will be open for public
comment until July 12, would give federal inspectors ``much better
control of imported products entering food channels'' in the United
States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
