<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Prices     05-13 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Prices,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Food Prices In State Stores Raised Up To 60 Percent In Beijing,
Shanghai</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for pork, eggs and other non-staple foods
are rising by up to 60 percent in state-owned stores in Beijing and
Shanghai as part of government efforts to phase out subsidies,
official reports say.
   Food bills of urban shoppers already have climbed sharply in the
past few years due to growing demand and stagnating grain and pig
production.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Thursday that state stores
in Shanghai this week increased the price of pork 60 percent and of
eggs 30 percent.
   A separate Xinhua report said prices for pork, eggs, vegetables
and sugar in state stores in Beijing would be raised by 30 percent
to 60 percent as of Sunday. It did not detail the increases for
each item.
   Pork has sold for about 50 cents a pound in state stores in
Beijing. Eggs have cost about 25 cents a pound.
   Both cost more on the unsubsidized free market.
   The average urban worker earns about $27 a month.
   Beijing and Shanghai soon will begin distributing monthly
subsidies to compensate for the price increases. Xinhua said in
Beijing the subsidies will be $2.16 for college students and $2.70
for workers and retirees.
   Xinhua said the increases in Beijing are expected to add $1.76
each month to the average person's food bill.
   Overall, retail prices rose 11 percent nationwide in this year's
first quarter, but official reports have said vegetable prices in
free markets have increased up to 40 percent in some cities over
the past year.
   For years, the government suppressed inflation by fixing prices
for goods and subsidizing the difference between the production
cost and retail price.
   As part of its decade-long program of reducing central planning
and increasing the role of market forces, the government has
reduced the number of items sold at fixed prices and raised prices
still under state control.
   The State Administration for Commodity Prices said last week
that the government eventually plans to stop setting prices
altogether for pork, eggs, vegetables and sugar.
   Premier Li Peng, who has advocated moving gradually to
rationalize prices, was quoted by Xinhua Thursday as telling a
meeting of mayors from 10 cities that each should move toward
letting the free market set prices.
</TEXT>
