<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Liberals     05-13 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Liberals,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liberal Party Leader David Steel Steps Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALASHIELS, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Steel, leader of Britain's
centrist Liberal Party for 12 years, has announced that he will not
be a candidate to lead the newly merged Social and Liberal
Democrats.
   Steel, 50, on Thursday told party workers at Galashiels in his
Scottish electoral district: ``Those who have urged me to stay
should not feel let down.''
   The new party, formed through a merger this year of the Labor
and Social Democratic parties, is to elect its leaders in July.
   Steel said his leadership was the longest in the history of the
150-year-old Liberal Party except for Herbert H. Asquith, who led
it for 18 years until 1926 and was prime minister from 1908-1916.
   He said he intends to remain a legislator in the House of
Commons.
   The Liberals formed an electoral alliance in 1981 with people
who broke away from the Labor Party and formed the Social
Democratic Party, claiming Labor was moving too far to the left.
   Steel was joint leader of the alliance with Social Democratic
leader David Owen, a former Labor foreign secretary.
   Members of the two parties decided by majority votes to merge
after failing in their aim to supplant Labor as the main opposition
to the governing Conservatives. They won just 22 of the 630 House
of Commons seats in the June 1987 general election.
   Owen opposed the merger decision and has relaunched a new Social
Democratic Party under his own leadership.
</TEXT>
