<HEAD>Guerrillas Free West German Diplomat, Colombian Politician</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARRANCABERMEJA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas freed a West
German diplomat and a Colombian politician, the last of 16 people
they had kidnapped in a propaganda move.
   Siegfried Markert, 59, honorary West German consul in
Bucaramanga, and Dario Parra, the council president of Santander
state, were released unharmed in the cemetery of this eastern port
city on Thursday, police said.
   The two had been held for 10 days.
   The pro-Cuban National Liberation Army kidnapped Markert, Parra
and 14 other people over a three-day period in what it called a
``sovereignty and dignity'' operation. None of the captives was
harmed.
   Markert said he was well treated.
   Parra said the guerrillas talked to them about nationalizing the
oil fields ``to avoid the plundering of Colombian national riches
by foreign companies.''
   President Virgilio Barco called the guerrilla operation
``worthless propaganda.''
