<HEAD>Two Robbery Suspects Hold Policeman Hostage; Demand Drugs for His
Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two robbery suspects holding a police
officer hostage Thursday night demanded drugs in exchange for the
officer's life, authorities said.
   The hostage told his fellow officers that the pair are desperate
and will kill him unless they are provided with the drugs, said
Henry Groepper, spokesman for the Portland Police Bureau.
   Groepper said the officer, whose name was not immediately
released, was a veteran who was handling the situation ``real
well'' under the circumstances.
   A hostage negotiation team was in place and the officer was
acting as an intermediary over the telephone and a police radio,
Groepper said. He said the gunmen were asking for Dilaudit, a form
of morphine used in cough syrup.
   The officer was taken hostage while he was investigating a
robbery that occurred about 7 p.m. at a Safeway store in the
southwest part of the city.
   The officer checked a tip that two suspicious men were staying
at the nearby Portland Rose Motel and he went to their room, where
he was admitted by one man, Groepper said.
   Other officers brought witnesses from the grocery robbery who
identified the man as a suspect. As the officers were handcuffing
the suspect, another man emerged from the bathroom and pointed at
gun at police.
   ``Don't anyone do anything foolish,'' Groepper quoted the man as
saying.
   The gunman took one officer hostage and forced the others out of
the motel room.
   Asked whether police would meet the demands, Groepper said:
``We'll take it as it comes.''
</TEXT>
