<HEAD>Report: SEC Investigating Shopping Center Developer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is
investigating whether shopping center and sports magnate Edward J.
DeBartolo Sr. secretly helped a corporate raider accumulate stock
in companies targeted for takeover, a published report said today.
   The SEC is also trying to determine whether DeBartolo improperly
concealed multimillion-dollar loans to Paul Bilzerian, his
relatives and Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. employees to acquire stock
in takeover targets Hammermill Paper Co. and Cluett Peabody & Co.,
The Washington Post reported.
   Other focuses of the SEC's DeBartolo-Bilzerian probe include
Allied Store Corp., Carter Hawley Hale, H.H. Robertson Co., Armco
Inc. and Fruehauf Corp., the Post said, citing subpoenas and other
documents.
   DeBartolo Corp., based in Youngstown, Ohio, is one of the
nation's leading shopping center developers. In addition to the
shopping centers and other real estate, DeBartolo Corp., owns the
San Francisco 49ers football team and the Pittsburgh Penguins
hockey team.
   The Post said documents related to the DeBartolo investigation
became public in a dispute over the company's production of papers
requested under SEC subpoenas. SEC lawyers went to U.S. District
Court in the District of Columbia to obtain the documents, and a
settlement was reached last week that provides for the records to
be made available to the agency.
   The SEC subpoena seeks information from DeBartolo about certain
stock trading and telephone records between January 1985 through
July 1987, the newspaper said.
   ``The matter is in the hands of our lawyers and we have been
cooperating and will continue to cooperate with the
investigation,'' DeBartolo told the newspaper through his
spokesman, attorney Stephen Flood. A spokesman for Bilzerian
declined to comment.
</TEXT>
