<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YouthSuicide Bjt   05-13 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Youth Suicide, Bjt,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Depressed Youths Predisposed To Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery of chemical abnormalities in
depressed teen-agers intent on killing themselves could provide a
better understanding of suicide and help identify those likely to
self-destruct, researchers say.
   ``The things we learn on this may well help future tests to
identify the highest risk for suicides, and that can make a
difference in the treatment,'' said Dr. Neal D. Ryan, assistant
professor of psychiatry at the University of Pittsburgh.
   The brains of suicidal adolescents secrete smaller amounts of a
growth hormone than those of healthy teen-agers, according to
research by Ryan and Dr. Joaquin Puig-Antich, professor of
psychiatry at Pitt.
   The study, reported Thursday at the American Psychiatric
Association's annual meeting in Montreal, is believed to be the
first to demonstrate neurochemical abnormalities in suicidal
adolescents.
   ``It's not purely a mind phenomenon,'' Ryan said. ``There's
something that goes on with the brain, and there are environmental
phenomena that impinge on that.''
   Earlier studies have found similar abnormalities in the brains
of suicidal adults, although experts are divided as to what
conclusions can be drawn.
   ``Nothing has worked out as a diagnostic tool,'' said Irma Lann,
a science administrator in child and adolescent disorders research
for the National Institute of Mental Health.
   Ms. Lann called the researchers' work interesting but
preliminary, and said further study is needed.
   ``We've made a big step toward understanding, identifying, the
risk for suicide. But we're not there yet,'' said Dr. David Brent,
a University of Pittsburgh psychiatrist who specializes in
adolescent suicide.
   Youths 19 and under accounted for 2,127 of the 29,453 suicides
committed in the United States in 1985, the last year for which
figures are available, according to the National Center for Health
Statistics. About 80 percent of them were boys.
   Boys and girls are afflicted about equally by depression, one of
the main forces behind suicide. More girls attempt suicide, but
more boys succeed at it, Ryan said.
   However, therapists may be mistaken in treating suicidal
teen-agers much the same as depressed adolescents, Puig-Antich said.
   ``What it (study) points out is that the biology of suicide may
be different than the biology of depression,'' he said. ``If so,
there may be treatment for suicidal depressives that is different
than treatment of patients with depression.''
   From 1980 to 1987, Puig-Antich and Ryan monitored the growth
hormone secretion of 140 carefully selected adolescents ranging in
age from 12 to just under 18. The tests were conducted while the
subjects slept.
   Most growth hormone secretion occurs during sleep, especially
during the first several hours, Ryan said. At least three
neurotransmitter systems in the brain are involved in controlling
sleep growth hormone secretion, which also affects moods.
   Thirty-four youngsters who suffered from major depression and
had attempted suicide or devised a suicide plan secreted less
growth hormone than 40 depressed but non-suicidal students and 66
healthy children, whose levels were about the same, Ryan said. The
subjects' sex was not a factor.
   Later, 43 students were given a shot of Desipramine, an
antidepressant known to stimulate the release of growth hormone.
   Eight depressed, suicidal youths who received the shot had less
growth hormone released than the 12 depressed but non-suicidal
students and 23 healthy adolescents, Ryan said.
   Puig-Antich said the research ``definitely can help in
prevention, especially if we can know ahead of time who are at the
greatest risk.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880513-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Airlines-Fines     05-13 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airlines-Fines,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Proposes $6.5 Million in Fines Against 15 Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $1.26 million fine against United Airlines
is among the nearly $6.5 million in penalties the Federal Aviation
Administration says it wants to impose on airlines for alleged
safety and security violations.
   Fifteen of the nation's airlines face the penalities, which have
been proposed in letters from the FAA. If an airline can show a
charge is unfounded, the fine can be reduced.
   Chicago-based United is targeted for the biggest fine. The next
highest proposed fine is against Hawaiian Airlines, $1.17 million,
followed by Continental, $982,130; Eastern Airlines, $893,500;
Braniff, $518,000; American Airlines, $421,250; and Northwest
Airlines, $371,000.
   The other airlines listed in the FAA's documents and the
proposed fines are: Pan Am, $264,500; USAir, $166,100; Delta,
$147,250; Midway, $128,000; TWA, $118,000; Southwest, $56,500;
America West, $1,500; and Alaska, $1,000.
   According to the FAA, $705,850 of the fine pending against
United was imposed after the airline removed vapor-seal covers from
the wings of its 19-plane fleet of 767s for about a month. The
covers, the agency said in its letter to United, are supposed to
vent leaked fuel from the wing. Without them, the FAA said, there
is a risk of fire.
   A spokesman for United, Dan Sheehy, said it was too soon to
discuss the proposed penalties publicly because ``they are
currently being discussed between United and the FAA. It really
would be inappropriate to comment further.''
   The FAA said a major part of Hawaiian's proposed fine was
prompted by the airline's alleged delay in replacing a damaged
sleeve on a DC-9's wheel and brake assembly. A spokesman for
Hawaiian could not be reached immediately for comment.
   Continental, meanwhile, faces more than $200,000 in proposed
fines for allegedly failing to comply with several 1987
airworthiness directives requiring inspections of engines and
pressure bulkheads on a leased Boeing 727.
   Bruce Hicks, a spokesman for Continental, said the airline is
seeking to have some of its $982,130 in fines reduced but he didn't
know specifically which fines were being contested.
   ``These are by and large issues that are many months to more
than a year old,'' Hicks said in a telephone interview from
Continental headquarters in Houston. ``Two-thirds of the issues
were actually referred to the FAA by Continental. ... That's the
way the industry is supposed to work.''
   The FAA also proposed fining Braniff for alleged inadequate
surveillance of its inspection and maintenance programs and
American for alleged operating a Boeing 727 despite pilot
complaints that two of the engines weren't accelerating rapidly
enough.
   The FAA made the list of proposed fines available to The Wall
Street Journal and The Washington Post in response to requests. The
agency released the documents to The Associated Press on Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
