<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Guatemala     05-13 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Guatemala,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Legal Action Will Be Taken Against Coup Plotters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Vinicio Cerezo says civilians
were involved in an attempted uprising by dissident army officers
that was quickly quashed and that his government would take legal
action against them.
   ``The situation is completely under control,'' Cerezo said
Thursday in his first public comments on Wednesday's rebellion.
   He refused to identify the civilians or specify what kind of
legal action would be taken against them. But Cerezo did say that
none of the leaders of the country's 14 legally registered
political parties was involved.
   ``For the moment, we can announce that legal action will be
taken in the case ... against those civilians who participated in
the capacity of intellectual planners in the rash attempt,'' he
said.
   Cerezo made his comments during a visit to the Finance Ministry.
   Troops arrested two army officers Wednesday morning who were
leading soldiers toward the capital, Defense Minister Gen. Hector
Alejandro Gramajo Morales said Wednesday.
   He said the two had led officers and soldiers from bases in
Jutiapa, 75 miles south of Guatemala City, and Retalhuleu, 115
miles southwest of the capital.
   The government has not said how many mutineers were involved or
whether there was any violence or injury.
   Gramajo Morales said those involved were fooled by ``speculation
and disinformation'' propagated by civilians, whom he did not
identify.
   Col. Arturo Getella, commander of the Jutiapa base, on Thursday
identified one ringleader as Col. Gustavo Cifuentes, a subcommander
of the same facility.
   The afternoon daily La Hora, citing confidential sources,
identified the uprising's other leaders as Col. Gustavo Adolfo
Padilla, subcommander of the Retalhuleu base, and Manuel Maria
Gordillo Martinez.
   It did not specify Gordillo Martinez's rank or where he was
based.
   The newspaper said Gordillo Martinez is the brother of retired
Col. Francisco Luis Gordillo Martinez, who with Gen. Horacio
Maldonado Schadd and Gen. Efrain Rios Montt formed a military junta
after a coup in March 1982 that overthrew the government of Gen.
Fernando Romeo Lucas Garcia.
   Cerezo, a lawyer and leader of the Christian Democratic Party,
won the presidency in November 1985 in the first election in 16
years in which the military did not field a candidate.
   He succeeded Gen. Oscar Humberto Mejia Victores, who seized
power in August 1983 from Rios Montt.
</TEXT>
