<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0413EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0443 05-13 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0443,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Criticizes Administration On Noriega</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS two grafs after 5th, ``I don't...'' to update with
Oregon appearance; picks up 7th pvs, As he...; no events before
noon EDT; lead prospects uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner
Michael Dukakis is criticizing the administration's reported deal
to dismiss charges against Panama's military leader, saying ``I
don't believe you drop indictments against suspected drug runners
and murderers.''
   Dukakis was beginning his first full day of West Coast
campaigning today with events across California after stopping
briefly in Portland Thursday night. Tuesday's contest in Oregon is
a prelude to his final round of primaries against Jesse Jackson on
June 7 in California and New Jersey.
   Holding a long lead in delegates going into the final few
primaries, Dukakis continued to focus on the Reagan administration
as he reacted to reports the administration had offered to drop
federal drug-trafficking charges against Panama's Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega if he would step down as the country's leader.
   ``I think before we start talking about dropping indictments and
making deals, the American people deserve a full explanation of
what kind of relationship this administration has had with
Noriega,'' Dukakis said.
   ``I don't believe you drop indictments against suspected drug
runners and murderers,'' Dukakis said earlier before arriving in
Oregon.
   Dukakis continued the criticism during his brief stop in
Portland. He also jabbed at Reagan over recent disclosures that the
president's schedule has been guided through the use of astrology
by his wife, Nancy.
   ``Eight months from now, the Reagan era will be over,'' Dukakis
said at a mock political convention by Oregon high school students.
``America will have a new president. We'll be putting away our
horoscopes.''
   As he increasingly turns his criticism on the Republicans and
their expected nominee, Vice President George Bush, Dukakis has
made a common theme of challenging the administration for dealing
quietly with the Panamanian strongman.
   Bush, Democrats contend, should have had knowledge of Noriega
going back to the vice president's days as head of the CIA, and
more recently as head of an administration task force to stop
illegal drug smuggling.
   Noriega and U.S. officials have been negotiating in recent
months to solve the problem posed by his continued position of
power in the face of U.S. indictments alleging deep involvement in
large-scale drug operations.
   Noriega's continuing presence has been regarded as an
embarrassment for the administration and a political problem for
Bush.
   ``The administration got into this soup. It isn't going well,
and it looks to me as if they're desperate to get out of it,''
Dukakis said.
   Dukakis made the comments as he devoted much of the day to
making the rounds of Democratic congressional leaders in Washington
_ sessions in keeping with his role as likely party nominee and
aimed at assuring Capitol Hill Democrats he wants to cooperate.
   In the process he picked up the endorsement of Senate Majority
Leader Robert Byrd. Dukakis overwhelmingly won this week's
presidential primary in West Virginia, Byrd's home state. He was
also endorsed by House Ways and Means Chairman Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill.
   Byrd said Dukakis had run a positive campaign that would help
the party unite. He said it was time for Democrats to gather around
the Massachusetts governor as its standard bearer for the fall.
   ``He has not dipped into the trough and gone negative,'' Byrd
said. ``We need to begin to close ranks, and that's what we're
doing today.''
   Dukakis also met with House Speaker Jim Wright, who refused to
answer when asked if he was endorsing the governor. When asked,
Wright responded in Spanish with what amounted to a no comment.
   Dukakis also met with House Majority Leader Tom Foley, D-Wash.,
who also withheld an endorsement. When asked about Foley as a
running mate, Dukakis smiled and turned to him with the same
question he once put to Jackson when they shared a stage and the
same question arose: ``Are you interested in it?''
   Foley smiled but made no audible reply.
</TEXT>
