<1ST_LINE>r w PM-StarWarsContract     05-13 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Star Wars Contract,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Electric Selected To Oversee Star Wars Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. has become the Pentagon's
prime design contractor for an initial Star Wars missile defense
system, receiving a $235.9 million contract for five years of
research.
   The award, announced Thursday, is one of the largest Star Wars
contracts to date. Under the contract, GE's Aerospace Division in
Philadelphia will oversee research work on the five key
technologies now being considered for a Star Wars system.
   The award capped a five-month competition that pitted GE against
General Dynamics Corp. The competition was limited to companies
that were not working as prime contractors on the five technologies
identified for an initial Star Wars system.
   Both GE and General Dynamics were judged technically competent
to perform the work, but GE had a lower bid, the Pentagon indicated.
   The Star Wars program, known formally as the Strategic Defense
Initiative, is an effort to develop lasers and other exotic weapons
that could be deployed in space and on the ground to automatically
shoot down nuclear missiles fired at the United States or its
allies.
   Last September, then-Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger
selected five technologies for accelerated research, saying they
would form the core of any initial Star Wars system if proven
feasible.
   They consist of two different types of satellite surveillance
and tracking systems; two different ``interception,'' or rocket
weapon, systems; and a battle management-command, control and
communications system _ the computer ``brains'' of any Star Wars
defense.
   GE will be expected to coordinate the work being done on those
five projects. For example, it would set the performance standards
for each component in order to satisfy ``the military requirement
to intercept a certain percentage of targets,'' the Pentagon said.
   GE also will play a particularly crucial role in the work on the
battle management system because it will be asked to ``design the
functions to assist in the selection of algorithms, network
concepts, (computer) processors and software,'' the Pentagon added.
   GE already has assembled a team of subcontractors to assist in
the work and will establish a ``systems engineering and
integration'' office in northern Virginia near the Pentagon, the
Defense Department said.
   The subcontractors include the Science Applications
International Corp. of McLean, Va,.; AT&T Federal Systems Division
in Greensboro, N.C.; the Nichols Research Corp. of Huntsville,
Ala.; the McDonnell Douglas Astronautics Co. of Huntington Beach,
Calif., and the Computer Science Corp.'s Defense Systems Division
in Moorestown, N.J.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
