<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FlakeAllegation 1stLd-Writethru a0424 05-13 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flake Allegation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0424,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Facing Church Judgment on Sexual Misconduct Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 7-10 to Insert dropped material and add comment
from Scott, picks up pvs 10th graf bgng ``The Rev. ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Floyd Flake of New York says he will
defend himself against a complaint filed with his church that he
sexually harassed a female employee of his congregation before he
was elected to Congress.
   The woman's allegations are being considered by a judiciary
committee of the African Methodist Episcopal Church in Buffalo,
N.Y., and a decision could be reached by Sunday, said Flake
spokesman Edwin Reed.
   He said the woman claims that Flake, a first-term New York
Democrat who is also a pastor in the church, fired her from an
administrative assistant job at his 4,000-member Allen A.M.E.
Church in Queens, N.Y., after an affair between the couple ended.
   ``She alleges that they had an affair and when it was over, she
was forced out,'' Reed said in a telephone interview from Buffalo,
where the regional A.M.E. Church is holding its annual meeting.
   Reed said the woman was fired in 1985 before Flake was elected
to Congress, ``but not for those reasons. She was fired because of
her inability to be compatible with the whole staff.''
   Flake was busy at the meeting and not immediately available for
comment, Reed said. But in an interview with The New York Post,
Flake identified the woman as Thelma Singleton-Scott and said she
was trying to blackmail him.
   ``She asked me for money to keep quiet about this,'' said Flake.
``I'm prepared to defend myself against the charges that she
brings.''
   Mrs. Singleton-Scott, who lives in Brooklyn, told The New York
Times Thursday from her Buffalo hotel room that she decided to
disclose the affair only after Flake ``defamed my name and told
church members to stay away from me and removed me from the church
rolls.''
   ``I want him removed from the pulpit,'' she said. ``He committed
adultery.''
   Ms. Singleton-Scott said the affair began shortly after she
started work at the church in 1983 and ended in 1984, according to
the Times.
   The Rev. John Collier, a spokesman for A.M.E. Bishop Frank
Cummings, told the Post that a statement on the allegations will be
issued in a few days.
   Flake, 43, was elected in November 1986. He is married and has
four children.
</TEXT>
