<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   05-13 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld - Writethru,f0263,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Post Big Gain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished the week higher Friday in
dealings against the Japanese yen, while stock prices posted a
strong gain.
   The dollar closed at 124.70 yen, up 0.31 yen from Thursday's
finish. It had opened the day higher at 124.60 yen, and moved
between 124.55 and 124.73 yen.
   Traders said the dollar was moving higher in anticipation of a
slight decline in Japan's trade surplus.
   ``Market participants are also paying attention to U.S. trade
figures for March,'' said a dealer with a major commercial bank,
who spoke on condition of anonymity. The U.S. figures are to be
released next Tuesday in Washington.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which won 51.53 points Thursday, gained another
255.73 points, or 0.93 percent, to end the week's session at
27,468.31.
   A brokerage official, who also reguested anonymity, said share
prices rose almost across the board in early trading, as the market
continued on its bullish trend extending over from Thursday.
   The official said a good overnight showing on Wall Street, in
the wake of recent declines, and good results from the refunding
auction of U.S. Treasury bonds in the United States made investors
confident about market prospects.
</TEXT>
