<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-BuildingCollapse 4thLd-Writethru   05-13 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Building Collapse, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0485,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Building Collapses; 12 Dead, 45 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic NY17, locator map.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with report of 12 dead, 45
injured. PICKS up 6th graf pvs bgng, Cardenas said Red ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AGUASCALIENTES, MEXICO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top four floors of a building
under construction collapsed Thursday, burying the basement offices
of a furniture factory. At least 12 people were reported dead and
45 injured.
   Rescue crews used specially-trained search dogs and tunnelling
equipment early Friday to locate survivors trapped under tons of
concrete, said Commander Marco Cerilla, chief of the Aguascalientes
police department.
   He said personnel from the Mexican army, national Red Cross
headquarters and federal Public Security department arrived to
coordinate the search effort.
   Cerilla said police did not know how many people remained buried
under the rubble.
   Esperanza Cardenas, a spokeswoman for the Mexican Red Cross in
Aguascalientes, said early Friday that nine people had been
confirmed dead and 40 injured.
   Juan Manuel Hinojo, a reporter for the Aguascalientes daily El
Heraldo, later told The Associated Press that officials at the site
said there were 12 dead and 45 were rescued, all of who were
injured. He said at least five more people were still unaccounted
for, based on survivors' knowledge of who was in building at the
time.
   Cardenas said authorities did not know how many people had been
in the structure when it collapsed at about 5 p.m. Thursday (7 p.m.
EDT).
   Cardenas said Red Cross workers believed about 40 people had
been rescued alive from the building and all were taken to local
medical facilities because of injuries. Their conditions were not
immediately known.
   ``Exactly how many there are or how many more are inside the
building isn't known,'' she said.
   One of the dead was an unidentified boy about 10 years old,
Cardenas said.
   She said construction workers and employees of the Romo
furniture factory, located in the basement of the building, were in
the building when it plummeted.
   Aguascalientes, capital of Aguascalientes state, is about 320
miles northwest of Mexico City.
   The cause of the collapse was not immediately known.
   Jorge Alberto Castaneda Alvarado, head of the Aguascalientes
Civil Engineers Association, announced early Friday the formation
of a committee of engineers and architects to investigate the
collapse.
</TEXT>
