<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-13 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar strengthened against the Japanese
yen in Tokyo today, while stock prices rose substantially following
an overnight rally on Wall Street.
   After opening the day at 124.60 yen, up 0.21 yen from Thursday's
finish, the dollar edged up slightly to end the week's trading at
124.70 yen, up 0.31 yen.
   ``The dollar was already high at the start of trading, following
its firm finish on overseas markets,'' said a dealer at a major
commercial bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   There was some speculative dollar-buying prompted by the
announcement that Japan's trade surplus for April had decreased for
the 12th-consecutive month, but the market was relatively quiet and
the dollar moved in a narrow range of 124.55-124.73 yen, he said.
   Japan posted a trade surplus of $6.746 billion in April, falling
from $7.535 billion a year earlier and $7.459 billion in the
previous month, the Finance Ministry said today.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which rose 51.53 points Thursday, gained another
255.73 points, or 0.93 percent, in active trading to close the week
at 27,468.31.
   Share prices rose almost across the board during early trading,
helped by an overnight rally on Wall Street and news reports
indicating a success in Thursday's refunding auction of 30-year
bonds by the U.S. Treasury, traders said.
   Nihon Keizai Shimbun reported today that Japan bought about half
the bonds auctioned in the United States late Thursday.
   ``Investors were also encouraged by the market strength shown
Thursday, when it bounced back promptly from an early plunge of
about 200 points,'' said a brokerage official, who spoke
anonymously.
   Popular issues included machineries, steels and electricals.
Automobiles, constructions and housings were also higher. Among the
losers were some foodstuffs.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.1 billion shares,
up from 900 million shares Thursday.
</TEXT>
