<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     05-13 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Intelligence Committee Approves Notification Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Intelligence Committee has approved
a bill that would require the president to notify Congress within
48 hours when he authorizes any covert action by U.S. agencies and
officials.
   The legislation was prompted by the recommendations of the
congressional panels that investigated the Iran-Contra affair when
it was revealed that Congress had not been informed until 10 months
after President Reagan had approved a secret arms-for-hostages swap.
   The committee annnounced Thursday that it had approved the
legislation by an 11-to-6 party-line vote.
   It is similar to a covert-action measure passed March 15 by the
Senate on a vote of 71 to 19.
   Under the current bill, a covert action is any U.S. activity,
other than traditional military, diplomatic and law enforcement
actions, designed ``to influence political, economic or military
conditions abroad so that the role of the United States government
is not intended to be apparent or acknowledged publicly...''
   The bill, which requires the president to give prior written
notice of any but emergency covert action, now goes to the full
House for a vote.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Votes To Make Itself More Immune To Civil Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has unanimously approved a
resolution to help protect its members from civil lawsuits in
connection with news releases, new conferences and communication
between government officials.
   The 413-0 vote on Thursday was triggered by a federal appeals
court decision that limited lawmakers' immunity to activities such
as speaking and voting on the House or Senate floor as granted by
the Constitution's speech and debate clause.
   The resolution asks that the Supreme Court hear an appeal of the
case to consider a broader interpretation of immunity.
   The court made its decision in a case involving Rep. Don
Sundquist, R-Tenn. and the Menphis Area Legal Services Corp.
   Sundquist made a reference to a staff attorney letters he wrote
to the attorney general and the president of the corporation about
a controversy regarding expenditure of federal money by the office.
   Sundquist later released the letter to the news media and the
attorney sued for defamation of character.
   The case originally was dismissed in U.S. district court but
that ruling was reversed by the appeals court. Sundquist then
appealed to the Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Appropriations Subcommittee Cuts NASA Budget By $780 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House appropriations subcommittee has cut
more than $780 million out of the NASA budget and agency officials
said the reduction could seriously affect the civil space program.
   The Appropriations Committee's subcommittee on housing and urban
development and independent agencies approved a total budget for
the space agency for fiscal year 1989 of $10.706 billion. NASA had
asked for $11.488 billion.
   One of the largest cuts came in NASA's request for the
struggling space shuttle program. It was reduced by more than $200
million.
   ``Something will have to be cut. There's nothing left. If they
do make these cuts, some serious things will happen to the civil
space program,'' said shuttle astronaut Jon McBride.
   The space shuttle has been grounded since January 1986 when the
explosion of the Challenger shuttle killed seven crew members. The
winged spacecraft fleet is scheduled to resume flights in August.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Near East, South Asia Are World's Largest Arms Markets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional study says the Near East and
South Asia are the Third World's largest arms importers, and the
Soviet Union is their biggest single supplier.
   The Congressional Research Service report, released Thursday,
found that the United States ranks second among the world's 11
major arms suppliers to the Third World.
   France, Britain and China rounded off the top five arms
merchants to the Third World. The 70-page study by defense analyst
Richard F. Grimmett said the Beijing government committed 79
percent of its arms exports to Iran and Iraq from 1984 to 1987, the
period covered by the report.
   The rest of the list of the top 11 are Italy, West Germany,
Czechoslovakia, Spain, Brazil and South Korea.
</TEXT>
