<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Education     05-13 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Education,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Educators, CDC Convene Conference On AIDS and School-Age Youth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS-Worldwide, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former school superintendent who has AIDS was
scheduled as the keynote speaker tonight at a major conference on
how to stop the spread of the fatal disease among school-age youth.
   ``I know there will be no cure for AIDS in my lifetime,'' John
W. Washburn Jr., 48, said in pre-conference remarks released
Thursday. `The only vaccine we have now is education.''
   Public health officials and more than 100 educators from across
the country were expected to attend the three-day conference
sponsored by the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and the National
Education Association.
   The conference is part of what NEA President Mary Hatwood
Futrell has called the teacher group's ``all-out war against AIDS.''
   Washburn, the retired superintendent of the Brighton School
District near Rochester, N.Y., was diagnosed as having AIDS last
spring. He revealed his illness in January, when he embarked on a
series of speeches.
   Conference organizers said Washburn would talk tonight about his
experiences as a person with AIDS and efforts to educate students
and teachers about the disease.
   Other scheduled conference participants include Dr. Gary Noble,
CDC deputy director for AIDS, and other officials and researchers
with the Atlanta-based health agency.
   The NEA and the CDC's parent agency, the Public Health Service,
are members of the Health Information Network, created last year as
part of the AIDS education effort. Last fall, the network
distributed 1.9 million copies of ``Facts About AIDS,'' a handbook
for teachers.
   AIDS has struck 973 U.S. children under 13; 566 have died,
according to the CDC. In all, AIDS has struck more than 61,000
people in the United States, killing more than 34,000 of them so
far.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
