<DOCNO> AP880513-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0549EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ReaganBook     05-13 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan Book,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Book Calls Reagan Highly Intelligent But Passive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new book by a former Reagan aide
describes the president as ``highly intelligent, with a
photographic memory,'' but it also characterizes him as a passive
president who governs like a ``Turkish pasha.''
   ``Ronald Reagan ... had one distinctive personality trait that
was highly unusual, perhaps unique for someone who rose to the high
level of managerial responsibility he attained,'' writes Martin
Anderson, former assistant to the president for policy development.
``He made no demands and gave almost no instructions.
   Anderson's book, ``Revolution,'' is scheduled to be published
May 18. Some advance copies have been distributed.
   The book is generally laudatory of Reagan's presidency, but it
tends to confirm other books, most recently one written by former
Chief of Staff Donald Regan, that describe Reagan as passive.
   ``Essentially, he just responded to whatever was brought to his
attention and said yes or no, or `I'll think about it.' At times he
would just change the subject, (and) maybe tell a funny story,''
writes Anderson, now a senior fellow at Stanford University's
Hoover Institute.
   ``It was something that all those who had worked closely and
intimately with Ronald Reagan knew. But we rarely talked about it
among ourselves and never to outsiders. We kept it a secret.
   ``He is highly intelligent, with a photographic memory,'' says
Anderson, ``He has a gift for absorbing great amounts of diverse
information and is capable of combining various parts of that
information into new, coherent packages and then conveying his
thoughts and ideas clearly and concisely in a way that is
understandable to almost anyone.''
   But Anderson says Reagan made decisions ``like an ancient king
or a Turkish pasha, passively letting his subjects serve him.
Rarely did he ask searching questions and demand to know why
someone had or had not done something.''
   The president was ``very dependent'' on his advisers, Anderson
says. ``And the degree to which he trusted and depended on his
advisers is probably the key to understanding the Iran-Contra
affair that crippled Reagan's presidency.''
   Anderson describes Nancy Reagan as ``highly intelligent, with a
sixth sense for asking insightful, penetrating questions. Above
all, her judgments on public policy issues, political strategy and
personnel were superb,'' he says.
   The book makes no mention of Regan's account that the first lady
consulted with an astrologer on her husband's schedule and other
issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880513-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CyanideTrial     05-13 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyanide Trial,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Juror Admits Involvement in Own Contaminated Product Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the jury that convicted a woman in
the nation's first death-by-product-tampering case has admitted
that she was involved in an earlier product contamination case she
filed against a cracker company.
   Juror Laurel Holliday, who had been the lone holdout for
acquittal until changing her mind on the panel's last vote Monday,
also told the court that she received an anonymous phone call last
week telling her that Stella Nickell failed an FBI polygraph exam.
The information was inadmissible during the trial.
   U.S. District Judge William Dwyer ordered the seven-woman,
five-man jury to return to court today for questioning about
whether they were improperly influenced.
   Mrs. Nickell, 44, of Auburn, was convicted of killing her
husband and a woman with cyanide-laced Extra-Strength Excedrin
capsules in June 1986. She faces possible life imprisonment at a
June 17 sentencing.
   Ms. Holliday, who was retained on the jury with the consent of
defense lawyer Thomas Hillier II, said neither the phone call nor
her previous experience with product contamination influenced her
decision to vote for conviction. She said she was eventually swayed
by what she called a series of discrepancies in Mrs. Nickell's
testimony.
   Dwyer and Hillier declined comment Thursday on the new
disclosures in the case.
   After the verdict, when it became known Ms. Holliday had been
the lone holdout for acquittal, Hillier raised the issue of
possible jury tampering and suggested another juror might have
influenced Ms. Holliday or that she ``contrived'' the anonymous
call to avoid the pressure of being the holdout vote.
   Ms. Holliday denied making the call herself and said she doubted
any other juror would have made it either.
   Court records show Ms. Holliday settled a lawsuit for $500
against Pepperidge Farm Inc. She had said she bit into a Goldfish
cracker that contained an aspirin substitute, ibuprofen.
   There were no witnesses and Pepperidge Farm attorneys questioned
whether the event ever took place.
   Ms. Holliday said she didn't think her lawsuit was important and
``had no bearing on'' the cyanide case, so she didn't reveal it to
the judge or lawyers involved in picking jurors for the cyanide
trial.
   ``I thought it didn't apply,'' she said. ``He (the judge) asked
about product tampering. ... There was no reason to bring it up.''
   She said she regarded the cracker incident as a manufacturing
mishap and said there was no suggestion that it involved product
tampering.
   The episode occurred in July 1986, a month after the two cyanide
deaths.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
