<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PregnantQueen     05-13 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pregnant Queen,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pregnant Girl Crowned High School Queen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pregnant 17-year-old senior was crowned
May Day queen of her high school, but she and 45 other students
were suspended from classes today for protesting limits placed on
her royal duties.
   ``I know there are people out there tonight who feel strongly
against me being up here, and I never thought such a big issue
would be raised about it,'' AnnaMaria DeVries said at her
coronation Thursday night.
   ``Some people are saying that I have no morals, but those people
don't realize I could have taken an easier way out,'' she added.
   The Dayton Junior-Senior High School's student body elected
DeVries queen last month. DeVries, who is single and nearly six
months pregnant, says she plans to marry and keep the baby.
   There were no protests at the ceremony in the school gymnasium
in this farming town of 1,470.
   ``Everything went very well,'' principal Tom Gallagher said.
``She gave a very classy speech.''
   Earlier Thursday, school officials suspended 45 students who
protested limits placed on DeVries' reign because of her pregnancy.
   The May Day queen traditionally visits Dayton Grade School the
day after her coronation. But after receiving complaints this year,
Gallagher canceled the visit.
   ``We got quite a few phone calls from local patrons, parents,
ministers, whatever, just a gamut of different people from the
community that were upset that the school would allow a pregnant
young lady to be elected,'' Gallagher said.
   Parents of grade school students were worried that DeVries'
pregnancy could cause problems by forcing them to answer questions
from children who see her at the grade school's May Day event, he
said.
   ``My stance was, does the grade school need to be put in that
position?'' he said. ``That's their May Day, their fun day. It
could have put a damper on their celebration.''
   Friends of DeVries asked the school board Monday to overturn
Gallagher's decision, but the board unanimously supported the
principal.
   About 75 students from the 330-student high school responded
Wednesday with a campus sit-in that ended when many of the
protesters, including DeVries, left the campus without permission
for a march through town, Gallagher said. Those students were
suspended for one day, effective today.
   DeVries, an honors student who played on the school's softball
and girls' basketball teams, said she initially went along with
Gallagher's decision but changed her mind after talking it over
with friends.
   ``The decision really didn't surprise me. I had already heard
about the complaining,'' she said.
   Matt Yaskovic, a senior and organizer of the protest, said the
school was setting a poor example.
   ``They tell us all the time you're adults and have to act like
one, and they get us with all these kiddy rules,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
