<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-13 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady In Europe, Gold Fractionally Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was steady in early European
trading today with dealers predicting little major movement before
next Tuesday's release of U.S. trade figures for March. Gold prices
were fractionally lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the volume of dollar trading was
very low because many European traders decided to turn Thursday's
Ascencion Day holiday into a four-day weekend.
   Traders expect the March trade deficit to range from $12.5
billion to $13.5 billion. The U.S. trade gap stood at $13.8 billion
in February.
   ``You'd need a deficit at least as low as $12 billion to inspire
any positive move to the dollar,'' said one Milan trader.
   Traders said they didn't attach much importance to today's
report that Japan's trade surplus with the United States shrank to
$4.125 billion in April from $5.129 billion in April 1987.
   ``The (U.S.) deficit with Japan may have improved, but it could
well have worsened with other strong Asian economies like Taiwan or
(South) Korea,'' the Milan trader said.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar rose 0.31 yen to a closing 124.70. Later, in London, it fell
back to 124.52 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates:
   _1.6823 West German marks, up from 1.6813
   _1.3968 Swiss francs, down from 1.3987
   _5.7043 French francs, up from 5.7020
   _1.8864 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8850
   _1,252.75 Italian lire, up from 1,250.50
   _1.2315 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2298
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.8850 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.8823 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $450.20 a troy ounce,
down from $451.50 late Thursday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $451.05.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $451. The Zurich market was closed
Thursday for Ascencion Day.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.61 to close at a bid $451.67.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.56 a troy
ounce, unchanged from late Thursday.
</TEXT>
