<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TransitArrests     05-13 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Transit Arrests,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Transit Police Officers Charged With False Arrests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities have charged two transit
police officers with falsely arresting six men on sexual abuse
charges in subways in an apparent attempt by the officers to
improve their arrest records.
   Officers Mary McDermott, 31, and Alphonse Iannacone, 41, were
charged Thursday with five counts of conspiring to violate the
civil rights of citizens, U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani said.
   The cases of seven other transit officers who also had high
numbers of questionable arrests during the same time period are
under investigation, Giuliani said at a news conference.
   The two officers charged had arrested six black and Hispanic men
in 1983 and 1984 on charges they lewdly rubbed themselves against
women in the subway. However, the ``victims,'' who were mostly
white women, told the officers they were not aware of the men's
actions and were not interested in pressing charges.
   Nevertheless, the officers allegedly filed false statements,
indicating the women ``were victims who could identify the suspects
and were willing to press charges,'' Giuliani said. ``Not only were
the charges not supported, but there was a substantial allegation
they were trumped up.''
   However, William McKechnie, president of the Transit Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association, said he believed that if the officers are
indicted, ``we are sure that they will be vindicated by a jury of
their peers.''
   McDermott and Iannacone, who were suspended without pay after
their arrest, face a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and a
$250,000 fine on each of the five counts.
   A 1984 Transit Police Department report alleged widespread
improprieties by McDermott, Iannacone and two other transit
officers.
   The report, prepared by Lt. Thomas Dargan, said the managements
of the Transit Authority and the transit police shared some of the
blame, because the officers were motivated by a system that gave
better assignments to those making the most arrests.
   ``I feel sad for the officers,'' Dargan said in a telephone
interview Thursday.
</TEXT>
