<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites, Sub, a0455,0172</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf of 1st item to CORRECT to ``dachshund,'' sted
``dachsund.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OCEAN CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Summer will arrive a week early this
year, according to a tiny hermit crab and a dachshund named Gus The
Amazing Weather Dog.
   The crab, named Martin Z. Mollusk, was carried to the beach
under warm, sunny skies Thursday for the annual ritual in this
Jersey resort.
   Martin ``predicted'' that summer will arrive June 14 instead of
June 21, said city spokesman Mark Soifer.
   ``For the 13th consecutive year, Martin has seen his shadow,''
Soifer said. ``If it was cloudy, we would use a flashlight to make
sure he saw it.''
   The forecast method is unabashedly similar to that of
Punxsutawney Phil, the Pennsylvania groundhog used to predict when
spring will arrive.
   Gus The Amazing Weather Dog served as Mollusk's translator.
   ``Gus can get down really low,'' Soifer explained. ``He sniffed
around Martin and woofed and let us know, then he tried to bury
Martin.''
