<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoriegaReax     05-13 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega Reax,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Say They're Ready to Try Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Noriega, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors say they're ready to press their drug
case against Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, while a
federal judge investigates whether the government could drop
charges against the embattled leader.
   Chief Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Gregorie, the lead
prosecutor in the case, said Thursday he strongly opposed any deal
in the case as part of an effort to persuade Noriega to surrender
his post.
   ``I am against the dismissal, and right now I am ready to try
this case,'' Gregorie said.
   U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner, who met with Attorney General Edwin
Meese III in Washington, agreed.
   In a statement released through his office, Kellner did not
divulge details of his meeting with Meese but said he was ready to
proceed with the trial.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater acknowledged Thursday
that U.S. officials were engaged in ``plea bargaining'' with
Noriega, but stopped short of saying that dismissal of the
indictments was under negotiation.
   Noriega is charged in a 12-count Miami indictment with accepting
$4.6 million in bribes from Colombia's Medellin Cartel to protect
its interests, while in Tampa he faces three marijuana smuggling
counts.
   U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler, who is handling the case,
questioned whether the government alone can drop the drug
indictment against Noriega.
   ``My understanding and knowledge of the law is that the
presiding judge is not required to dismiss an indictment on the
motion of the government,'' Hoeveler said. ``However, I am having
the law researched further.''
   In previous rulings on the case, Hoeveler has noted the
government has an obligation to show the indictment was not
politically motivated.
   U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle, who brought the Tampa indictment
against Noriega, refused to comment Thursday on reports that he has
threatened to quit if the charges are dropped.
   But Noriega's attorneys said the government has little choice
but to dismiss the indictment because it was politically motivated.
   ``Gen. Noriega believes, and always has believed, that the
indictment against him was a political indictment,'' Noriega
attorney Neal Sonnett said Thursday. ``So a dismissal of the
indictment would have to be a pre-condition to any discussions.''
</TEXT>
