<HEAD>PRECEDE Beijing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Taiwan Calls Hijackers' Motives `Simple And Noble'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with quotes from hijackers, passengers back in
Canton, Taiwan government comment, report that phony weapons were
used. Changes byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Chinese men who threatened to blow up
a Boeing 737 unless it flew from the mainland to Taiwan were
welcomed as refugees today because they ``risked their lives to
seek freedom and democracy,'' Taiwan said.
   China thanked the rival government for returning the Chinese
airliner and its 107 passengers and 11 crew members today, nine
hours after the aircraft was hijacked to a Taiwanese military base.
   The air pirates, meanwhile, appeared on Taiwan television and
said they would have killed themselves had their hijacking failed.
   Chang Ching-kuo, 27, said in an interview on Taiwain's official
Chinese Television Service that he and his companion, Lung
Kuei-yun, 26, used a toy pistol and a bottle of a phony explosive
to force the plane to Taiwan Thursday.
   He said he and Lung also carried knives.
   ``We would have committed suicide if we failed,'' Chang said on
television. ``We never planned to return (to China).''
   The aircraft was hijacked Thursday evening after it left the
coastal city of Xiamen in Fujian province for Canton, the capital
of neighboring Guangdong province.
   It landed at an air force base in central Taiwan at about 9:30
p.m. Less than six hours later, the plane was refueled and sent
back to Xiamen with the passengers aboard.
   The hijackers remained in Taiwan and were granted political
asylum.
   Chang was identified as a worker at an arsenal in China's
southern Yunnan province, and Lung, a steel mill worker in southern
Guizhou province.
   A smiling Chang displayed a toy pistol and a bottle during the
televised interview. He said he defected because he ``detested the
brutality of communism.''
   Government spokesman Shaw Yu-ming said at a news conference that
authorities were investigating the air piracy. It was the first
hijacking of a civilian Chinese airplane to Taiwan.
   The Chinese Communists and the Taiwan Nationalists both claim to
be the legitimate rulers of China and have no direct communications
links.
   ``The two (hijackers) are our compatriots,'' Shaw said. ``They
have risked their lives to seek freedom and democracy. We must
respect their wishes and offer them protection. Their motives were
simple and noble.''
   Taiwan does ``not condone nor encourage any hijacking
behavior,'' Shaw said. He added: ``We would have been sending them
to their doom if we turned them back to the communists.''
   The hijackers didnot appear at the news conference.
   In Beijing, Hu Yizhou, director general of the national airliner
Civil Aviation Administration of China, originally asked Taiwan to
return the hijackers.
   After the plane flew back to Xiamen, however, Hu thanked the
Civil Aeronautics Bureau in Taiwan for the quick return of the
airliner and those aboard without mentioning the hijackers.
   ``We are very grateful to you for your help,'' Hu was quoted as
saying by China's official Xinhua News Agency.
   Xiamen, in southeastern Fujian province, is 136 miles across the
Taiwan Straits from Taiwan.
   In 1986, when the pilot of a Taiwan airliner operated by China
Airlines diverted his plane to Canton, mainland officials returned
the plane and other crew members but did not hand over the
defecting pilot.
   That incident led to the first direct talks between Communist
and Nationalist officials. Last fall, the Nationalists lifted a ban
on travel to the mainland.
</TEXT>
