<HEAD>Nine Killed In Plane Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with ages, nationalities of victims.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine plane crashed into
the side of a valley on North Island, killing all nine people
aboard, including three children, officials said today.
   Rescue workers in helicopters found the wreckage of the Piper
Seneca early today in rugged country near the Cook Strait town of
Wanganui. The cause of the crash was not determined.
   The victims included a woman and her two children, ages 9 and 7,
and a 19-month-old boy and his mother, said police spokesman Rob
Rattenbury. All passengers and crew members were New Zealanders.
   The plane vanished from radar screens as it approached Wanganui
on a flight from Hamilton, said Peter Northcote of the Rescue
Coordinating Center in Wellington.
   Northcote said wreckage was strewn along the side of Ahuahu
Valley about 20 miles north of Wanganui.
   The plane, one of three from Foxpine Air Charter Ltd. of Foxton,
lost radio contact Thursday evening, Northcote said.
