<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NurseShortage     05-13 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nurse Shortage,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nation's Nursing Shortage Gets Worse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's nursing shortage worsened last year,
causing delays in admissions, surgery and temporary closings of
emergency rooms, the American Hospital Association says.
   ``The nursing shortage continues to be a problem for most
hospitals, and although fewer hospitals report a severe shortage,
we still have the same situation _ not enough nurses,'' Joan Moss,
director of the association's Center for Nursing, said Thursday.
   Of 2,000 randomly surveyed hospitals, 78.6 percent reported a
nursing shortage in April 1987, up 2.4 percent from a year earlier,
the Chicago-based association said.
   Large hospitals in urbans areas on both coasts were more acutely
affected than smaller, rural institutions in the nation's
midsection.
   To combat the nursing shortage, three out of four hospitals
surveyed relied on overtime for nursing staff and 41 percent
employed temporary or agency nurses.
   Foreign nurses were recruited by 10 percent of hospitals,
predominately larger hospitals in the East.
   The association is a not-for-profit organization that serves as
a national advocate for hospitals and informs the public about
health care issues.
</TEXT>
