<HEAD>Lawmaker Convicted Of Embezzlement, Fined $3 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former aide to
ex-President Salvador Jorge Blanco has been fined $3 million and
sentenced to nine months in jail for embezzling $85,000.
   Rafael Flores Estrella, a member of the Chamber of Deputies and
Blanco's former administrative assistant, was sentenced following
his conviction Thursday night by the Supreme Court.
   He is one of nearly 20 former government officials, including
Jorge Blanco, accused of widespread corruption that allegedly
occurred during the former president's administration. Estrella was
the first to stand trial.
   Flores Estrella was tried by the Supreme Court because he is a
member of the legislature, a post he automatically loses because of
his conviction.
   He was charged with taking $85,000 from the treasury for a 1985
trip that Jorge Blanco was to make to Panama and Costa Rica.
Prosecutors alleged the trip was never taken and the money never
was returned.
   Flores Estrella denied any wrongdoing.
   The court stipulated that one day would be added to his jail
term for each dollar of the $3 million fine that Flores Estrella
does not pay.
   Jorge Blanco and other officials are accused of misusing
government funds to buy military equipment at inflated prices and
embezzling money earmarked for a public food program.
   Jorge Blanco, president from 1982 to 1986, has said the charges
are politically motivated. The corruption probe was ordered by
current President Joaquin Balaguer after he took office.
   The former chief executive was allowed to leave Santo Domingo a
year ago for treatment of a heart ailment at Emory University
Hospital in Atlanta.
   Jorge Blanco has ignored an order to return home and the
government has not attempted to extradite him. He is expected to be
tried regardless of whether he returns.
