<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AlzheimerDrug     05-13 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alzheimer Drug,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alzheimer Drug Showing Promise, Side Effects in Early Trials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early studies of a highly publicized drug for
Alzheimer's disease show some promise, but also serious side
effects in up to 80 percent of patients, a researcher says.
   Nausea, vomiting, allergic reactions and a worrisome increase in
liver enzymes have appeared in patients taking the drug, said Vinod
Kumar of the Southern Illinois University School of Medicine in
Springfield.
   No conclusions can be reached yet about the usefulness of
tetrahydroaminoacridine, often called THA, he said Thursday.
   Kumar reviewed results of published and unpublished studies from
Canada, Britain, Sweden and the United States at the annual meeting
of the American Psychiatric Association.
   THA generated excitement in 1986 when a study in the New England
Journal of Medicine reported dramatic improvement in Alzheimer
symptoms, particularly those related to memory deficits.
   A nationwide study at 17 institutions began last September, but
it was stopped in October because about 20 percent of patients
showed the liver abnormalities. The trial was restarted earlier
this year.
   Alzheimer's disease is a progressive, irreversible neurological
disorder affecting an estimated 2.5 million Americans. It kills
more than 100,000 people a year.
   Symptoms include gradual memory loss, impaired judgment,
disorientation, personality change and loss of language skills.
Eventually patients can no longer take care of themselves.
   The disease's cause is unknown, and it has no cure.
   Kumar, an investigator in the nationwide THA project, said early
results at his institution are promising enough to justify
continuing the study, but they do not prove that the drug is
effective.
   In one of the new studies, Kumar said, Canadian researchers
reported significant improvement among 17 patients who took THA for
six weeks. But 80 percent of the 51 patients who began the study
suffered side effects, and 36 percent of the 17 who completed the
experiment had the liver problem, which indicates cellular
abnormalities.
   A Swedish study found significant improvement in five of 10
patients who took THA for one to two weeks. But the side effects
appeared in seven patients, and two showed allergic reactions to
the drug that Kumar said had not been reported before.
   Three of six patients in a British study showed dramatic
improvement but also the liver enzyme increase, he said.
   In contrast to the other studies, a 10-patient experiment in
California found no improvement after one week on THA. Perhaps the
drug must be taken longer to have an effect, Kumar said.
   Three of the California patients had the liver enzyme problem.
   ``No one in any way expects this to be a cure in that it halts
the progression of Alzheimer's disease,'' said THA investigator
Maurice Dysken of the University of Minnesota.
   Instead, the hope is that it will quickly produce an improvement
in learning and memory, he said. If the patient's abilities then
deteriorate at the same rate as they would have without the drug,
he will at least be starting from a higher level and so be better
off at any given point during the decline, Dysken said.
   ``That would be an advance,'' Dysken said in an interview.
   ``If you had a drug that delayed the need for nursing home
treatment, that's not a trivial effect,'' said Stephen Read, an
Alzheimer researcher at the John Douglas French Center in Los
Alamitos, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
