<HEAD>Afghan Leader Replaces 23 Provincial Governors</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: One name for Najib is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Afghanistan's
Soviet-backed government has replaced 23 of the country's 29
provincial governors without explaining why.
   Official Radio Kabul, monitored Thursday night in Islamabad,
said President Najib has named new governors in 23 provinces
including Kabul.
   It then gave a list of all 23 but nothing more.
   Terse announcements are common in the radio's Pushtu, Farsi,
Urdu and English newscasts. The change of governors appeared
connected with national elections Najib suddenly called in April.
   Official figures indicated voter turnout was about 20 percent in
the vote for parliamentary and provincial officials from a slate of
socialist parties.
   Western diplomats in Kabul have said most parties are fronts for
the ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan.
   The burly Najib, former chief of the feared State Security
Agency KHAD, has made frequent government shake-ups in his two
years in power.
   His fate soon will be in the hands of his 100,000-man security
force when Soviet troops leave.
   Under an agreement signed last month in Geneva, the estimated
115,000 Red Army soldiers are to begin withdrawing Sunday.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in 1979 to replace one
pro-Soviet regime with another and defend it against a U.S.-backed
Moslem rebel movement, which is believed to control about 80
percent of the countryside.
   Guerrillas and diplomats said Thursday that about 4,000 Soviet
soldiers have started evacuating their biggest garrison in eastern
Afghanistan in preparation for the total pullout.
   People coming from Jalalabad, site of the Soviet garrison, are
reporting that ``the Russians are sending their heavy equipment to
Kabul,'' said Kabir, a member of the military committee of the
Yunis Khalis guerrilla faction.
   A Western diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
guerrilla sources reported that up to 60 Soviet trucks headed west
Thursday toward Kabul, 110 miles away.
   Moscow's troops reportedly have handed dozens of posts over to
Afghan troops in recent weeks. But well-armed guerrilla fighters
have overrun many of them.
</TEXT>
