<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   05-13 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0534,0717</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Riot Police Clash With Worshipers, 17 Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with clash, injuries, 300
Palestinians freed. Changes byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HAITHAM HAMAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli riot police entered the sacred Temple
Mount today and fired rubber bullets at protesting Moslem
worshipers on the final Sabbath of the holy month of Ramadan.
Fifteen Arabs and two policemen were injured, army radio said.
   An estimated 5,000 worshipers crowded the Al Aqsa mosque to mark
the holy day. The figure was much lower than in previous years.
Officials, fearing violence, closed off large parts of the occupied
territories and blocked Palestinians from reaching Jerusalem to
worship.
   The army command reported today that Israeli soldiers shot and
killed a Palestinian in the West Bank village of Qabatiyeh on
Thursday after he ignored orders to halt during a search of the
village.
   The death brings to 187 the number of Palestinians killed since
the beginning of the Arab uprising Dec. 8. An Israeli soldier and a
teen-age girl also have died.
   The army said 300 Palestinians from the West Bank were being
released from prison today as a goodwill gesture. An army spokesman
said some of the prisoners had been arrested on security charges
and others for criminal offenses but did not elaborate.
   An army helicopter hovered over the Temple Mount and military
police perched on rooftops as about 1,000 worshipers emerged from
prayers chanting pro-PLO slogans and burning Israeli flags. Several
hundred hurled stones at a nearby Israeli police station.
   Hundreds of helmeted military police then broke into the
complex, firing rubber bullets to disperse the protesters.
   Army radio said 15 protesters and two policemen were injured.
Police spokesmen could not be reached for comment.
   Israel radio said at least 20 people were arrested.
   Hundreds of worshipers remained inside the Al Aqsa mosque,
afraid to leave, after police entered the Temple Mount, known to
the Arabs as Harm al Sharif, or ``Noble Enclosure.'' The Moslem
prayer leader called on police to withdraw.
   ``Go away!'' prayer leader Mohammed Hussein called out through
the mosque loudspeakers. ``Allow the Moslems to leave peacefully.''
   Outside, worshipers paraded outlawed Palestinian flags and black
flags of mourning as they circled the mosque complex.
   ``Jews out!'' the protesters chanted. ``We don't want to see any
Zionists!''
   Others shouted: ``No fear, no fear. The stone is better than the
Kalashnikov (rifle)!''
   Unprecedented security precautions were implemented to thwart
expected violence beginning Thursday night, when Moslems celebrated
the ``Night of Fate,'' a holiday marking the revelation of the
Koran, Islam's holy book, to the prophet Mohammed.
   Journalists and non-residents were barred from the Gaza Strip,
home to 650,000 Palestinians, and the West Bank city of Ramallah,
home to 40,000. Police and soldiers turned back cars from the West
Bank heading for Jerusalem.
   Police Commissioner David Kraus said 3,300 policemen were
deployed in Jerusalem to maintain order.
   The army also clamped curfews on 120,000 Palestinians in Nablus,
the largest West Bank city, and neighboring refugee camps. A
military spokesman said the curfews were imposed in the morning
after the army received reports that disturbances might break out.
   Curfews also were in effect in parts of Gaza City and the
Dheishe refugee camp near Bethlehem. During a curfew, residents are
barred from leaving their homes.
   This reporter counted three roadblocks in the 10-mile stretch of
road between Bethlehem and Jerusalem. Soldiers turned back every
car bearing West Bank license plates unless drivers carried special
military government permits.
   An army spokesman refused to comment on the roadblocks but said
the army was taking various measures to guarantee quiet over the
weekend and during the Id El Fitr holiday, which follows Ramadan.
   Ramadan is due to end Monday or Tuesday with the sighting of the
new moon.
   Officials also feared there might be violence Sunday, when
Israelis mark the 40th anniversary of the state and celebrate
Jerusalem Day, the 21st anniversary of the capture of Arab east
Jerusalem.
   Thursday night, one policeman was injured when a rock hit his
head during a aclash between riot police and worshipers on the
Temple Mount, Israel radio said. Thirty-eight Palestinians were
arrested for stone-throwing.
</TEXT>
