<HEAD>Sanitation Workers Find $48,900 in Trash _ And Turn It In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two sanitation workers found $48,900 in cash in
a cardbox they were throwing away and turned it in to authorities.
But the women whose trash can the bills came from say the money
isn't theirs.
   ``As far as I know it's not ours,'' said Marianne Bosted of the
two bundles of bills that fell out of a trash can Thursday behind
her house in Queens.
   ``I keep saying to my aunt, `Are you sure you weren't saving
this in a box to give to me?''' Ms. Bosted told the New York Post.
   The two Sanitation Department workers who found the cash have
insisted on anonymity, said department spokesman Vito Turso.
   ``I guess everybody has always fantasized about finding a lot of
money and what they would do with it,'' he said. ``These guys found
it and did the right thing _ they turned it in.''
   Police are trying to determine who the money belongs to and how
it got into Ms. Bosted's trash, said Police Sgt. John Venetucci.
   An officer at the 104th Precinct told New York Newsday the money
was discovered when the sanitation workers accidentally dropped a
cardboard box. The bottom broke and the money fell out, he said.
   The Daily News reached a woman who lived nearby who said: ``I
threw out some boxes that belonged to my (late) husband. I didn't
look inside of them.''
