<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Psychiatrist-Fortune     05-13 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Psychiatrist-Fortune,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychoanalyst Under Fire Over Patient's Fortune Takes Leave from
Institute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBRA HALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head of the American Psychiatric
Association is taking leave as president of a prestigious research
institute while he prepares to face accusations that he exploited a
wealthy patient, the institute says.
   Dr. George Pollock was granted a leave of absence from his
position as president of the Chicago Institute for Psychoanalysis,
Gilda Buchbinder, chairwoman of the institute's board of trustees,
said Thursday.
   In court papers, Pollock has been accused of unduly influencing
the late Anne P. Lederer, who gave him $80,000 a year in trusts and
bequeathed $5 million to a psychiatric institute she founded during
the decade he treated her for depression.
   ``Dr. Pollock has requested and been granted a leave of absence
in order to have time to prepare for the trial of the lawsuit and
to address matters raised by news releases about that case,'' Mrs.
Buchbinder said. ``He has not resigned, nor has the board requested
him to resign.''
   The allegations against Pollock are contained in documents filed
by Mrs. Lederer's only child, Francis L. Lederer II, who is
contesting her will leaving him $200,000. Mrs. Lederer died in 1984
at age 78.
   Pollock, one of Chicago's leading psychoanalysts, has referred
all questions about the case to his attorney, Robert Tepper of
Chicago, who also declined comment Thursday.
   Pollock denied the allegations, however, in an affidavit Dec. 4,
1986.
   The case is to come to trial July 5 in Cook County Probate Court.
   Mrs. Buchbinder said that Dr. Henry Seidenberg, vice president
of the Chicago institute, would assume the president's duties in
Pollock's absence. The institute trains psychiatrists and
therapists to become psychoanalysts.
   ``The board has not appointed an interim president or a new
president,'' she said, declining to say anything further.
   Seidenberg also declined comment Thursday, saying, ``there is
litigation involved.''
   Pollock's term as president of the 34,000-member APA
automatically expired late Thursday at the end of the association's
annual meeting in Montreal. He is being succeeded by Dr. Paul J.
Fink of Philadelphia.
   Psychoanalysis is a branch of psychotherapy in which a patient
meets frequently with a therapist and is encouraged to explore his
or her innermost feelings, childhood experiences and other emotions.
   Pollock conducted up to five sessions a week with Mrs. Lederer
from 1969 to 1980.
   During those years, Mrs. Lederer established a trust fund that
has paid Pollock $50,000 a year since 1976 and will continue paying
him through 1993, court documents show. A second trust has paid
Pollock's family $30,000 a year since 1978, the records show.
   In 1980, Mrs. Lederer founded the Anne P. Lederer Research
Institute to promote psychiatric research and music. It has never
paid out any money because of the court fight, court documents show.
</TEXT>
