<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Angola-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru   05-13 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0553,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks End On Southern Africa</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with eight grafs to UPDATE with talks ending. Pick up
7th pvs, `Diplomatic sources...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa and Angola today
completed a second round of talks on Angola's 13-year civil war and
independence for South-West Africa and said they would meet again
with U.S. and Cuban diplomats present.
   South African Foreign Minister Roelof ``Pik'' Botha said the
Congo government had offered to host further talks.
   Botha also said the United States and Cuba, which were not
present at the meetings here today, would be invited to the next
round of talks. No date was given.
   This week's talks follow meetings last week in London, attended
by Angola, South Africa, Cuba and the United States.
   The United States and South Africa support Angolan rebels
fighting the Marxist government, which is backed by 40,000 Cuban
troops.
   According to a report Thursday by Angola's official news agency
ANGOP, the meetings here took place at the request of the South
African government. The Congo government did not participate.
   The South African delegation included Botha and Defense Minister
Gen. Magnus Malan. Angola was represented by Justice Minister
Fernando Van Dunem and the deputy chief of staff of the army.
   ``I want to affirm that my government strongly believes that we
as Africans ought to resolve our problems ourselves,'' Botha said.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
South Africa appeared to be trying to chart an independent course
in the negotiations.
   They said U.S. diplomats had not been officially informed of
today's meeting.
   But American diplomats praised Congo President Denis Sassou
Nguesso for hosting the talks and for helping the United States
arrange earlier meetings with Angola.
   Sassou Nguesso's socialist leadership has close ties with
Angola's Marxist government.
   Angola demands that South Africa withdraw an estimated 9,000
South African troops from southern Angolan soil and wants to halt
South African and U.S. aid to the rebel National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola.
   Neither UNITA nor the South-West African People's Organization,
a group fighting South African rule in South-West Africa for 22
years, were included in the talks.
   Angola also demands that South Africa withdraw from South-West
Africa, also known as Namibia, and grant the former German colony
independence in accordance with a 1978 U.N. Security Council
resolution.
   South Africa, backed by the United States, in turn demands the
full withdrawal of an estimated 40,000 Cuban support troops from
Angola.
   U.S.-brokered peace talks on the related issues of the Angolan
civil war and Namibian independence have foundered for years on
reluctance by both sides to be the first to withdraw.
   A major breakthrough came in March, when Angolan and Cuban
negotiators presented U.S. officials with a proposed, four-year
plan to send the Cuban forces home. London talks on May 3-4
followed.
   South Africa was handed administration of Namibia after World
War I under a mandate of the now-defunct League of Nations. The
United Nations first called for the territory's independence in
1966.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
