<HEAD>Shiite Clashes Flare Anew As Truce Frays</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf pvs: `Most of...' to UPDATE
with specifics of meeting and background on militias. Pick up 9th
graf pvs: `Also today...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite militias battled with
rocket-propelled grenades and machine guns in the slums of south
Beirut today, shattering a 36-hour-old truce brokered by Syria and
Iran.
   There was no immediate report of casualties as Syrian and
Iranian mediators struggled to rescue the fraying cease-fire
between their main Lebanese proxies.
   The fighting between the pro-Syrian Amal militia and the
Iranian-backed fundamentalists of Hezbollah, or Party of God,
flared anew in the Shiite neighborhoods of Raml el-Ali, Haret
Hreik, Ouzai and Ein el-Sikkeh.
   The clashes forced the closing of all roads leading to Beirut
airport, said a police spokesman who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Planes continued to take and land while bursts of gunfire hit
the runways and tarmac, the spokesman said.
   He said today's fighting was the most serious violation of the
cease-fire since it was called by Presidents Hafez Assad of Syria
and Ali Khamenei of Iran Wednesday night.
   That truce ended a six-day bloodbath in which at least 188
people were killed and 543 wounded in the savage street fighting
between Amal and Hezbollah for control of the 16 square miles of
slums.
   Most of the 18 foreign hostages held by Shiite extremists are
believed to be imprisoned in the embattled district.
   Assad's personal representative, Brig. Gen. Ali Hammoud, and
Khamenei's envoy, deputy Foreign Minister Hossein Sheikholeslam,
met at the Iranian embassy with delegates from the warring factions
in an effort to restore the cease-fire, the police spokesman said.
   Hezbollah's 3,000 fighters are outnumbered more than 2-to-1 by
Amal's Syrian-armed militia.
   Also today, the Christian Voice of Lebanon radio reported that
Christian militia leader Samir Geagea, a pro-Israeli foe of Syria,
was the target of a car bomb that exploded north of Beirut.
   Police confirmed that a car containing an estimated 330 pounds
of TNT exploded at 10 p.m. (4 p.m. EDT) Thursday in the village of
Mastita, 20 miles north of Beirut in the Christian heartland.
   But Geagea's Lebanese Forces militia, the Christians' main
military machine, issued a communique denying that he had been the
target of an assassination attempt.
   No group has claimed responsibilty for the blast. On April 23, a
car bomb explosion killed 69 people and wounded 111 in the mainly
Moslem northern port of Tripoli.
</TEXT>
