<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ChildPreacher 2ndLd-Writethru a0554 05-13 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child Preacher, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0554,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Self-Styled Child Street Preacher Suspended Fourth Time From
School</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from boy, mother,
assistant principal, color from scene. Pickup 9th graf, `Duffey's
letters...' DELETES last 2 grafs, now outdated. Note language in
last graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old boy who was suspended three
times after shouting biblical epithets at teachers and classmates
received his fourth suspension today after he stayed outside school
preaching as his mother watched.
   ``If it pleases the Lord, I'm enjoying it,'' said Duffey Strode
as an assistant principal tried to get him to come inside. ``I'd
rather get gold and silver up in heaven than my education down
here.''
   Duffey, recovering from chicken pox, arrived about 7:30 a.m. on
his bicycle in a steady rain and was immediately surrounded by some
two dozen reporters and cameramen. Wearing a black jacket and
carrying a zippered case apparently containing a Bible, he began
preaching in the parking lot.
   ``Thou shall not take the name of the Lord thy God in vain,'' he
shouted. ``Thou shalt not commit adultery! You're guilty! Even your
eyes are filled with adultery! Men can't keep their eyes off women
and women can't keep their eyes off men. Adulterers shall be put to
death and their blood shall be upon them!''
   Assistant Principal Shirley Ramsey told Duffey several times
that he was supposed to be in the school building before classes,
but the youngster ignored her.
   ``Everyone in there can do their hellish things. Why can't my
own do theirs?'' asked Robin Strode, Duffey's mother, after she
received the boy's letter of suspension from Eastfield Elementary
School.
   Mrs. Strode's other son, Matthew, 5, also has been suspended for
preaching. Her daughter, Pepper, 6, also has been suspended because
she stayed outside with her brothers while they preached. Matthew
and Pepper's suspensions expire May 19 and Mrs. Strode said she
expected them to be suspended again.
   She also said it was her children's decision to preach.
   ``After the first suspension, we asked them to stop preaching
for a couple of days,'' Mrs. Strode said. ``It just about broke
their hearts. They got real upset.''
   Mrs. Strode said the letter gave no indication about future
action to be taken against Duffey if he continued his street
preaching when he returns to school.
   Mrs. Ramsey said after handing the boy the letter, ``We're
trying to keep the door open for Duffey to return to school.''
   Today's suspension was the latest in a month-long battle between
the Strode family and school officials.
   ``I see no resolution in sight, I just don't see it,'' Duffey's
father, David Strode, said earlier this week. ``It's just a bunch
of people full of the devil. There must be a real cesspool of sin
here.''
   His son had been suspended once for fighting and twice before
for remaining outside the school, hurling biblical epithets at
students and teachers.
   Duffey's letters of suspension haven't mentioned his preaching.
Principal James Gorst wrote a letter to the Strodes that said the
boy had created ``a loud disruptive noise by screaming at school
staff members.''
   But Duffey's parents, who moved to Marion 17 months ago from
Pennsylvania, said they are convinced the only problem is Duffey's
preaching.
   The Strodes call the suspensions an attack on their
constitutional guarantees of freedom of speech and freedom of
religion and say they plan to take the county school system to
court.
   ``Nobody nowadays wants to stand up for Jesus Christ,'' Mrs.
Strode said. ``I just don't understand it.''
   Federal Appeals Court Judge Sam Ervin III told school officials
Thursday that if they take reasonable action in such cases, they
are protected under the law.
   ``Constitutional rights of students are not automatically
co-extensive with adults in a general setting,'' Ervin said.
   School officials and Duffey's parents agree that his street
preaching intensified after a March 18 scuffle with three other
boys at school.
   Gorst decided to paddle all four boys, but when it was Duffey's
turn, he bolted from the school and ran home, Mrs. Ramsey said.
   His flight earned him his first suspension.
   When he returned, he began his preaching, first directing his
warnings of hellfire and damnation at other students.
   Later, he hurled them at teachers as they arrived for work each
morning, calling them ``fornicators, whoremongers, adulterers and
queers.''
</TEXT>
