<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlantFire     05-13 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Fire,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plant Explosion Kills One, Two Others in Critical Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A metal processing plant where a fire killed
one worker and injured nine others had been cited for previous fire
safety problems, according to city fire records.
   The explosion in a metal dust collector at Mineral Met Inc. on
the city's east side Thursday spewed flaming metal chips throughout
an industrial plant, sparking a fire that took three hours to bring
under control. Two of those injured remained in critical condition
today.
   Fire inspectors' reports indicate the company has been cited for
poor fire prevention, including the accumulation of highly
flammable dust and poor dust control.
   The records also show fires in 1984 and 1986 were attributed to
careless smoking in dusty conditions, and a 1976 fire was started
by machinery sparks.
   However, plant manager Keith Edwards told radio station WERE-AM
today, ``In recent years I think we've cooperated very well with
the fire prevention department, and even a couple of them had
commented that they thought we had been doing a good job in recent
years.''
   Twenty-nine employees were inside the plant when the fire
erupted.
   ``The dust collector blew up and spread these flaming metal
chips and debris all over and started the fire,'' said Fire Chief
James McNamee. ``The workers were in the grinding room where this
dust is generated.''
   The most explosive powdered metals, including aluminum and
manganese, were stored away from the fire behind four fire doors
the city ordered installed in 1986.
   Firefighters found the dead worker's body inside the plant after
the blaze was brought under control about noon. Lonall Drake, 32,
of Cleveland, a temporary worker at the plant, was killed in the
explosion, a coroner's spokesman said.
   Businesses near the plant on the city's east side were
evacuated, while firefighters worked to keep the blaze from
spreading to a the warehouse containing the powdered metals.
   Cleveland Metropolitan General Hospital spokeswoman Terri Manns
said two men were in critical condition with burns over 30 to 37
percent of their bodies. Four others remained in fair or good
condition at the hospital, she said.
   One person was transferred to an Erie, Pa., with a foot injury
and three others were treated and released at other hospitals.
</TEXT>
