<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Sikhs 2ndLd-Writethru a0557 05-13 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0557,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Kill 5 Sikhs in Golden Temple</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more killings. Trims. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police snipers killed five Sikh militants
in the Golden Temple complex today, and one Sikh militant was
killed trying to escape a police cordon around the holy shrine,
police said.
   Today was the fifth day of a siege of the temple, where a band
of militants was holed up. About 100 Sikh militants remain in the
temple complex, which is surrounded by about 2,500 policemen and
paramilitary troops.
   Punjab state police chief K.P.S. Gill said the militants and the
security forces exchanged fire after sunrise for much of the day.
During the afternoon, police sharpshooters positioned in nearby
buildings killed five militants, Gill said.
   The other militant was killed earlier in the day when a
half-dozen men tried to shoot their way through the security
forces' cordon, he said.
   The government launched its siege Monday after Sikh militants in
the temple complex opened fire on security forces and injured five
officers. No food or other supplies have been allowed into the
temple since then.
   The killings brought the death toll at the complex to at least
27 since Monday. At least five of those killed were civilians
caught in the cross-fire.
   Because any attempt to storm the shrine would almost certainly
spark violent reprisals by Sikhs outraged at the desecration of
their holiest shrine, the siege appears aimed at forcing the
militants into submission or at least containing them. The temple
complex is the foremost stronghold of armed Sikhs who want to
establish a separate Sikh nation in Punjab state.
   The army stormed the complex in June 1984 to oust extremists,
and about 1,200 people were killed. In retaliation, Prime Minister
Indira Gandhi was assassinated by two of her Sikh bodyguards.
   On Thursday, police lifted the curfew in the old, walled city
except for the immediate vicinity of the shrine. People began
returning to the streets today.
   Gill told a news conference six Sikh militants firing AK-47
rifles attempted to storm out of the Golden Temple complex shortly
after midnight.
   Security forces, whose weapons apparently were equipped with
night-vision scopes, returned fire and killed one of the Sikhs. Two
escaped into the city and three retreated into the temple complex,
Gill said. He said that one of the escapees was believed injured.
   Gill said two paramilitary soldiers with the Central Reserve
Police Force were injured in the shootout.
   At daybreak, the bodies of more five men were seen inside the
complex. Gill said they apparently died during overnight exchanges
with security forces.
   Gill said security forces ``control all the dominant features
around the temple.''
   Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Islam and Hinduism, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million people but are a majority in this
northern state.
   The extremists have been waging a guerrilla campaign since 1982
for more political autonomy or an independent homeland in Punjab.
   At least 955 deaths in Punjab state have been blamed on the
extremists so far this year. Most of the victims have been Hindus
or moderate Sikhs opposed to the separatist campaign.
   The Golden Temple stands toward the western end of the complex
at the center of a large pool. The middle section contains a dining
hall and a large meeting hall, while office buildings are to the
east.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
