<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseSpending 1stLd-Writethru a0426 05-13 0898</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Spending, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,890</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new, picking up 3rd graf pvs, The anti-drug</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate was trying to agree today on a plan
for Navy ships and Air Force planes to become more involved in the
war on drugs, but the Pentagon was resisting the proposals.
   The key dispute involves whether to give the Navy authority to
arrest suspected drug traffickers caught outside the three-mile
limit recognized by the United States, say senators involved in the
effort.
   ``This issue of arrest powers is a very tricky and involved
legal issue,'' said Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska. ``The military is
very worried about the implications of this and just how it would
work. But we'll be able to work something out, no question.''
   ``The public wants this done,'' said Stevens. ``I get a lot of
people saying to me that we ought to get the military involved in
this, that the military has the power to do something about this.''
   ``The Pentagon isn't too happy about this,'' Stevens said. ``But
they're going to have to get involved. It's a war out there and
it's time for them to join the war.''
   The anti-drug plan was the major unresolved issue as the Senate
worked toward completion of a Pentagon budget bill for the fiscal
year beginning Oct. 1.
   The House version of the Pentagon bill, approved by that chamber
Wednesday, ordered President Reagan to have the military
``substantially halt'' the flow of illegal drugs across U.S.
borders.
   Neither of the two main Senate plans goes that far, but whatever
passes the Senate eventually will have to be reconciled with the
House measure during a conference committee.
   One Senate proposal, backed chiefly by Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga.,
chairman of the Armed Services Committee, would have the military
provide logistical help and intelligence, chiefly from Air Force
radar planes, to civilian law enforcement agencies.
   The other, authored by Sens. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., and Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., goes beyond the Nunn plan by also giving the
military the authority to arrest suspected drug traffickers on the
high seas.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci spent several hours Thursday
afternoon at the Capitol, discussing the various plans. Carlucci
said earlier this week that he didn't feel the Pentagon should be
involved in law enforcement work.
   D'Amato, asked about the reaction of Pentagon officials to his
plan, said, ``They're not happy. ... They're not doing cartwheels.''
   But Wilson said ``the military is going to have to do more. They
may not be happy, but they'll do what they can.''
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., agreed. ``Local law enforcement is
being overwhelmed by a flood of drugs. We need to stop it beyond
the borders. Once it gets into the United States, it is
immeasurably more difficult to control.''
   The military is now barred from enforcing civilian laws by the
Posse Comitatus Act, an 1878 law enacted to halt the practice of
having the Army enforce laws in the post-Civil War southern states.
   That law was amended in 1981 to permit the military to provide
some aid, and U.S. military surveillance information is now passed
along to some civilian agencies. In addition, Coast Guard officials
now travel aboard Navy ships patrolling the Caribbean Sea.
   At the Pentagon on Thursday, chief spokesman Dan Howard said the
military could slow, but not halt, drug trafficking.
   ``We have ample military resources to be able to stop every
aircraft at our border, but in fact that's a much more complex
problem than I think most people realize,'' he said.
   Nunn agreed. He noted that, for example, Pentagon aerial
surveillance is chiefly aimed at relatively high-flying Soviet jets
and bombers, rather than the small, low-flying planes used for drug
trafficking.
   The bill authorizes overall military spending in the next fiscal
year of $299.5 billion. That is the same amount in the House
measure.
   In working on the bill Thursday, the Senate:
   _Killed, 82-13, the latest attempt to have the chamber express a
formal opinion on Reagan's Persian Gulf policy. The plan by Sen.
Brock Adams, D-Wash., would have asked for a detailed plan from
Reagan about his policy in the region, and would have given
Congress 15 days after that to vote on the policy.
   _Killed, 57-39, a proposal to halt most U.S. underground nuclear
testing. The House approved an underground test ban, meaning the
issue will have to be resolved by a conference committee.
Above-ground atomic tests have been outlawed since 1963.
   _Restored, on a 64-32 decision, a ``Buy America'' provision
requiring the Pentagon to purchase U.S.-made products, including
anthracite coal. The Pentagon says it already has a four-year
supply of the coal and doesn't need any more. The ``Buy America''
plan had been stripped out of the bill by the Armed Services
Committee.
   _Rejected, 60-37, an amendment banning any U.S. combat troops in
leftist-ruled Nicaragua or its neighbor, U.S.-backed Honduras. The
troop ban was approved last week by the House, an indication that
lawmakers distrust Reagan's repeated assurances that he has no
intention of using U.S. combat troops against Nicaragua.
   _Killed, 61-36, a proposal to cut spending for the railroad
version of the MX nuclear missile from $700 million to $200 and use
the extra $500 million to buy more non-nuclear weapons. The House
proposes to spend only $100 million for the rail version of the MX.
</TEXT>
