<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-USMilitary     05-13 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-US Military,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Lawmakers Approve U.S.-Japan Military Accord</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers agreed today that Japan will pay the
benefits of Japanese employees of the U.S. military.
   The Parliament's House of Councilors approved the measure, which
was a revision of an agreement with the United States in which
Japan agreed to pay half the costs.
   During a visit to Washington in January, Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita pledged to increase Japan's contribution to the cost of
maintaining American forces here.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party and the Democratic
Socialist Party, the third-largest opposition party, backed the
agreement, said Sadanori Yajima, a House official. It was opposed
by the Socialist and Communist parties and the No. 2 opposition
Komeito.
   Under the revision, Japan will shoulder up to 100 percent of the
costs of eight types of benefits and allowances of the
approximately 21,000 Japanese now employed at U.S. military bases,
Yajima said.
   The benefits include retirement pay, housing, transportation and
cost of living allowances.
   The workers' basic salary is paid by the United States
government.
   In the earlier five-year agreement which went into effect last
June, Japan agreed to pay 50 percent of those costs, amounting to
an estimated $167 million in fiscal 1988, according to Yajima.
   The revision will boost Japan's share to 100 percent by 1991. It
was prompted by calls from the United States for Japan to increase
its share of the costs in light of the appreciating value of the
yen.
   The measure was approved by the Cabinet and earlier passed the
lower House of Representatives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
