<DOCNO> AP880513-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Cuomo-DeathPenalty     05-13 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuomo-Death Penalty,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY Gov. Cuomo Vetoes Death Penalty For Sixth Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BELLAFIORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo today vetoed legislation
that would have restored the death penalty in New York. It was
Cuomo's sixth veto of the bill, and the 12th consecutive year it
has been blocked by the state's chief executive.
   It was not immediately known if the state Legislature would
attempt to garner the two-thirds vote needed to override Cuomo's
veto. But Assemblyman Vincent Graber, the death penalty's chief
advocate in that chamber, said last week that he didn't have enough
votes to override.
   Cuomo said once again that he would urge the Legislature to pass
his alternative proposal to give life without parole to the state's
most violent criminals.
   ``My opposition to granting to the state the power to execute
this ultimate and violent act of retribution is well-known,'' Cuomo
said. ``If there is a serious interest in enhancing the sanctions
for the most serious crimes, there should be no reason to postpone
enactment of a life without parole statute.''
   Restoration of the death penalty was vetoed six consecutive
years from 1977-82 by Cuomo's predecessor, fellow Democrat Gov.
Hugh Carey, and has been vetoed every year since then by Cuomo.
   The last criminal to die in New York's electric chair was Eddie
Lee Mays in 1963. Federal and state court rulings have since
rendered capital punishment statutes sill on the books in New York
to be unenforceable.
   Death penalty advocates hoped that outrage over three police
officer shootings in New York City so far this year would change
the minds of some legislators opposed to capital punishment. Those
deaths include the execution-style slaying of New York City rookie
officer Edward Byrne, who was killed while guarding a witness in a
drug case.
   An override in the 150-member Democratic-controlled Assembly
would need 100 votes, but the vote on the bill in that house last
week fell eight votes short of that total.
   The Republican-controlled Senate passed the bill 38-17 in
February but sponsor Sen. Dale Volker said he could generate the
three additional votes needed in the 61-member house.
   The legislation would have allowed the death penalty in cases
where an on-duty police officer or prison guard was murdered, when
the murder was committed to prevent a person from testifying at a
criminal proceeding, in murder-for-hire cases or when the defendant
committed murder along with another violent felony such as
kidnapping, rape or robbery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
