<2ND_LINE>PM-Lehder Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0514,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lehder Case To Go To Jury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with additional remarks from
prosecutor, case going to jury. Pickup 3rd graf, `the jury...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor in the
cocaine-smuggling case of Carlos Lehder Rivas today urged jurors
who have heard seven months of testimony to convict the Colombian
of ``everything ... or nothing.''
   ``In fact, he is guilty of all the counts in the indictment. You
either convict him of everything in this case or convict him of
nothing in this case,'' U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle said in his
final arguments.
   The panel, which is being sequestered, then received
instructions from U.S. District Judge Howell W. Melton and began
deliberations.
   The jury must determine whether Lehder was responsible for
smuggling tons of cocaine into this country from his native
Colombia or whether he was victimized by a group of deceitful
American smugglers, as the defense contends.
   Lehder, 38, and co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed, 57, are charged
with conspiring to smuggle 3.3 tons of cocaine via Lehder's private
Bahamian island, Norman's Cay, from 1978 to 1980.
   In arguments Thursday, Merkle charged that Lehder wore masks
``that have been stripped away by the evidence.''
   Merkle claimed that arguments by defense attorney Edward R.
Shohat were an ``attempt to plant a seed of doubt in your mind that
is not there.''
   The prosecutor challenged the defense's contention that Lehder
was victimized by convicted drug smuggler Ed Ward and members of a
U.S. smuggling organization. ``Ward was just another pilot,''
Merkle said.
   He reserved his harshest comments for Lehder, who has been
depicted by more than 100 government witnesses as a flamboyant,
womanizing neo-Nazi.
   ``This guy has a screw loose, ladies and gentlemen,'' Merkle
said. ``He wasn't playing with a full deck.''
   In a surprise move last week, defense lawyers announced they
would call no witnesses. Shohat concluded his arguments Thursday by
telling jurors to ``do what you feel is right.''
   The jury must not condemn Lehder based on the prosecution's
attacks on his character, said Shohat, but stick to the specific
charges in the indictment.
   ``The issue is not whether Mr. Lehder was good or bad. The issue
in this case is the 11 counts in the indictment,'' said Shohat.
   He ridiculed the government for trying to make it appear that
Lehder, who has been identified as a key figure in Colombia's
violent Medellin cartel, was responsible for this country's drug
problem.
   ``If that is true, you could lock up the doors to this
courthouse and tear down all the `Just Say No,' signs,'' Shohat
said, referring to the national anti-drug campaign.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise. He was arrested near the Colombian
city of Medellin in February 1987 after a shootout, and was
immediately flown to Florida for trial.
   Reed of San Pedro, Calif., is charged with smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
