<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GiuffreClosing     05-13 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Giuffre Closing,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Closes Philly Hospital, Cites 12 Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Health Department has closed
all but two units of a private, inner-city Philadelphia hospital
where officials say inadequate care might have caused 12 deaths in
the past year.
   The action Thursday followed a three-month investigation at the
James G. Giuffre Medical Center that focused on 66 cases since May
1987. It found 124 deficiencies, including 29 instances of
unnecessary surgery and 55 cases of post-operative complications,
according to department spokesman Gary Froseth. Included in the
allegations was a report that a doctor's unlicensed son had
assisted in surgery. The hospital's namesake and chief executive
officer and his daughter, both licensed physicians, must refrain
from patient care until further investigation by the state.
   ``The hospital will remain closed until they submit a plan of
corrections and we determine those areas cited as deficient have
been corrected,'' Froseth said Thursday. ``When we have done that,
those areas can be reopened.''
   He said no deadline for the plan was set.
   In a statement, hospital officials said many problems already
have been addressed and the officials hope to receive permission to
reopen all units soon.
   ``We are pleased that Giuffre officials have agreed to this
plan,'' Health Secretary N. Mark Richards said. ``We believe a
change in the Giuffre board is the first step in implementing other
changes which will allow the facility to eventually operate in
accordance with departmnent regulations.''
   Richards said the department is willing to work with Giuffre to
ensure that the facility meets proper health-care standards.
Investigators were to return to the hospital today to check reports
that some deficiencies already have been corrected, he said.
   While scrutiny in many patient cases fell on Giuffre, many of
the other problems involved the board of directors, according to
Froseth.
   Under an agreement Giuffre and state officials signed Thursday,
Froseth said Health Department officials expect Giuffre's entire
board of directors to leave immediately. The 15-member board will
be replaced by May 25, Froseth said.
   But Peter D. Carlino, the board's chairman told The Philadelphia
Inquirer Thursday night that the board had agreed only to
``reorganize'' and that some members could remain. He said no
decision had been made yet on whether Giuffre would remain.
   Froseth said the order bans Giuffre and the two other doctors
comprising Allied Surgical Associates _ his daughter, Dr. Adrienne
Giuffre, and Dr. Lee Weissman _ from participation or involvement
in administration, patient care, consultation or other services
until the state has determined that all questions regarding the
group's activities and conduct have been resolved.
   The order allows the hospital's clinic and the drug and alcohol
in-patient services to continue operating. It closes all in-patient
acute care, including surgical services, the emergency room and the
podiatric clinic. Patients already at the hospital, which treats
some of the city's poorest residents, will continue receiving
treatment, Froseth said.
   The hospital's status as a Medicare treatment center also has
been jeopardized, the state said.
</TEXT>
