<2ND_LINE>PM-Friday The 13th, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0409,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Friday The 13th Or Not, Many Gamblers Are Superstitious</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, ``The study xxx, with two grafs to CORRECT
that drops were NOT for just one day and show that study projected
daily results over a full year</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For every superstitious gambler who
plans to avoid casinos on Friday the 13th, it seems just as many
believe they'll hit the jackpot today.
   ``On Friday the 13th, we expect weird players. They get more
excitable,'' said casino pit boss Margaret Miller, who supervises
gambling tables. ``We just hope it's not a full moon on top of
that.''
   But if the portents are unclear for casino gamblers, stock
market players might want to note a University of Miami study that
says the ill-starred day often does bring them bad luck.
   The study, released Thursday by Professors Robert Kolb and
Ricardo Rodriguez, showed that stocks over a 23-year period dropped
on Fridays the 13th at an average annualized rate of 24.5 percent.
That, the professors said, is how much the market would drop in a
year if it dropped as much every day as it did on the unlucky
Fridays.
   The study also showed that on all other Fridays, stocks rose at
an annualized average rate of 27.9 percent.
   The study examined all trading days from 1962-1985, the school
said.
   Most casino employees say Friday will be like any other day
because gamblers routinely do quirky things in pursuit of the big
win.
   Take, for instance, Asian players who ask dealers to remove jade
jewelry.
   ``They believe it brings good luck to those who wear it,'' said
floor person Bill Jarrett, who oversees dealers, monitors betting
and caters to gamblers who bet large sums of money.
   Italian gamblers often sprinkle salt on the table's green felt,
supposedly to ward off evil spirits, said floor person Guy Brady.
   ``You don't say anything and just clean it up later,'' Brady
said.
   One dealer recalled a man who wouldn't settle for just a
rabbit's foot and hid a live rabbit in a paper bag.
   ``Sometimes people rub your hand or touch your arm for good
luck,'' said dealer Jeanne Vercio. Other players, she said, put a
variety of lucky charms on tables, including small plastic
leprechauns, coins and shamrocks.
   Some players place a rosary or place voodoo dolls on their
cards, dealers say.
   Floor person Loretta Sutton said some gamblers get upset if a
dealer changes the colors of their chips to advance them to a
higher denomination.
   ``And a lot of players also don't like pregnant dealers,'' she
said. ``They think the house will win all the time'' because a
pregnant woman is lucky.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880513-0106 </DOCNO>
