<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--FloodInsurance     05-13 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Flood Insurance,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flood Insurance Expanded, But Rules Change June 1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal flood insurance program has been
expanded, but coastal residents who want full protection may need
to act before June 1.
   Under the new regulations, insurance coverage will be extended
to coastal buildings subject to ``imminent collapse or subsidence''
as a result of erosion.
   Coverage would provide funds to either relocate or demolish the
structure in imminent danger. Previously, insurance coverage
extended only after damage had occurred.
   However, to obtain this protection the insurance must be in
place by June 1, according to the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, which oversees the flood insurance programs.
   After that date protection for ``imminent'' collapse will be
available only after insurance has been in place for two years, or
for the full time of ownership if that is less than two years, FEMA
said.
   While FEMA supervises the program, the actual insurance policies
are sold through private local insurance brokers.
</TEXT>
