<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Church     05-13 0617</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Church,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Demands New Policy In Letter To Communist Premier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Czechoslovakia's Roman
Catholic Church has written an unusually tough letter to the
Communist premier saying church-state relations are at the crisis
point and that government policy must be changed.
   In the letter, dated April 23 and made available this week to
emigres in Vienna, Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek told Premier Lubomir
Strougal that police force used to break up a peaceful
demonstration in Bratislava in March showed a new policy of
dialogue is needed.
   ``It has become clear that the contacts between the state and
the church have reached a crisis,'' the letter said. A copy was
obtained by The Associated Press.
   ``The policy towards the church to date can now only be
continued at the price of using force,'' the 88-year-old primate
wrote. ``Through force, the crisis will not be solved, but deepened.
   ``Catholics are conscious of their rights, they will demand them
and are prepared to make sacrifices,'' the cardinal stressed.
   Relations between the Communist authorities and the Roman
Catholic Church in Czechoslovakia have been strained for years over
the Communists' refusal to allow any bishops to be appointed in the
last 15 years.
   Ten of the country's 13 sees are vacant _ a situation the
cardinal described as ``catastrophic'' _ and the three living
bishops are all over 75.
   Last month, the Vatican and Prague authorities reached agreement
on appointing two auxiliary bishops for the Prague archdiocese and
one titular bishop for Trnava in Slovakia. But these are not full
bishops.
   Increasing anger among believers prompted about 500,000 to sign
a petition organized by a Catholic lay activist last December to
demand more bishops, more priests and an end to harassment of
churchgoers.
   Tomasek gave unprecedented backing to the petition in a letter
to all Roman Catholics on Jan. 4. The state-run media responded
with strong attacks against the cardinal and the organizers of the
petition. Churchgoers in Bratislava and other cities reported
detentions, interrogations or other harassment of believers who
signed or collected signatures.
   About 2,000 Catholics gathered in downtown Bratislava, the
capital of Slovakia, on March 25 to demand religious freedom and
the appointment of more bishops. Police drove street-cleaning
trucks into the crowd to disperse the peaceful rally, then used
water cannons when some protesters didn't leave.
   Czechoslovak dissidents claimed that several demonstrators were
beaten by police.
   In his letter to Strougal, Tomasek stressed that the petition
fully complied with a Czechoslovak law guaranteeing citizens the
right to petition authorities and expect a reply.
   ``I welcomed and supported (this action) because my efforts of
many years at a normal life for the church and for believers had
yielded almost no results,'' Tomasek said.
   He criticized media attacks on the petition and its backers for
what he called a return to the vocabulary of the Stalinist 1950s,
when the Cardinal and thousands of other believers and clergy were
imprisoned.
   ``We demand a change in the position of the state towards the
church,'' Tomasek wrote. ``Let us not go further along the path of
confrontation, but move towards a dialogue.''
   A speech made by a Communist official in Brno last weekend,
however, indicated the party will continue to crack down on
believers.
   South Moravian party chief Vladimir Herman revealed that the
party's ruling Presidium is sending local party cells information
on ``the endeavor of some illegal structures to interfere with our
efforts'' in church-state relations.
   Herman did not specify what ``illegal structures'' he had in
mind.
   He charged these were part of an attempt to revert to a
non-Communist regime and to thwart the party's declared policy of
reform.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
