<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hostage-Buckley     05-13 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostage-Buckley,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CIA Official Killed as Hostage Honored at Arlington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly three years after he died as a hostage
in Lebanon, William Buckley, a former CIA official in Beirut, was
honored today in a military ceremony at Arlington National Cemetery.
   CIA Director William Webster joined the families of four
American hostages now held in Lebanon in remembering Buckley as a
man who loved his country.
   ``Bill did things that none of the rest of us would have done,''
Webster said. ``He lived by example.''
   Webster brought along a letter from President Reagan, which said
that Buckley ``loved the United States. ... He cherished liberty.''
   Buckley, Reagan noted, had been seized in March 1984, by
terrorists who ``tortured him and finally killed him.''
   Buckley died June 3, 1985, in captivity, but his body was never
recovered. He was 58.
   Buckley never married but the ceremony in a shaded valley of the
cemetery near Washington was attended by a longtime friend, Beverly
Surratt of North Reading, Mass., and two sisters, Maureen Moroney
of Salem, Mass., and Joyce Wing of Saugus, Mass., and their
families.
   One of the speakers at the 40-minute ceremony was Peggy Say,
sister of hostage Terry Anderson, who has been held in captivity
longer than any of the other nine Americans.
   Anderson, The Associated Press' chief Middle East correspondent,
was captured in March 1985.
   Mrs. Say, who returned from France after seeing former French
hostages on Thursday, said it was important for her to come to the
ceremony.
   Her voice choking with emotion, she said Buckley's family ``have
been there for me for three years.''
   The ceremony, known as a full honors ceremony, included the
drawing of a caisson, the playing of Taps and the firing of three
rifle shots.
</TEXT>
