<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--SharkScare 1stLd-Writethru a0563 05-13 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Shark Scare, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0563,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lifeguards Clear Water After 20-Foot Great White Spotted Off Beach</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lede, INSERTS new 5th graf with beach reopened.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swimmers and surfers were allowed
to return today to a five-mile stretch of beach evacuated when a
20-foot great white shark cruised within 20 yards of the shore,
lifeguards said.
   The shark was eventually frightened by a police helicopter sent
to track it and swam out to sea, authorities said.
   About 30 people were ordered from the water in this Orange
County beach town 40 miles southeast of Los Angeles after the
sighting Thursday afternoon, said lifeguard Eric Bauer.
   ``We have verified it as a great white, about a 20-footer,''
Bauer said. The water along the entire 5-mile length of Newport
Beach was evacuated, he said.
   The beach was reopened this morning, said lifeguard Don Stewart.
   The shark was first spotted by the crew of a boat operated by
Vessel Assist, which provides assistance to boaters at sea.
   Bauer said the appearance by a great white in Newport Beach
waters was unusual, noting that ``a couple of years ago we had a
15-foot hammerhead shark, but nothing since.''
</TEXT>
