<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Clash     05-13 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bangladesh-Clash,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>50 Jute Workers Injured In Clash With Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police opened fire and wounded at least
50 workers in a clash at a Chittagong jute mill, officials in the
port city said Friday.
   About 500 workers had occupied the privately owned Makbulur
Rahman jute mill for three days to demand bonuses to help pay for
an Islamic feast next week, according to officials who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   On Thursday, the mill owners asked riot police to disperse the
workers. When the police arrived, the workers hurled rocks and
homemade bombs, the officials said. Police then opened fire, the
officials said.
   They said the workers were demanding at least $10 apiece to
celebrate Eid al-Fitr, which marks the end of Ramadan, a monthlong
period of dawn-to-dusk fasting for Moslems.
   Jute is a strong fiber used for making burlap, sacks, mats and
rope.
</TEXT>
