<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Hostages     05-13 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Hostages,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine Says Hostages Have Been Moved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The magazine Ash-Shiraa said today that
foreign hostages were moved to a less vulnerable prison as
Iranian-backed fighters and pro-Syrian Shiite Moslem rivals clashed
in south Beirut.
   It said the blindfolded hostages were taken last Saturday to the
house of Sheik Ibrahim al-Amin, the spokesman for Hezbollah, or
Party of God, believed to be an umbrella group for kidnappers.
   Hezbollah is battling the Amal militia of Justice Minister Nabih
Berri for control of south Beirut's slums, where many of the 18
foreign hostages were believed to be held.
   Ash-Shiraa, a Beirut-based weekly, said the hostages were moved
to al-Amin's house in a relatively safer south Beirut area, but did
not name the neighborhood where the house is located.
   Shiite sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
al-Amin's house is in Manshieh Street in the Harek Hreik slum about
50 yards from the residence of Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah,
spiritual leader of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah.
   The weekly, which was the first to report the secret U.S. arms
sales to Iran in November 1986, did not say where in south Beirut
the hostages were imprisoned before they were moved.
   It said the hostages were blindfolded when they were taken to
al-Amin's house in several civlian cars with a heavy militia escort.
   The magazine cited no sources and the report could not be
independently verified. Al-Amin was not available for comment.
Hezbollah's press office in south Beirut's district of Bir el-Abed
did not answer telephone calls.
   Ash-Shiraa has good sources in the Iranian government and among
the Shiite community in Lebanon, but many of its recent reports on
foreign hostages have not panned out.
   Nine Americans are among the 18 foreign hostages in Lebanon. The
longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for
The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
