<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-Amerasians     05-13 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Amerasians,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 4,000 Amerasians Resettled In America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This week's departure from Vietnam of
22 Amerasians brought to more than 4,000 the number of Amerasians
who have left Vietnam for the United States, the U.S. Embassy in
Bangkok said Friday.
   The 22 children, including one American citizen, arrived in
Bangkok on a regularly scheduled flight Monday from Ho Chi Minh
City, formerly Saigon, an embassy news release said.
   They and 58 accompanying family members will spend a few days in
Bangkok before flying to the Bataan refugee processing center in
the Philippines for several months of language study and cultural
orientation.
   More than 4,000 Amerasians have left Vietnam under the U.S.
Orderly Departure Program since regular processing of Amerasians
began in September 1982, the release said. More than 6,000 family
members have accompanied them, it said.
   The United States and Vietnam have agreed in principle that all
of the remaining Amerasians _ estimated at 8,000-12,000 _ should go
to the United States as quickly as possible.
   The Amerasians were fathered by U.S. servicemen and civilians
during the U.S. intervention in the Vietnam War.
</TEXT>
