<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--TabathaFuneral     05-13 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Tabatha Funeral,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral Monday For Transplant Patient</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISONVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transplant patient Tabatha Foster will
be buried Monday following services at her family's church, a
funeral director said Friday.
   Willie Mae Elliot, owner of Elliot Mortuary, said the funeral
was scheduled at Oak Grove Baptist Church.
   Tabatha, the world's longest survivor of a five-organ
transplant, died Wednesday at Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh.
Doctors said an infection caused her heart, kidney and liver to
fail.
   The girl's mother, Sandra Foster, was choir director at Oak
Grove before leaving to work full-time raising money for medical
bills.
   The girl received a new liver, small intestines, pancreas and
parts of a stomach and colon during an experimental operation that
ended Nov. 1.
   Doctors had to remove almost all of her small bowel three days
after birth because of an intestinal deformity. She was placed on a
highly concentrated liquid diet, which damaged her liver.
</TEXT>
