<DOCNO> AP880513-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Elections     05-13 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Elections,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini Squelches Death Reports As Elections Wind Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos TEH1,TEH2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, ending
rumors that he had died, voted in the final round of Iran's
parliamentary elections Friday. Demonstrators burned effigies of
President Reagan and Saudi Arabia's King Fahd.
   Khomeini cast his vote in a special mobile polling booth outside
his heavily guarded residence in north Tehran's Jamaran suburb soon
after polls opened at 7 a.m.
   The revolutionary patriarch is 87 and rarely leaves his
residence and adjoining mosque. Iranian state-run television,
monitored in Cyprus, showed him casting his ballot.
   Hours earlier, rumors swept the Hong Kong stock market that
Khomeini had died.
   In the first round of voting April 8, 188 of the 270 seats in
the Majlis, or parliament, were elected. Friday's election was to
fill the other 82 electoral districts, including 16 of the 30 in
Tehran, where no candidate got a clear majority last month.
Candidates are elected to four-year terms.
   IRNA said final results would not be known until Tuesday.
   Among the 168 candidates fighting it out in Tehran and other
cities were President Ali Khamenei's brother Hadi, seeking
re-election in the northeastern city of Mashhad. He survived a
grenade attack by leftist guerrillas last year.
   Another was Habibollah Asgar-Owladi, an Islamic zealot jailed
for life during the reign of the late Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi
for involvement in the 1965 assassination of Prime Minister
Hasan-Ali Mansur.
   Asgar-Owladi was freed when Khomeini toppled the shah in 1979.
   IRNA said that Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, who
received more than 1.3 million votes in April, and other Khomeini
aides cast their votes in Jamaran after the bearded patriarch.
   President Khamenei and Prime Minister Hussein Musavi voted in
south Tehran mosques, which were used as polling stations, IRNA
said.
   They later joined big marches in the capital to mark Qods
(Jerusalem) Day, proclaimed by Khomeini in 1979 to protest Israel's
seizure of the Arab half of the holy city in 1967.
   IRNA reported that millions of men, women and children, chanting
``Death to Israel! Death to America!'' marched through Tehran and
other cities, carrying huge portraits of Khomeini and burning
effigies of Reagan and King Fahd.
   Saudi Arabia severed relations with Tehran last month, citing
``terrorism and subversion.''
   The Parliamentary election is the third since Khomeini's Islamic
revolution toppled the monarchy in 1979.
   The April 8 voting was held amid Iraqi missile and air attacks
on Iranian cities. But both sides in the 7{-year-old war have
observed a cease-fire in the so-called ``war of the cities'' since
April 21.
   Friday's voting took place amid Iran's growing isolation,
deepening economic troubles and major military setbacks in the war.
   These included the loss of the Faw peninsula in southern Iraq _
recaptured by the Iraqis April 18 after two years of Iranian
occupation _ and naval clashes the same day in which the U.S. Navy
sank or crippled six Iranian vessels.
   Radicals and Moslem extremists were expected to widen the
sizeable gains they made in April when several leading
conservatives lost their seats.
   The main election issues have been economic and social reform.
   The radicals seek centralized state control of the economy and a
broad spectrum of reforms.
   The cleric-led conservatives, who favor a strong private sector,
are supported by the ``Bazaaris,'' the weathy merchant class which
has survived the revolution.
   Philip Robbins, an Iran specialist with the Royal Institute of
International affairs in London, said in a telephone interview that
the new Majlis will be ``a far more radical body than it was
before, particularly on the important issue of economic policy.''
   Khomeini, who wants to see his revolution set on a firm course
before he dies, strengthened the radicals' hand before April's poll.
   He delivered a series of edicts widening state powers that
opened the way for reformist legislation vetoed by the 13-member
council and last year disbanded the Islamic Republic Party, the
conservatives' main power base.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
