<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shevardnadze Bjt   05-13 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shevardnadze, Bjt,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Foreign Minister Optimistic on Strategic Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet foreign minister expressed optimism
Friday that ``substantial results'' in reducing long-range nuclear
weapons will be achieved at the superpower summit, the official
East German news agency reported.
   Eduard A. Shevardnadze briefed President Erich Honecker and the
other Warsaw Pact foreign ministers on two days of talks in Geneva
with Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   On Thursday, he and Shultz said it would not be possible for
President Reagan and Mikhail S. Gorbachev to sign a treaty on
long-range, or strategic, arms at the summit scheduled for May
29-June 2 in Moscow.
   The news agency, ADN, said: ``Eduard Shevardnadze came away
(from Geneva) with the impression that progress and substantial
results can be made at the Moscow summit in all areas that have
been under discussion.''
   It said Shevardnadze told Honecker ``there is the determination
on both sides to cut in half the number of strategic nuclear
weapons, as has been agreed in principle. Intensive work is being
done in this regard.''
   ADN added that Shevardnadze told Honecker the Kremlin is aware
that ``results are expected from the Moscow summit which would give
the process of disarmament and detente a new impulse.'' It did not
elaborate.
   Shevardnadze met with Honecker soon after his arrival, then
briefed the foreign ministers.
   A communique issued by the ministers said they ``gave their full
support to the Soviet Union's efforts in negotiations with the
United States, and voiced hope that the talks between Gorbachev and
Reagan will result in the halving of strategic offensive weapons
and achieve results in other disarmament areas.''
   After the Geneva talks, Shultz said he and Shevardnadze resolved
a dispute over verification procedures for a treaty eliminating
intermediate-range nuclear missiles. It was signed in December but
has yet to be ratified by the Senate.
   Foreign Minister Ioan Totu of Romania did not attend the
briefing, an East German Foreign Ministry spokesman said, adding:
``I don't know why he decided not to come.'' Romania was
represented by its ambassador, Gheorge Caranfil.
   Shultz met with NATO foreign ministers Friday in Brussels.
   He told the allied officials, in a closed meeting at North
Atlantic Treaty Organization headquarters, that there was no chance
of the superpowers concluding before the Moscow summit a treaty
cutting long-range missiles by half.
   David Mellor, a British minister of state, said Shultz had given
NATO allies ``no further insights'' into how long it might take to
wrap up such an agreement.
</TEXT>
