<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HostageOfficer 6thLd-Writethru a0655 05-13 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostage Officer, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0655,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Officer Escapes From Captors, Men Found Dead
^Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Police later ...,' with 2 grafs to add police
spokesman saying men outside in parking lot did not fire weapons.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD M. GREEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer held hostage in a motel
room by two robbery suspects escaped unharmed today after seizing a
gun and shooting at least one of his captors, police said.
   Both suspects were later found dead in the room, said police
spokesman Henry Groepper.
   The hostage officer, Larry Strayer, fired about five shots
inside the room before fleeing shortly before 4 a.m., eight hours
after the hostage incident began, said Groepper. Strayer was
investigating a supermarket robbery when he was taken captive,
police said.
   About two hours later, with the men still holed up in the room,
five gunshots were heard. Police drove an armored truck into the
motel courtyard, and more gunfire followed.
   Police later fired tear gas into the motel room, but the men did
not emerge, Groepper said. When police broke down the door and
entered the room, they found the men's bodies.
   Groepper said he didn't know whether the men had died from
gunshot wounds nor did he know whether the deaths were
self-inflicted. There was no exchange of shots between the men and
police stationed outside the room in the motel's parking lot, who
only fired the tear gas, he said.
   Authorities had blocked off all lanes of Interstate 5 and Barbur
Boulevard, a major roadway, causing a massive traffic tieup several
miles southwest of downtown Portland during the morning rush hour.
   The two men had threatened to kill the officer unless
authorities met their demands for drugs and safe passage out of the
motel. Groepper said no drugs were given the men.
   Strayer said over his radio while he was held hostage that the
suspects had threatened to kill him.
   ``Please get me out of here,'' he said during the standoff.
``They indicated this is the last time I can talk on the radio. If
anybody rushes the door I'm dead.''
   Late-night television news reports, broadcast live from a nearby
parking lot, irritated the suspects, and Groepper asked television
reporters to play down the story.
   With the officer inside acting as an intermediary, police
negotiators talked with the suspects on the telephone and over the
police radio.``On the radio he sounds like he's doing real well,''
Groepper said.
   Police said the gunmen were asking for Dilaudid, a form of
morphine used in cough syrup.
   Strayer was taken hostage while he was investigating a robbery
that occurred about 7 p.m. at a Safeway store.
   About an hour after the robbery, the officer was checking a tip
that two suspicious men were staying at the nearby Portland Rose
Motel. He was admitted to a room at the motel by one man.
   Groepper said other officers brought witnesses from the store
robbery who identified the man as a suspect, but as the officers
were handcuffing the suspect, another man emerged from the bathroom
and pointed at gun at police.
   ``Don't anyone do anything foolish,'' Groepper quoted the man as
saying.
   He said the gunman took Strayer hostage and forced the others
out of the motel room.
   The suspects set one deadline for delivery of the drugs they
requested, but it passed at about 9:15 p.m. and they continued
negotiating with police, Groepper said.
</TEXT>
