<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AN-NorthKorea-Japan     05-13 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AN-North Korea-Japan,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Calls Japanese Allegations Groundless Slander</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea's official news agency on Friday denied
Japanese allegations that Pyongyang helped a Japanese terrorist
return to Japan.
   ``The Japanese authorities are hurling groundless slanders at
our republic,'' the Korean Central News Agency said,
   Japanese police arrested Yasuhiro Shibata, 34, near his Tokyo
apartment last Friday after identifying him as one of nine alleged
Red Army members who commandeered a Japan Air Lines Boeing 727 to
North Korea with 129 people aboard in 1970.
   After the hijacking, the nine stayed in North Korea, and
Japanese police and Foreign Ministry officials said Shibata's
return could only have taken place with the approval of the North
Korean government.
   ``It is a well known fact that several Japanese youths belonging
to the Red Army group came to our country in the incident of the
JAL plane,'' the news agency said in a report monitored in Tokyo.
   ``As they entered the territory of our country, the (North
Korean) government only provided them conveniences for their life
and treated them as foreigners from the humanitarian stand,'' the
news agency reported.
   ``As for their going outside the (North Korean) boundary, we did
not mind where they went, regarding it as their right proceeding
from their free will.''
   The news agency charged the Japanese government is trying to
shift the responsibility for the hijacking to North Korea, even
though ``the Japanese government is to blame.''
   It also said Shibata may have wanted to return to Japan because
he was homesick.
</TEXT>
