<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Regan-Brady 1stLd-Writethru a0640 05-13 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Regan-Brady, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0640,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Regan Says He Passed False Report That Brady Died in Reagan
Shooting</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT that Hinckley found innocent by
reason of insanity and changes middle initial to W sted T</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House chief of staff Donald T.
Regan says that in the confusion following the 1981 assassination
attempt on President Reagan he erroneously told Cabinet members
that presidential press secretary James Brady had died.
   The president, Brady, Secret Service agent Timothy J. McCarthy
and a Washington police officer, Thomas K. Delahanty, were wounded
in the assassination attempt outside the Washington Hilton.
   John W. Hinckley Jr. was arrested but was found innocent by
reason of insanity. He is in St. Elizabeths Hospital, a mental
institution in Washington.
   There were erroneous news reports at the time that Brady had
died.
   In his new book, ``For the Record: From Wall Street to
Washington,'' Regan, who was secretary of the treasury at the time
of the attempt on Reagan's life, included what he said were notes
that he made a few days after the March 30, 1981, shooting.
   He said in the notes that he received information from the
Secret Service, which is part of the Treasury Department, and
relayed it to other members of the Cabinet gathered in the White
House Situation Room.
   ``An unfortunate message came to me from the Secret Service, and
it caused confusion and consternation,'' Regan said. ``At the end
of a message describing the president's condition, someone had
added the words `Brady died.' I announced this sad news to a
stunned group.''
   He said Richard Allen, the president's national security
adviser, asked for a moment of silent prayer.
   ``Apparently someone relayed this information to the group at
the hospital and we got word back that it was not true,'' Regan
said.
   In his book, ``Speaking Out: Inside the Reagan White House,''
former presidential spokesman Larry Speakes gives substantially the
same account and adds that Regan relayed the word to Howard Baker,
then the Senate majority leader and now the White House chief of
staff, at his Senate office.
</TEXT>
