<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewAge     05-13 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Age,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Channelers, Astrologers and UFO Buffs Gather for Whole Life Expo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astrologers, UFO buffs, health
enthusiasts and other assorted New Age advocates, apparently
undaunted that the calendar read Friday the 13th, converged for the
Whole Life Expo.
   About 40,000 people were expected at the Pasadena Convention
Center for the three-day event, featuring 200 speakers who will wax
loquacious on such topics as ``The Magic World of Crystals,'' ``The
Feminine Warrior: Embracing the Goddess,'' ``Channeling: A New Way
of Looking at Reality'' and ``Tibetan Gongs, Singing Bowls &
Voices.'' A panel discussion on UFOs also is scheduled.
   Convention-goers can snack on blue-green algae, tofu shakes and
meatless hot dogs as they stroll among exhibits on spiritual
healing, numerology, fire-walking and colon cleansing.
   Celebrity guests include Michelle Phillips, Susan Strasberg and
Timothy Leary.
   Uri Geller, the psychic guru best known for his purported
ability to twist spoons mentally, will take the stage, as will
Elizabeth Clare Prophet, a Montana-based religious group's leader
who will lecture on the lost years of Jesus.
   The expo, first held in 1978, is sponsored by tofu maker
Mori-Nu, a company called Naked Juice and Whole Life Times magazine.
   ``It's a show about health and awareness,'' said Brian Duggan,
president of Teamwork Promotions, the concern managing the Whole
Life Expo. ``Our goal is to provide a variety of viewpoints and
choices. There seems to be a willingness for more people to try
this. I think people want more fulfillment in their lives.
   ``The fact that so many people are interested and ga-ga over
Nancy Reagan and astrology shows just what an interest there is in
this.''
   He said more people are attending the expo each year. And he
pointed to the expo's more conventional seminars on AIDS awareness,
health insurance, clean water processing and business.
   ``You can find places in any city where you can buy health foods
and buy New Age music,'' Duggan said. ``It's not just a
California-weirdo phenomenon. It's part of mainstream society.''
</TEXT>
