<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Sikhs Bjt   05-13 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs, Bjt,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Sharpshooters Kill Five in Golden Temple Complex</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police sharpshooters firing from high
vantage points killed five Sikh militants inside the Golden Temple
compound Friday and tightened their siege, taking over about
one-third of the sacred complex.
   About 100 extremists in the temple grounds, the holiest shrine
of Sikhism, rejected a government demand for surrender.
   Twenty-seven people, including at least five civilians, have
been killed since Monday, when 2,500 police and paramilitary
troopers surrounded the Golden Temple and its walled compound.
   The gunmen inside are part of a separatist movement that has
waged a terror campaign since 1982 seeking an independent Sikh
homeland in Punjab, a rich northern agricultural state where the
sect has a majority. Thousands of people have been killed.
   K.P.S. Gill, police chief of Amritsar, said government forces
took control of a narrow road that runs through the complex and
seized the temple offices and hostel. The complex covers the
equivalent of about five city blocks.
   The temple offices and hostel are on one side of the road and
the temple, its residential quarters and the dining hall are on the
other.
   Gill said police and troopers controlled ``all dominant
features'' around the compound, including a 150-foot water tower
with a sweeping view over the walls, which are 20 feet high.
   No food or people have been allowed into the temple since the
siege began, and the militants have let no one leave since Tuesday,
when about 800 pilgrims were evacuated.
   Some civilians remained in the compound Friday but no estimate
of their number was available.
   Government forces and the gunmen inside exchanged intermittent
fire during the day, then police announced over a loudspeaker at 4
p.m. that they would stop shooting so women and children could come
out.
   Sarabjeet Singh, deputy police commissioner, said the response
was four shots, apparently fired into the air. He said a Sikh
gunman was guarding the main gate to keep anyone from leaving.
   The siege began Monday after Sikhs inside shot at paramilitary
forces outside the complex, wounding five officers. The
400-year-old Golden Temple is the political and military center of
the Sikh militants.
   Killings by the separatists have increased dramatically in
recent months. At least 955 people have been killed in Punjab so
far this year compared with 1,032 in all of 1987.
   If the government storms the Golden Temple, it risks the wrath
of many moderate Sikhs who would consider the action a desecration
of holy ground.
   Prime Minister Indira Gandhi sent soldiers into the temple in
1984 to dislodge militants, and about 1,200 people, most of them
Sikhs, were killed. Five months later Mrs. Gandhi was assassinated
by her own Sikh bodyguards.
   On Friday, at least three companies of Black Cat commandos from
the National Security Guard joined police and paramilitary troopers
at the temple, a police officer reported.
   He said the three companies, totaling about 270 men, had
submachine guns and the kind of drills used to bore through walls.
Some had rifles equipped with night-vision scopes, he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Soon after midnight, half a dozen Sikhs tried to shoot their way
out of the temple complex, according to Gill, the police chief. He
said one was killed, two escaped and the others apparently
retreated inside.
   How long the militants' ammunition and food would last was not
known, but they keep large supplies of both on the grounds.
   Reporters allowed into the compound Wednesday saw many
containers of water. The temple also is surrounded by a vast pool
in which pilgrims immerse themselves.
   Sikhs, whose men can be recognized by their turbans and beards,
make up only 2 percent of India's 800 million people and Punjab is
the only state with a Sikh majority.
   They claim discrimination by Hindus, who account for 82 percent
of the population. Sikhism was founded 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
