<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-13 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friday the 13th did not begin well for Gov.
Ted Schwinden. His first appointment was with a goat.
   The animal's presence in the gubernatorial office launched the
annual fund-raising project by Helena's Big Brothers and Sisters
program.
   The goat, dubbed ``Half-Pint'' and accompanied by his own
paper-lined box to prevent public indiscretions, was sent to
Schwinden by Jonas Rosenthal, a former aide and one-time director
of Big Brothers and Sisters in Bozeman.
   As with each recipient of the goat throughout the day, Schwinden
had two choices _ either baby-sit the unpredictable animal for an
hour or offer a $10 contribution to send him to someone else.
   Schwinden wasted little time in choosing Half-Pint's destination
_ Highway Department Director Gary Wicks, who is known as a
jokester himself.
   ``I'd love watching dust shake lose from Wicks' $10,'' Schwinden
said gleefully. ``Wicks doesn't like to pay for anything.''
   A certificate sent along with the goat calls for the sender to
identify himself from several categories: friend, associate,
employee, archrival or detested enemy. Schwinden settled on ``none
of the above'' and bid Half-Pint goodbye.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Kermit and Beatrice Shelton Friday the
13th is a lucky day and always has been.
   The Sheltons were both born on Friday the 13th _ he in March
1914 and she in April 1917. They got married on Friday the 13th in
May 1938. And 50 years later, they celebrated their golden wedding
anniversary on Friday the 13th.
   ``I never thought about the 50th anniversary being on a Friday
the 13th,'' said Shelton, a retired government employee who
continues to work in real estate.
   ``I never thought about being here for the 50th,'' he admitted.
   The couple have always gone out of their way to flout
superstition.
   There were 13 in their wedding party, and each year they have
tried to get the number 13 included in their automobile license
plates. But they balked at friends' suggestion that they have 13
children.
   ``I had one and she's worth 13,'' said Mrs. Shelton.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A USA Today reporter who once described
Lincoln as a polyester-loving town was given a grand tour of the
capital that left her feeling, in her words, ``polysaturated.''
   Karen S. Peterson, in a May 3 article in her newspaper, called
Lincoln ``the edge of nowhere, a city still comfortable with
fulsome waistlines and polyester.''
   That struck a chord with two radio personalities and Rita
Bennett of the city's visitor and convention bureau, who organized
a drive to collect polyester clothing to send to the reporter.
Things snowballed, and 10,000 pounds of polyester clothing were
collected in two days.
   Peterson was invited to Lincoln from her home base in Arlington,
Va., and on Thursday she was serenaded at lunch at the Cornhusker
by Attorney General Bob Spire, engineered the train at the
Children's Zoo, and received an admiralship in the Nebraska Navy by
Bill Orr, husband of the governor.
   Peterson, interviewed by a flock of reporters, said she meant no
harm by her sentence and was just trying to set the scene on a
story about Cliff Hillegass. The founder of Cliffs Notes prefers to
run his publishing dynasty from Lincoln rather than New York City.
   Although the bales of polyester clothing will be donated to
charity, Peterson retained one souvenir _ a neon green, textured
polyester double-knit vest with metal buttons.
   ``It's a classic,'' she said.
</TEXT>
