<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-ArmsTreaty 1stLd-Writethru a0421 05-13 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0421,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders voiced optimism today that the
anti-cheating arms control bargain struck by U.S. and Soviet
negotiators at Geneva will remove the final roadblock delaying
debate and ratification of the medium-range missile treaty.
   Senate Majority leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said debate
could begin early next week, after a trio of Senate committees
examine the agreements and formally approve them.
   ``They are the experts in their fields,'' Byrd said.
   Commenting after a 90-minute luncheon briefing by National
Security Adviser Colin Powell, Byrd said Senate leaders were told
the agreement was significant and ``enhances the national security
of this country.''
   ``The briefing was positive and good,'' Byrd said.
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas said it is clear
Byrd's decision last week to postpone action on the treaty while
negotiators addressed concerns that the Soviets were backing away
from effective implementation of inspection provisions ``played a
very constructive role.''
   ``It did make a difference,'' Dole said.
   Several other senators who attended the briefing also said the
results of the Geneva talks between Secretary of State George P.
Shultz and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze do seem
positive and constructive.
   ``Im optimistic we can move ahead,'' said Sen. Claiborne Pell,
D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
   ``I think at this moment there is more optimism for the passage
of this treaty than at at any other time during this long
process,'' said Sen. John Warner, R-Va., the ranking GOP member of
the Senate Armed Services Committee.
   Warner said that it appears the Soviets agreed to change their
position on all issues raised by the U.S. side.
   ``I'm confident my colleagues on Monday will come to a similar
conclusion,'' Warner said.
   Some senators said there is now at least a possibility that the
Senate will consent to the ratification of the treaty by the time
President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev convene
their Moscow summit on May 29.
   Since most vote counts show overwhelming Senate support for the
pact, the leading question is whether Reagan will have a ratified
treaty in hand as incentive for the two superpowers to make further
progress on arms reduction.
   Byrd said the treaty is too important to national security for
either him or the Senate to be ``driven by artificial, automatic,
arbitrary calendar deadlines.''
   Byrd said he will try to push the treaty through the Senate as
quickly as possible once debate opens but will not guarantee that
can be done before the summit.
   He said he will not permit debate to begin until the on-site
inspection plan worked out in Geneva is examined and approved by
the Foreign Relations, Armed Services and Intelligence committees.
   ``We were told all the I's were dotted and all the T's were
crossed,'' Byrd said of the Reagan administration's position on the
treaty before the latest furor.
   ``It was through the examination of these committees that it was
found that this was not the case,'' he said.
   ``If we make a mistake in this treaty and we find we have been
hoodwinked or outsmarted, then you can kiss the next arms treaty
goodbye,'' Byrd said. ``Let's do this thing right.''
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Foreign Relations
Committee, said Shultz will testify before that panel Monday
afternoon with the Senate's bipartisan leadership and the chairmen
and ranking GOP members of the two other committees invited to
participate.
   Pell said that if no further snags are uncovered, Senate debate
could open Tuesday.
   Earlier this week, Byrd postponed action on the new treaty until
Shultz and Shevardnadze resolved a serious dispute over the
implementation of anti-cheating provisions.
   The dispute centered on what U.S. inspectors will be permitted
to see and do as they try to learn whether the Soviets live up to
the requirements of the treaty to eliminate all their medium-range
missiles.
</TEXT>
