<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   05-13 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syrian Troops Clash With Hezbollah; Magazine Reports Hostages
Moved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian troops clashed with Iranian-backed
fundamentalists on Beirut's airport highway Friday in the first
Syrian intervention in the battle over south Beirut. Six people
were reported killed.
   The Ash-Shiraa magazine said the Iranian-backed guerrillas have
spirited foreign hostages, who are believed held in the slums of
south Beirut, from one hiding place to another to prevent their
liberation.
   The fight between the Syrian troops and Hezbollah guerrillas
came as Hezbollah pushed Syrian-backed Amal fighters out of one
slum neighborhood, police said.
   Hezbollah guerrillas, moving behind a heavy barrage of
howitzers, fought deep into the Raml el-Ali section and seized the
Mosque of the Great Prophet from Amal troops, a police spokesman
said.
   The rival militias battled with tanks, mortars and
rocket-propelled grenades over the area, which abuts the main
Beirut airport highway.
   Hezbollah's victory brought portions of the airport and the
airport highway, controlled by the Syrian army, within the army's
firing range, said the spokesman, who under standing rules cannot
be named.
   Shortly thereafter, a Hezbollah sniper killed an aide of a
senior Syrian officer on the highway.
   ``A group of Hezbollah fighters clad in Iranian flags over their
battle fatigues later attempted to cross the highway. The Syrians
opened fire and killed five Hezbollahis,'' the spokesman said.
   All roads to the airport were closed, but planes continued to
land and take off even though stray bullets whizzed over the
runways and tarmac.
   ``We shall wipe out any attempt to re-establish any militia
presence in any Syrian-policed territory and shall crush any
encroachment on our lines or soldiers,'' said Brig. Gen. Ali
Hammoud, commander of the Syrian contingent.
   The Syrians maintain a 7,500-strong contingent in Moslem west
Beirut. Until Friday, they had stayed out of the Hezbollah-Amal
confrontation, but the warned they would not tolerate any attack
against them.
   Police said Amal's positions in the slums were ``rapidly falling
one after another'' into Hezbollah's hands after the fighting broke
out at 1 p.m.
   In all, police said 10 people were killed and 18 wounded in
Friday's fighting, which ended a 36-hour truce, one of several
cease-fires brokered by Syria and Iran. The figure included those
killed in the Syrian-Hezbollah battle.
   The overall toll was 198 killed and 561 wounded since the
confrontation for control of the 16-square-mile shantytown began
last Friday.
   Lebanon's Ash-Shiraa magazine said the blindfolded foreign
hostages were taken last Saturday to the house of Sheik Ibrahim
al-Amin, the spokesman for Hezbollah, which is believed to hold
most of the 18 hostages _ including nine Americans _ missing in
Beirut.
   Ash-Shiraa, a Beirut-based weekly, said the hostages were moved
to al-Amin's house in a relatively safer south Beirut area, but it
did not name the neighborhood where the house is located.
   Shiite sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
al-Amin's house is about 50 yards from the residence of Sheik
Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, Hezbollah's spiritual leader.
   The weekly, which was the first to report the secret U.S. arms
sales to Iran in November 1986, cited no sources, and the report
could not be independently verified.
   Al-Amin was not available for comment. Hezbollah's press office
in south Beirut's district of Bir el-Abed did not answer telephone
calls.
   Ash-Shiraa has good sources in the Iranian government and among
the Shiite community in Lebanon, but many of its recent reports on
foreign hostages have not panned out.
   Amal, Arabic for hope, accused Hezbollah of using the four-day
truce, called by presidents Hafez Assad of Syria and Ali Khamenei
of Iran, to prepare for the latest onslaught.
   Police said the personal representatives of Assad and Khamenei,
Syrian Brig. Gen. Ali Hammoud and Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister
Hussein Sheikholeslam, were holding talks with delegates from the
two warring factions at the Iranian Embassy.
   Hezbollah's fighters won control of 70 percent of the slums
before the latest cease-fire was proclaimed Wednesday. Police said
Friday's drive left only the Shiyah district under Amal's control.
   Meanwhile, Christian militia leader Samir Geagea, a pro-Israeli
foe of Syria, was reported Friday to have escaped an attempted
assassination by a car bomb in Lebanon's Christian heartland north
of Beirut.
   The Christian-controlled Voice of Lebanon radio station said the
bomb exploded as a Lebanese Forces militia motorcade was passing
through the tiny village of Mastita near the ancient port of Byblos
at 10 p.m. Tuesday.
   It said Geagea, who commands the 4,000-strong Lebanese Forces,
the Christians' main paramilitary machine, was supposed to be
traveling in the six-vehicle motorcade but wasn't.
   Police confirmed that a car packed with 330 pounds of TNT
exploded in Mastita, 20 miles north of Beirut, wounding five people.
</TEXT>
