<2ND_LINE>AM-Bankston,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>17-Year-Old Given Five Life Sentences for Georgia Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boy was sentenced on his 17th birthday to
five consecutive life terms in prison after pleading guilty but
mentally ill to five murders.
   Clinton Bankston Jr. will be eligible for parole in 25 years,
Clarke County District Attorney Harry Gordon said Thursday.
   Bankston told Clarke County Superior Judge Joseph Gaines: ``I
want to tell you, judge, I'm sorry I killed those people.''
   Bankston laughed loudly as he was escorted from the courtroom.
His attorney, Edward Tolley, said the laugh under stress is
symptomatic of his client's mental illness.
   Bankston pleaded in the April 1987 stabbing deaths of retired
University of Georgia professors Glenn and Rachel Sutton in their
home and the August hatchet slayings of Sally Nathanson, 59, her
daughter, Helen, 22, and Mrs. Nathanson's sister, Ann Orr Morris,
63.
   Bankston was 15 when the Suttons were killed and 16 at the time
of the other murders.
   Tolley said he decided to enter the plea because evidence of
both guilt and mental illness were overwhelming and because of a
recent Georgia Supreme Court decision barring execution of people
who were under age 17 when they committed their crimes.
</TEXT>
