<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1547EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Ireland     05-13 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Ireland,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ireland to Resume Extraditing Terrorists to Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ireland has agreed to resume extraditing terror
suspects to Britain after a five-month disagreement over
procedures, the Attorney General's Office said Friday.
   The governments long have been at odds over the Irish Republic's
reluctance to extradite people sought for trial in connection with
the Irish Republican Army's bloody campaign to drive the British
from Northern Ireland.
   Britain has refused to abide by an Irish extradition law that
took effect Dec. 1. It requires London to provide detailed
evidence, including names of witnesses, to support warrants and
empowers the Irish attorney general, currently John Murray, to pass
on all extraditions.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher called the legislation a ``step
backward'' that would make it harder for Britain to secure
extradition of IRA suspects.
   Under new arrangements, the British attorney general, Sir
Patrick Mayhew, will send a summary of evidence and his Irish
counterpart will decide ``on a case-by-case basis'' whether
suspects should be arrested, Mayhew's office said in a statement.
   Ireland's government declined comment on the new procedures,
which news reports said were agreed upon earlier this week when
Mayhew and Murray met in Dublin.
   Mayhew's office said: ``The Irish attorney general has modified
certain stipulations which in the United Kingdom's view went beyond
the requirements of the legislation.
   ``The Irish have accepted the validity of British concerns that
there must be no prejudice to the administration of justice in any
eventual proceedings in the United Kingdom on the return of the
fugitives.
   ``We understand that the Irish attorney general has already
authorized the backing of warrants in one particular case under the
new procedure.''
   Relations between the governments have deteriorated in recent
months because of several disputes over the quality of British
justice.
   Those include the British Appeal Court's refusal to grant a
retrial to six Irishmen serving life sentences for twin bomb
attacks that killed 21 people in 1974. The six claim they were
convicted on the basis of faulty forensic evidence and confessions
that they claim were beaten out of them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
