<2ND_LINE>AM-Small Kidnapping,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Selected To Hear Small Kidnap-Slaying Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury was seated Friday to hear the trial
of a man charged in the kidnapping and death of a businessman who
was buried alive in a box.
   Daniel J. Edwards, 31, is charged with kidnap and murder in the
death of Stephen Small, 40, of Kankakee who was abducted Sept. 2.
Small's abductors demanded $1 million ransom, but the family never
received clear instructions for delivery of the money and he
suffocated before he could be found.
   Edwards and Nancy D. Rish, 26, who lived together in
Bourbonnais, were arrested two days after the abduction and hours
before police found Small's body in woods.
   The Illinois attorney general's office, which is prosecuting the
case, has said it plans to seek the death penalty for Edwards.
   The jury and two alternates were selected from a pool of 53
people, who were questioned about their knowledge of the case and
their views on the death penalty.
   Kankakee County Circuit Judge John Michala was to hear further
motions in the case Friday afternoon. Opening statements were
scheduled Monday in Kankakee.
   Jurors were chosen from Winnebago County to avoid possible
prejudice. Michala planned to sequester the jury in Kankakee.
   Four jurors were chosen Thursday and the rest Friday.
   The body of Small, great-grandson of former Illinois Gov. Len
Small and a member of a family with major media holdings, was found
in a homemade box buried in 3 feet of sand. The box was equipped
with a jug of water, candy bars and an unconnected battery-powered
light.
   Ms. Rish also was charged with murder and kidnapping. No trial
date has been set for her.
</TEXT>
