<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SummitJudge     05-13 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit Judge,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boston Judge Could Be Summit Topic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Boston Housing Court judge may become a topic of
conversation at this month's U.S.-Soviet summit because a
defendant's wife wrote to Soviet officials that the judge had
treated her husband unfairly.
   Judge George E. Daher got a call this week from the State
Department's Human Rights Bureau asking for details of a case in
which he jailed James Lynch, a Boston man who reportedly cursed him
and charged the bench.
   The man's wife, Virginia, wrote to the Soviet Embassy in
Washington complaining that his rights had been violated.
   U.S. officials fear the letter could end up on the agenda of the
Moscow summit, Daher said Thursday.
   ``I can't believe they will raise this as a civil liberties
issue,'' Samuel Kreiter, the Human Rights Bureau staff member who
talked to Daher, said. ``If it does come up, it won't last very
long. We have evidence she and her husband were afforded due
process.''
   Daher said Lynch was not denied his rights.
   ``Any time the Russians want to play back the tapes (of the
hearing), we'll gladly play them back,'' he said. ``His due process
rights were protected.
   ``I'm so proud of our judicial system. We can stand the scrutiny
from the Russians or Martians or anyone. I am sure the Russians can
learn from it,'' Daher said.
   Lynch appeared before Daher last October after officials
complained he was violating city codes by operating an auto repair
shop out of a residential garage.
   Daher dismissed the case after the city dropped the complaint,
but court records indicate Lynch began arguing with police officers
as he was walking out of court.
   Daher reprimanded him, and Lynch swore at him and charged the
bench, according to the records.
   Daher ordered Lynch to undergo psychiatric evaluation, and when
he was found mentally competent, sentenced him to 90 days for
contempt of court.
   The judge freed Lynch for Christmas and canceled the rest of the
sentence.
   It was after Lynch was released that his wife wrote to the
Soviets.
   She was fired as a police officer in 1981 after being found
``unfit for duty,'' records show. She sued the city, contending she
had a nervous breakdown from being harassed by colleagues after
reporting three officers beat a handcuffed prisoner.
   She got a $93,000 settlement in court this year, but officials
said she had not picked up the check. She also was reinstated as an
officer but placed on disability leave.
   Last Dec. 27, Pravda, the Communist Party's daily newspaper,
published an article about Mrs. Lynch under the headline, ``Help
Virginia Lynch.''
   The newspaper said she was ``the victim of unjust repressions,''
and that police ``behaved themselves like gangsters'' for firing
her.
</TEXT>
