<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MathContest     05-13 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Math Contest,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Math Contest Winner Hardly Touches Pencil and Paper To Answer
Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrew Shultz, a 13-year-old Evanston, Ill.,
math whiz, hardly lifted a pencil Friday as he shut out the
competition and won the title of the nation's top grade school
``mathlete.''
   Shultz left rivals scratching their heads as he called out
answers while they were still jotting down the questions in the
final, frenetic rounds of a contest called Mathcounts.
   Seeded fifth, he made short work out of five contestants he
faced one-on-one by correctly answering 10 of 11 questions, doing
most of his calculations in his head.
   The only seventh-grader in the finals, Robert Kleinberg, 12, of
Iroquois Middle School in Wales Center, N.Y., captured second.
Daniel Hanish, 13, of Omaha, Neb., was third.
   Asked to explain his prowess at mental mathematics, Shultz said,
``I don't know. It just comes.''
   ``When I was 4, I couldn't write with pencil and paper,'' said
Shultz, an 8th grader at Haven Middle School in Evanston. ``My
writing's still pretty messy.''
   Some of that talent may be in the genes.
   His mother, who embarrassed him by penetrating a circle of
reporters and planting a kiss on his cheek (``MOM! You had to do
that?''), is an elementary math teacher and his father a professor
at Purdue University.
   The contest drew more than 200 contestants from around the
nation.
   Shultz won a gold medal, a computer and a week at the U.S. Space
Camp in Huntsville, Ala. He also led a contingent of the math
champions who met with President Reagan in the Oval Office.
   The final questions ranged from the score a bowler needed to
maintain his average to complex algebraic functions.
   Shultz ended the contest by answering ``Four square root two''
to the question: ``If f(x) equals x plus the absolute value of x,
find the distance between points A(2,f(2)) and B(-2,f(-2)).''
   Hanish, the third-place finisher, said, ``After he won three
rounds in a row, I knew he was probably going to take first. One of
the questions he answered so fast normally would have taken 20 to
30 seconds.''
   Shultz finished 71st at last year's finals, after ``I ate too
much food at breakfast,'' he recalled.
   ``You can't prepare a lot. If you prepare too much, you're up
too late and you wake up the next morning and you feel terrible,''
said Shultz, who likes ``chess and computers and playing a bit of
sports, although I'm not very good.''
   The other finalists, all 8th graders, in fourth to tenth place
were: Matthew Bruce, 13, Carver Middle School, Tulsa, Okla.; Akira
Negi, 15, East Northport Junior High School, N.Y.; Matthew Carle,
13, North Davie Junior High, Advance, N.C.; Richard Chung, 12,
Southern Junior High, Lexington, Ky.; Matthew Sakai, 13, Murray
Junior High, Ridgecrest, Calif.; Nathan Wilmes, 13, J.F. Kennedy
Junior High, Plantsville, Conn.; and Melissa Chen, 13, Lincoln East
Junior High, Lincoln, Neb. Melissa was the only girl in the finals.
   Some of the questions Shultz answered were:
   _``Joel's bowling average was 132 per game. Today his scores on
the first three games were 112, 182 and 142. What is the score he
must get on his fourth game in order to maintain his average
exactly?'' Ninety-two.
   _``A family has four children. If male births and female births
are equally likely, what is the probability that at least two of
the children are girls?'' Eleven-sixteenths.
   The contest is sponsored by the National Society of Professional
Engineers, the National Council of Teachers of Mathmatics, the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration, the U.S. Department
of Education and CNA Insurance Cos.
   The contestants were divided into teams of four by state or
territory. The top 10 state teams were: New York, North Carolina,
Illinois, Nebraska, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, Alabama, Kentucky,
California and Maryland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
