<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Theater     05-13 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Theater,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Royal Shakespeare Company Faces Hostile Press</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British critics are throwing brickbats at the
Royal Shakespeare Company after several poorly received productions
at home and the belated Broadway opening of its musical ``Carrie,''
which was panned.
   ``The RSC is a national asset. I think it's time to sound the
alarm,'' John Peter wrote in The Sunday Times after giving bad
reviews to two new productions in the company's home theater at
Stratford-upon-Avon, William Shakespeare's birthplace.
   Peter, who had harsh words for the new stagings of Shakespeare's
``Much Ado About Nothing'' and William Wycherley's ``The Plain
Dealer,'' wrote: ``There was a time, not that many years ago, when
you could look to the RSC for expertise, excellence, and
enjoyment.''
   Now, he said, ``the Royal Shakespeare Company is in trouble.''
   Michael Billington of the Guardian said the Stratford season had
an ``unnervingly shaky start.'' Of six productions since March 30,
only ``Across Oka,'' a new play by Robert Holman, received
favorable reviews.
   Negative reaction to ``Carrie'' in New York probably will
generate further talk of a decline. Peter lamented the prolonged
devotion of director Terry Hands to a show the critic called
``frightful.''
   In 1984-55, Hands' productions of ``Much Ado About Nothing'' and
``Cyrano de Bergerac'' took New York by storm, but he spent much of
the past year on the rock musical adaptation of the Stephen King
horror novel. ``Carrie'' opened May 12 at Broadway's Virginia
Theater after several delays.
   The $7 million musical received some sharp notices in New York,
and its initial reception in Stratford in February was harsher
still. Several critics wondered in print whether the company had
lost its sense of purpose.
   Michael Coveney in The Financial Times said ``Carrie'' was
``enjoyable in a masochistic way'' and decried Hands' participation
in ``an utter cultural vacuum of dance studio robotics with a hint
of cultural and classical pretensions.''
   Hands has fared little better in the non-musical area. His
productions of Shakespeare's ``Julius Caesar'' and Jean Genet's
``The Balcony'' were received with little enthusiasm.
   In an interview with The Associated Press before taking
``Carrie'' to New York, he said: ``I know it is fashionable for
everybody to know how to run the RSC and therefore to use their
pens and their newspapers to demonstrate their own particular area
of special interest.''
   He said the company has a ``tradition of music theater'' linked
to the extensive use of music in Shakespeare's plays. More
recently, the Royal Shakespeare won plaudits and profits with ``Les
Miserables,'' which premiered at the Barbican in October 1985 and
swept New York's Tony Awards last June.
   A trade newspaper, The Stage, said in the company's favor:
``Personally, and in spite of the somewhat spiky personalities of
certain people in charge of its affairs, we have a good deal of
sympathy with the RSC. To maintain that the RSC should be wound up,
as one or two of our readers suggest, is unthinkable.'' The Royal
Shakespeare's output is formidable. It opened 39 productions in six
theaters in 1987-88 and will open 37 this year. All of Broadway
averages about 30 shows a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
