<DOCNO> AP880513-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1637EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Budget     05-13 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Budget,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agreement Near on Budget, But Senate Panel Wants To Ignore It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate negotiators neared agreement
Friday on a $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget, but the Senate's main
spending committee voted to ignore it.
   The budget negotiators, deadlocked a month past their deadline,
were near approval of a plan that would delay a decision on whether
to add more spending for the space program or for education.
   With the Senate favoring more for space and the House more for
education, the budget proposal being circulated Friday would leave
the matter unresolved. Minimum amounts would be set for broad
spending categories, and a pot of $500 million would be left
uncommitted.
   A House vote on the compromise was expected next week. But the
budget, normally an important guidepost for Congress' production of
its annual spending bills, was taking the appearance of a
procedural exercise.
   Last fall's deficit-reduction agreement with President Reagan,
created in the wake of the stock market crash, pre-set the overall
totals for domestic, military and foreign aid spending. The House
and Senate spending committees, eager to finish their work this
election year, have gone ahead without the budget blueprint to
divide up the domestic pie.
   The House Appropriations Committee this week sent to the full
House three of the 13 annual appropriations bills, using its own
vision of how domestic spending should be allocated.
   On Friday, the Senate Appropriations Committee approved a set of
priorities sticking more closely to President Reagan's budget than
the one passed by the Senate.
   The committee approved a proposal drafted by Sens. Bennett
Johnston, D-La., and Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., to reject the
budget's tight restraints on water projects and interior programs,
and cut back on health, education and poverty programs.
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., also a
member of the appropriations panel, offered an amendment to shift
money back to the budget priorities, but was defeated 14-11.
   ``Water projects are important, but I thought education was
important. I thought health was important,'' he said.
   Sen. Lowell Weicker, a liberal Republican from Connecticut, said
in the past he was always fighting against the White House but now
it was the Democratic-controlled Congress providing less money for
education and AIDS research.
   ``Now I can train my guns on your party, and not my own,'' he
said.
   Johnston, who has been running the appropriations committee for
the ailing Sen. John Stennis, D-Miss., said his proposal reflected
the Senate's priorities better than the budget, which he called
``virtually meaningless.''
   He claimed the Senate did not understand the spending plan when
it approved it last month.
   The committee was relying on the budget resolution only for
technical definitions of how to comply with the deficit-reduction
agreement with Reagan, Johnston said.
   One of those technical disputes was settled Friday when
lawmakers and the White House tentatively agreed to allow about
$1.9 billion in total domestic spending beyond the level first
envisioned in the president's budget.
   Both the House and Senate budgets had sought to expand spending
by redefining some domestic accounts so they would not count
against the spending caps. The White House agreed to accept the
Senate level, which allowed slightly less new spending than the
House plan.
   The added spending would put the fiscal 1989 budget closer to
violating the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law. Although exact
figures were not available Friday, budget aides said if the deficit
swelled only $2 billion to $3 billion more, the spending plan might
hit the $146 billion threshold for triggering automatic spending
cuts as required by Gramm-Rudman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
