<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Degree,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Persistence Pays Off In Degree for Jackson's Mother-In-Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gertrude Brown dropped out of high school to
have a baby and returned to her own education four children later
at the age of 49. On Sunday, the 61-year-old mother-in-law of
Democratic presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson will get her degree
from Hampton University.
   ``I went back to school to get the skills to help people,'' Mrs.
Brown said at a Friday news conference with her daughter, Jackie
Jackson, at her side.
   Mrs. Brown is receiving her degree in social work and plans to
eventually open a center for teen-age parents.
   ``I was a teen-age mother,'' she explained.
   While working full time at the Veterans Administration in the
dietetics department, Mrs. Brown saw four of her children through
college, returned to get her high school degree and finally her
college degree.
   ``She has been the chief example in my life,'' said Mrs.
Jackson. ``I can remember her as a struggling young woman, who as a
positive person, a realist. I can also remember a number of
whippings because my vocabulary contained phrases like `I can't.'''
   Mrs. Brown was born in the Bahamas and raised in Flordia before
moving to Virginia.
   ``This is such an exciting time. I'm finally getting this
degree,'' she said. ``I was an honor student until this last
quarter. ... I think I was worrying too much about my children and
the campaign.
   ``But I'm not going to stop here,'' she said. ``I'm going to get
my masters now.''
   Mrs. Jackson said that when she was growing up, she considered
her mother to be overly strict and old fashioned. Now, she said,
she imposes on her own children the same rules as her mother
imposed on her.
   ``It has been an exciting summer, '' Mrs. Jackson said. ``Two of
my sons graduated from college and another from high school. ...
Now we have a rare occasion to see our parents fulfill a dream.''
   Jackson will give the commencement address to his
mother-in-law's class Sunday morning.
   Mrs. Brown's only comment about the Jackson campaign was that
she was excited.
</TEXT>
