<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1725EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FlyingPaycheck     05-13 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flying Paycheck,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Check Is In The Mail, Thank Goodness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DE FOREST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $300 expense check that blew out of a
broken airplane window will complete its trip to Cleveland the
conventional way _ through the U.S. mail.
   The check was in Robert J. Yaroma's suitcoat in the back of a
small plane flying at 16,000 feet Monday night when a rear window
blew out on the flight from Philadelphia to Cleveland. The jacket
and his raincoat were sucked out of the plane.
   On Tuesday, a worker mowing the grass at a former nuclear fuel
reprocessing plant about 30 miles south of Buffalo spotted the
check, said Mickie Andrus, a spokeswoman at the West Valley
Demonstration Project, which is cleaning up the site.
   A plant security official traced the check to Yaroma, an
investment counselor who lives in the Cleveland suburb of Westlake,
and first spoke to his wife. ``She just couldn't believe the check
was here,'' Ms. Andrus said.
   Later, Yaroma called back. ``He was just very, very polite and
couldn't thank us enough. He even wanted to send our security
official a reward,'' Ms. Andrus said.
   Yaroma said the coats are still missing.
   ``I figured my suitcoat is on the back of some cow or hanging in
a tree,'' he said.
   When the plane window blew out, thunderstorms were moving across
northeastern Ohio and into Pennsylvania and western New York. The
airplane landed safely at Cleveland without further incident and
nobody was injured, Yaroma said.
   Donald Wuerch, meteorologist in charge of the National Weather
Service office at Buffalo, said: ``I suspect the check was probably
caught up in a thunderstorm line that moved through the area. It
was probably caught in the atmospheric turbulence, with its
updrafts and downdrafts, until the storms died down Monday night
and the check settled to earth over western New York.''
   Ms. Andrus said the check was in surprisingly good condition.
``It had the stub on it and everything,'' she said.
   Because the check was found in an area where low-level
radioactive waste is stored underground, it was tested for
radioactivity and found to be safe before being mailed back to
Yaroma, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880513-0161 </DOCNO>
