<HEAD>Wife Tells How Loved Ones Aided In Spouse's Recovery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sarah Brady said she learned the invaluable role
loved ones play in the care and curing of the critically ill
following her husband's disabling injuries sustained during an
assassination attempt on President Reagan.
   ``It really can be a wonderful experience,'' she said Thursday
at a gathering of the American Associaton of Critical Care Nurses.
   Mrs. Brady said straight talk and compassion from the staff at
George Washington University Hospital, where White House Press
Secretary Jim Brady and Reagan were rushed after the shooting seven
years ago, made the time in the waiting room bearable.
   Brady was shot in the head by John W. Hinckley Jr., who also
wounded Reagan.
   Brady, once a garrulous, bearish man, is still fighting to
recover from the attack. After three operations and two bouts of
pneumonia, he relies on a cane or wheelchair and can work only a
few hours a week. His doctors say he will never regan use of his
left arm.
