<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1619EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BusinessInventories     05-13 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Business Inventories,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Sales Strong in March, While Inventory Growth Slowed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business sales climbed 1.9 percent in March,
the largest advance in more than a year, while the buildup of
business inventories slowed, the government reported Friday.
   The Commerce Department said total business sales rose to a
seasonally adjusted $479.5 billion in March. It was the largest
advance in 13 months and followed an equally strong 1.1 percent
rise in February.
   Business inventories were up 0.3 percent to $720 billion, the
smallest rise since last August. Inventories had grown by 0.4
percent in February and 0.7 percent in January.
   Analysts said the combination of booming sales and the slowdown
in the growth of inventories should translate into continued
strength in factory orders and production in the months ahead.
   The 0.3 percent rise in inventories included a tiny 0.1 percent
increase in unsold goods at the retail level, a 0.2 percent rise at
the manufacturing level and a 0.6 percent increase at the wholesale
level.
   David Wyss, an economist with Data Resources Inc., said the fact
that inventories were rising at the wholesale level meant part of
the buildup was occurring in imported goods and thus any needed
production cutbacks in this area would not hurt domestic
manufacturers.
   Michael Evans, head of a Washington forecasting firm, attributed
the small increase in retail inventories to the success car
manufacturers have had with their sales incentives at reducing
backlogs of new cars.
   The 1.9 percent rise in total sales was the largest increase
since a 4.1 percent jump in February 1987.
   It included a 1.7 percent rise in sales at the retail level.
However, the government reported Thursday that retail sales fell
0.6 percent in April as bad weather and an early Easter cut into
demand.
   Sales in March at the wholesale level were up 0.8 percent, while
sales by manufacturers rose 2.6 percent.
   The combination of rising sales and slower growth in inventories
left the inventory-to-sales ratio at 1.50 in March, down from 1.53
in February. That means that it would take 1.50 months to exhaust
inventories at the March sales pace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
