<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ValuableTrash     05-13 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Valuable Trash,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honest Sanitation Workers Turn in Bundles of Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two sanitation workers who found a stash of cash
in a barrel of trash turned in the $48,900 and were rewarded with a
thank you. That's all.
   The garbage collectors are not entitled to a nickel of the loot
_ 410 $100 bills and 158 $50s neatly bound with rubber bands, which
they found during regular pickup rounds Thursday in an alley in the
borough of Queens.
   Under state law, ``if the finder is an officer of New York state
or a public corporation, he or she is not entitled to money found
in the performance of their duty,'' police Sgt. John Clifford said
Friday.
   And instead of kind words, the do-gooders have been ridiculed by
people who think they were chumps to turn in the money.
   ``We have been getting calls that have been derogatory,'' said
Donald Koubek, their supervisor. ``They've been called dummies,
stupid, jerks.''
   The two, who joined the department in 1969 and 1970, have
refused to talk to reporters and their names have been withheld,
according to Vito Turso, a Sanitation Department spokesman.
   ``They have taken their fair share of ribbing from people who
try to second guess what they did,'' Turso said. ``But they did the
right thing. They followed department regulations and they are to
be commended, but at this point they are being commended
anonymously.''
   Koubek admitted it's tough to choose between kind words and cold
cash.
   ``It's what I would call a sanitation worker's dream,'' he said.
``Still, I think most people would turn it in after a little bit of
thought. These guys had no other thought than to turn it in. They
immediately called their garage and I was notified.''
   Koubek said that among co-workers, ``they are getting more
positive (reaction) than negative.''
   So far, no one has claimed the cash, Clifford said.
   There is no indication that the money was ill-gotten: The bills
were not marked, the serial numbers were not consecutive and they
were not counterfeit.
   ``As far as I know it's not ours,'' said Marianne Bosted of the
two bundles of bills that fell out of a trash can Thursday in the
alley behind her house.
   ``I keep saying to my aunt, `Are you sure you weren't saving
this in a box to give to me?' '' Ms. Bosted said.
</TEXT>
