<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LittleArchaeologists     05-13 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Little Archaeologists,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Program Aims To Spark Youth Interest In Archaeology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While some youngsters plan to be spending
their summer playing at the beach, others will be sifting through
the mud in search of ancient relics, thanks to a program for
budding archaeologists.
   The University of West Florida hopes its 1988 Summer Youth
Archaeology Program will encourage youths to enter the field and
will teach them the basics of literally digging into the past.
   ``It's dirty, but it's also exciting as archaeology gets,'' said
UWF associate anthropology professor Judy Bense, who heads the
school's Office of Archaeological Research.
   ``It isn't pretend or showcase. The most important aspect about
this project for youth is they get a chance to see real
archaeology,'' she said.
   Between June 20 and July 8, 15 to 20 youths will help excavate
and do lab analysis of artifacts recovered from previous digs of
American Indian and European culture sites.
   Pensacola lays claim to being the second-oldest continually
occupied American city, behind St. Augustine, and is rich in
artifacts. Actually, Spaniards settled Pensacola first, in 1559,
but then abandoned it for a few years, letting the title slip to
the Atlantic Coast city, settled six years later.
   The summer session costs $150.
   The program aims to give special attention to students who show
an interest in archaeology as a career, said Ms. Bense, who became
interested in her life's calling when she attended Bay County High
School in Panama City, another Florida Panhandle town.
   ``It had everything to do with the teacher we had,'' she recalls
of her earliest interest. ``He opened our eyes to the fact that
just because you are in Panama City _ which essentially is nowhere
_ and went to Bay County High School, which was a so-so school,
didn't mean you couldn't be an archaeologist.
   ``And there are seven archaeologists with Ph.D.'s from that tiny
little town,'' she said, adding that she hopes to similarly inspire
Pensacola students.
   Ms. Bense said she's optimistic about that happening.
   ``There are a couple that are real young ... that are really
eager beavers ... that I really think may be budding
archaeologists,'' she said.
</TEXT>
