<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Hughes     05-13 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Hughes,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Lets Stand TWA's $48 Million Judgment Against Summa Corp.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Supreme Court justice Friday refused to
block a $48.35 million judgment awarded Trans World Airlines
against a company formerly run by the late Howard Hughes.
   Justice William J. Brennan denied an emergency request by Summa
Corp. and William R. Lummis, administrator of the Hughes estate, to
suspend the judgment pending a formal appeal to the full court.
   The Delaware Supreme Court on April 4 upheld the award in a case
that began in 1962.
   Summa Corp., formerly called Hughes Tool Co. or Toolco, owned 78
percent of the stock of TWA when it was sued by other TWA
shareholders.
   The minority shareholders said TWA, which Hughes founded, was
denied an opportunity to be competitive and profitable because
Toolco refused to allow the airline to purchase its own jets in the
1950s. TWA was forced to lease jets and buy some from Toolco, the
suit said.
   ``For reasons clearly attributable to the eccentric or
idiosyncratic business methods of Howard Hughes, TWA was unable to
establish a jet fleet as quickly as its competitors,'' the Delaware
Supreme Court ruled.
   It upheld a lower court ruling that awarded TWA more than $17.2
million plus interest of about $31.1 million.
   The case is Summa Corp. vs. TWA, A-859.
</TEXT>
