<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Steelworks Strikers Reported Freed; Journalists Warned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-two people detained last week in
the police raid that ended a strike at the Lenin steelworks in
southern Poland have been freed, a spokesman at a church
sympathetic to the strikers said Friday.
   Sixteen others are believed still in custody, said the spokesman
for the ``Solidarity congregation'' at St. Maksymilian Kolbe Church
in Nowa Huta, just outside Krakow.
   The government, meanwhile, told a group of Western journalists
who entered the strikebound Lenin shipyard in Gdansk that they will
lose permission to work in Poland if such an incident occurs again.
   Police raided the steelworks in Nowa Huta before dawn on May 5,
and authorities said 38 people were detained.
   Six people were freed Thursday and one on Friday, said the
church spokesman, who asked that his name not be used.
   He said 15 people were freed last weekend after 48 hours'
detention and fined up to $202 by a misdemeanor court.
   He said six people were considered under arrest, which allows
them to be held for up to two months under arrest warrants. The
remaining 10 people in custody have been sentenced by misdemeanor
courts to two to four weeks' imprisonment, he said.
   Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak paid visits to the sites of
the two longest strikes during Poland's wave of labor unrest that
began April 25 and ended Tuesday.
   Kiszczak, a member of the Politburo of the Polish United Workers
(communist) Party, Friday visited the Lenin Shipyard in Gdansk, the
official PAP news agency said. A strike there ended Tuesday after
strikers voluntarily left without a settlement.
   The strike had been for higher pay and for recognition of a
local chapter of Solidarity, the trade union federation.
   While in Gdansk, Kiszczak met with shipyard managers and
representatives of various official workers' groups as well as
Gdansk Roman Catholic Bishop Tadeusz Goclowski.
   On Thursday, Kiszczak met with management and workers at the
steelworks in Nowa Huta, PAP said. He also met with Cardinal
Franciszek Macharski, archbishop of Krakow.
   In Warsaw, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, which accredits
foreign journalists in Poland, warned representatives of six news
organizations _ The Associated Press, Reuters, Deutsche Presse
Agentur, the Financial Times of London, Newsweek magazine and the
West German television station ARD.
   The government said it was illegal to enter the shipyard without
a pass issued by management, and that taking photographs in the
shipyard is banned by signs posted on its grounds.
   The 10 journalists employed by the six organizations entered the
shipyard on Monday morning and emerged together through a side gate
about four hours later. They were detained by police immediately
upon leaving the shipyard, held for about 2{ hours and released
after questioning.
   Film, tape recordings and some notes of the journalists were
confiscated.
   The group included six Poles employed by the Western news
organizations, one German, one Briton, one American and one
Yugoslavian.
</TEXT>
