<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Drugs-Priest     05-13 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs-Priest,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spanish Priest Faces Trial On Drug Trafficking Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Spanish priest and a defrocked
comrade face drug trafficking charges in Venezuela's first
narcotics smuggling case involving a Catholic Church official,
newspapers reported Friday.
   Authorities said Father Jose Luis Gil Fernandez, arrested with
45 pounds of the drug, told them the thousands of dollars he made
from earlier drug sales were spent on his chapel, school and
charity.
   Judge Francisco Caracciolo Lamus of the 40th Penal Court in
Caracas issued an arrest warrant late Thursday charging Gil
Fernandez, 57, former priest Jose Rojano Martinez, 54, and
Martinez' wife, Graciela de Rojano, 46, with trafficking in illegal
drugs, local newspapers reported.
   The defendants could each be sentenced to 10 to 20 years in jail
if convicted.
   ``The investigation is still open regarding other (suspects) and
the circumstances of the events,'' El Universal newspaper quoted
Caracciolo quoted as saying.
   Gil Fernandez was detained by police April 26 as he prepared to
board a plane for Madrid at Maiquetia International Airport outside
Caracas. More than 45 pounds of cocaine were found in his baggage.
   Rojano Martinez and his wife were detained hours later in a
Caracas residence. Police seized an apparently false passport and
four false $100 bills from the house but did not find drugs.
   The Spanish-born Gil Fernandez was parish priest in San Mateo, a
small town 35 miles west of Caracas, for 24 years.
   Following his detention he confessed to having carried drugs to
Spain on two previous occasions since 1984, officials said. He said
the money he received, around $41,000, was invested in the parish
chapel and school and in charity for poor parishioners.
   Initial investigations show the priest traveled repeatedly to
the United States, Panama, the Dominican Republic and several
European countries since 1980, Caracciolo said.
   Police are also investigating a travel agency in Maracay, the
city nearest San Mateo, that Gil Fernandez may own, Caracciolo said.
   The three suspects were being held in separate Caracas jails.
</TEXT>
