<1ST_LINE>u w AM-CrossSuit     05-13 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cross Suit,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Concerned About Cross Erected on Hawaii Marine Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge voiced concern Friday over
whether a 65-foot Latin cross erected more than 20 years ago at a
Marine base in Hawaii is an unconstitutional endorsement of
religion by government.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas F. Hogan made no ruling on a lawsuit
against the cross' presence at Camp H.M. Smith, but he expressed
doubts about the government's contention it served the purely
secular purpose or honoring Marines killed in the Vietnam war or
are missing in action.
   ``The court has concerns over the legitimacy of the cross,''
Hogan said at the conclusion of a hearing on the issue. ``There is
not a case where a cross has ever been accepted'' by federal courts
as a permissible symbol on government property.
   The Jewish War Veterans of the U.S.A. contends that the wooden
cross on a prominent point at the Marine base violates the
Constitution's ban on governmental endorsement of a particular
religion.
   The group's lawyer, Ronald Koerner, said the Latin cross cannot
be considered a secular object because it is the ``symbol of the
passion, death and resurrection of Jesus Christ.''
   ``It is one of the great ironies of the case that the government
has taken a profoundly religious symbol to devout Christians and
turned it into a secular symbol,'' Koerner said.
   ``Here a particular religion or a particular view is accepted, a
minority religion's view is disregarded,'' he said. Non-Christian
war dead are not honored by the cross, he added.
   ``Will non-Christian people have the right not to enter military
service because they are accorded no respect, honor and dignity?''
Koerner said.
   Justice Department attorney Frederick Morgan did not deny the
religious significance of the Latin cross, but he said ``the
history of the memorial is clear; it was erected as a secular
monument.''
   Although courts have ruled that Latin crosses on government
property are impermissible, Morgan said the Hawaii case is
different because it involves a cross that is part of a war
memorial.
   ``There is no religious purpose here,'' he said.
   But Morgan conceded under questioning by Judge Hogan that his
argument would be harder to prove if the cross were a crucifix _ a
representation of Christ on the cross that is a common symbol in
the Roman Catholic Church.
   Hogan noted a Marine press release issued in 1983 stated that
the original cross was built in 1966 for an Easter sunrise service.
But Morgan questioned the accuracy of the press release, which he
said was disavowed in deposition testimony by Marine officials,
including a former base chaplain.
   Hogan also noted that the press release referred to the cross
being rebuilt, after a fire, in time for it to be lit at Christmas.
   Morgan said the cross, located on a high point of land from
which it can be seen at sea, has become ``a beacon of hope for the
community and a landmark.''
   When there was a move to take it down three years ago, the
Marine base received 3,200 letters from local residents who wanted
cross kept where it was, Morgan said. Only one writer called for
its removal, he said.
   The cross has been a source of controversy for several years.
   In 1985, the Navy's judge advocate general, Rear Adm. Thomas E.
Flynn ruled that the cross' presence on the base was
unconstitutional and recommended that it be removed.
   Marine commanders ordered its removal, but Gen. P.X. Kelley,
then the Marine commandant, countermanded those orders.
   In the margin of a routing slip attached to Flynn's opinion,
Kelley wrote: ``And the cross came crashing down. Victory for the
forces of evil.''
   Kelley, now retired, said during a deposition taken in the case
that he was merely referring to lawyers as the forces of evil.
   Kelley's order keeping the cross was issued after retired Lt.
Gen. Victor Krulak wrote to say he had erected the cross in the
mid-1960s as a monument to Marines killed or missing in action in
Vietnam.
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1984 that the city of Pawtucket,
R.I., could erect a creche that depicts the nativity scene in a
park along with other symbols of Christmas such as reindeer.
   Since that decision, however, the high court has left
undisturbed court rulings by federal judges that ordered the
removal of crosses from municipal buildings in St. Charles, La.,
and Birmingham, Ala. In both cases, the lower courts held that the
crosses, which stood alone, were undiluted religious symbols that
should not be displayed on government property.
</TEXT>
