<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Personnel     05-13 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Personnel,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Plans to Nominate Djerejian As New Ambassador to Syria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan plans to nominate Edward
Djerejian, a career foreign service office, to be ambassador to
Syria, the White House announced Friday.
   Djerejian, who will succeed William L. Eagleton pending Senate
confirmation, has been serving as the principal deputy assistant to
the secretary of state for Near Eastern and South Asian affairs.
   From 1985-86, he was assigned to the White House as a special
assistant to the president for foreign affairs.
   Djerejian's last overseas assignment was in Amman, Jordan, where
he was deputy chief of mission at the American Embassy from 1981-84.
   In other personnel moves, Reagan:
   _Announced his intention to nominate Kenneth P. Bergquist to be
an assistant secretary of the Navy for manpower and reserve affairs
at the Defense Department. He would succeed Charles G. Untermeyer.
   _Said he plans to nominate David C. Chu to be an assistant
secretary of defense for program analysis and evaluation. This is a
new Pentagon position. Since 1981, Chu has been director of program
analysis and evaluation at the Defense Department.
   _Designated Becky Norton Dunlop, deputy under secretary of
interior, as a special representative to deal with relations
between the United States and the Northern Mariana Islands.
   _Named Peter M. Robinson to be a special assistant to the
president for speech writing. Since October 1983, Robinson has
served as a speech writer in the White House. Previously, he was
chief speech writer for Vice President George Bush.
</TEXT>
