<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Friday13th     05-13 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Friday 13th,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Club Members Revel on Friday 13th</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER SHINKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen members of the Friday the 13th club
sought to bring good luck to the Reading Terminal Market Friday by
breaking seven mirrors and dancing under a ladder with raised black
umbrellas.
   ``The idea is to spoof the whole idea of Friday the 13th bad
luck,'' said club member Ed Wohlmuth, who teaches fashion
merchandizing at the Art Institute of Philadelphia.
   But the club, which began its celebration at the market at 12:13
p.m., has its own superstitions.
   Max Buten did only two spins under the ladder with his umbrella.
``Any more than that is bad luck,'' he said.
   Friday's meeting, the club's second this year and 90th since its
founding in 1936, was designed to aid the Reading market, which is
located beneath a huge train barn last used as a commuter rail stop
two years ago.
   ``We want this place to survive,'' Wohlmuth said of the Reading
market, which has been mentioned as the possible site of a
convention center. ``Where else in America do you have a farmer's
market in the middle of a city?''
   Bob Boyle, executive vice president of the Reading Real Estate
Co., which manages the market, joined in the anti-superstition
ceremony. He said he wasn't sure whether the club's antics would
save the market, but he added, ``It can't hurt.''
   The club, founded in 1936 by Philadelphia ad man Harry Klein, is
exclusive. Membership is by invitation only, and is limited to 13.
``You have to wait for somebody to die to get in,'' Wohlmuth said.
   He also said the club has set its own expiration date, Friday
the 13th of October, 1988, ``to give the world a break.''
   Club members conceded bad luck had struck occasionally. Wohlmuth
said the club helped initiate an aquarium in South Philadelphia in
the mid-1960s. The aquarium closed by the end of the year. Then
there was the time they were invited to initiate a new subway
station below the market. ``That night they had stalled trains in
the tunnel,'' recalled member Henry Klein, brother of the founder.
   But who knows. On this Friday the 13th, a City Council committee
recommended limiting city support for the costly convention center.
</TEXT>
