<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1741EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Obit-Baker     05-13 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Baker,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Jazz Musician Dies In Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American jazz trumpeter Chet
Baker, famed for his 1950s appearances with Gerry Mulligan, died
Friday after falling from the second floor of his Amsterdam hotel.
   Baker, 59, fell from the hotel window shortly after 3:10 a.m.
and was found dead in the street by police, according to Amsterdam
police spokesman Klaas Wilting.
   No precise reason for Baker's fall was disclosed.
   Baker was scheduled to make several appearances as part of a
tour of the Netherlands.
   The jazz trumpeter was born Chesney Baker in Yale, Okla., in
December 1929. His early career contained phenomenal luck which
turned very sour.
   Famed for the thin, cool tone of his trumpet playing, Baker set
the the standard for what jazz buffs knew as the ``cool school.''
   In 1952, he was working with Charlie Parker on the West Coast
when he joined Mulligan, a baritone saxaphonist, and the rest of
his piano-less quartet.
   In 1953, Baker topped the Metronome trumpet poll and started his
own quartet. His work became more assured and outgoing. In 1955 he
took a group to Europe that showed high promise. Then his career
started to suffer, from narcotics, arrests, headlines and a
backlash against the fact he'd been overrated at the beginning.
   He had a cult following in the 1950s, because of his good looks
and youth and his fragile and introverted tone. He looked something
like James Dean and sounded something like Bix Beiderbecke. As a
player, Miles Davis was his main inspiration.
   In recent years, Baker said he had stopped taking drugs and
started making records again, appearing on an Elvis Costello album.
   He sang sometimes in a rather weak voice but was appealing to
female audiences.
   In San Francisco in 1968, Baker he was the victim of a beating
by hoodlums and suffered severe injuries that included loss of his
teeth, a terrible thing for a trumpet player. For two years he
didn't play.
   In 1974, critic John S. Wilson wrote in The New York Times that
had developed ``more range and assertivedness within the wistfully
ruminative style with which he has also been associated.''
</TEXT>
