<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Philby,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philby Buried in Moscow Cemetery With Full Honors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British traitor and master spy Harold ``Kim''
Philby was buried in a Moscow cemetery Friday with full military
honors after being praised as a courageous man who did his utmost
to defend the Soviet Union.
   Four speakers eulogized Philby, calling him ``Comrade Kim,'' and
lauding him as an outstanding agent of the KBG, the Soviet
espionage and state security police.
   Double agent Philby, 76, died on Wednesday in Moscow, his home
since he fled the West in 1963.
   BBC radio correspondent Jeremy Harris, who attended Philby's
funeral at Kuntsevo Cemetery in western Moscow, said the red-draped
coffin was open and the body was dressed in a dark suit and red tie.
   A 12-member honor guard from the Soviet border police fired a
volley of shots in salute as the coffin was lowered into the grave,
Harris said.
   Philby's fourth wife, a Soviet, wept.
   While spying for Moscow as a mole inside British intelligence,
Philby sent many Western agents to their deaths. The British secret
service valued him so highly that at one time it was considering
him for the top job, chief of MI6.
   For his services to the Soviet Union, Philby was awarded the
nation's highest decoration, the Order of Lenin, and other medals.
   Philby told Radio Moscow last November that he wanted to be
buried in the Soviet Union, ``which I consider to be my country
since the 1930s.''
   The official Tass news agency on Thursday praised Philby as a
``remarkable Soviet intelligence officer'' who accomplished
seemingly impossible feats to defend the Soviet Union and the world
progressive movement against Western spies.
</TEXT>
