<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Embezzlement     05-13 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Embezzlement,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Gave Embezzled Money To AIDS Home Received Prison Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former thrift executive has been sentenced to
four years in prison for embezzling more than $1 million and
donating some of it to gay charities in the mistaken belief he was
about to die of AIDS.
   ``I made an awful mistake, and now I'm trying to live with it,''
said Patrick Wayne Debenport, sentenced Thursday by U.S. District
Judge Barefoot Sanders.
   Debenport, 27, former manager of First Texas Savings and Loan's
Oak Cliff branch, was charged in March with 15 counts of
misapplication of funds after an FBI investigation found $1.1
million missing.
   Under a plea bargain, he pleaded guilty to three counts, and the
rest were dropped. Debenport, who admitted stealing the $1.1
million, had faced up to 15 years in prison and $750,000 in fines.
   Debenport said his five-month embezzling spree began in 1987
after he was told he had AIDS and just three months to live. Later,
he found he had only tested positive for exposure to the AIDS virus
but did not have the disease.
   The former bank manager said he had used the thrift's computer
system to transfer 15 bogus loans to his bank account in suburban
Mesquite.
   He used most of the money to buy a new home, a car and other
luxuries but donated $175,000 to the People With AIDS Coalition to
help buy a home for AIDS victims and gave $20,000 to a church.
   Thrift officials say most of the money has been recovered except
for the $175,000 that Debenport gave to the AIDS charity.
   Coalition directors said they did not know the money was stolen
and have already spent it to renovate the city's only home for AIDS
patients. The thrift has sued the coalition for repayment.
</TEXT>
