<HEAD>Rebels Renew Offer of Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels proposed Friday
a resumption of talks with the U.S.-supported government on ending
the civil war that began 8{ years ago.
   Roberto Viera, a spokesman for President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
said the government had not received formal notification of the
offer.
   In a statement distributed to news media, the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front guerrilla coalition and the political
Democratic Revolutionary Front suggested the first meeting be held
May 30-31.
   They said Monsignor Arturo Rivera Damas, the Roman Catholic
archibshop of San Savlador, should act as a mediator.
   The statement did not suggest a site for the meeting, but
proposed that it include delegates of Duarte's administration, the
national legislature and the armed forces.
   It called the proposal ``a contribution to the search for a
political solution to the crisis'' in El Salvador.
   Several meetings have been held since 1984 between the rebels
and Duarte administration, with Rivera Damas and other church
leaders mediating, but accomplishing nothing.
   The rebels broke off the last talks in October after a prominent
human rights activist was killed. Human rights groups and the
church say most of the 65,000 people killed in the civil war were
civilian victims of rightist death squads or paramilitary forces.
   Friday's statement proposed a meeting with an open agenda ``to
discuss ... concrete measures for ending the armed conflict,
together with measures to give continuity to this effort and
incorporate all the nation's sectors into a dialogue.''
