<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberia-Ritual Murders,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Six Executed for Ritual Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Friday ordered six people
executed for the murders of two boys killed in an occult ritual
intended to bring the defendants better political jobs.
   Criminal Court Judge George Tulay set May 27 as the date for
hanging.
   Defense lawyers won a stay of execution, however, when the
Supreme Court agreed to review the case. The high court set no
hearing date.
   The defendants included David Clarke, a former county boss of
the governing National Democratic Party of Liberia, and former
county attorney Faikai Bedell.
   All six were convicted of the October 1986 murders of Samuel
Johnson, 6, and Emmanuel Daliah, 7. The boys were killed in Harper,
490 miles east of the capital city of Monrovia.
   According to trial testimony, parts of the victims' body were
used to make charms that were supposed to guarantee the defendants
high positions in the government and the party in power.
   Police arrested the defendants by using an occult practitioner
of their own known as Madam Mary. Ten years earlier, she helped
police track down and convict seven people in the same county in
the ritual killing of a musician.
   The seven were hanged.
