<HEAD>Hundreds Of Cows Perish In Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LARVIK, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire destroyed a new barn at one of the
country's largest cattle farms Friday, killing hundreds of cows
inside, police said.
   The blaze at Fritzoe Farm killed 480 cows in Larvik, a town 80
miles southwest of Oslo, police said.
   The farm manager, Staale Landmark, said the remaining 120 cows
in the barn were rescued, ``but all of them must be slaughtered.''
   Damage to property and loss of animals exceeded $1.6 million, he
told the Norwegian national NRK radio.
   Johannes Stapenes, a police spokesman, told the national NTB
news agency that the blaze may have been caused by the spontaneous
combustion among and lye-soaked bundles of straw placed along the
barn.
   The blaze also destroyed an older farmhouse, two silos and a
building used to store potatoes.
