<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeltaPact     05-13 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta Pact,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mississippi, Louisiana and Arkansas Sign Cooperation Agreements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES SAGGUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governors of Mississippi, Louisiana
and Arkansas signed an agreement aboard a Mississippi River barge
Friday to wage war on poverty in the region and work together to
woo foreign business.
   Gov. Ray Mabus of Mississippi said the three states for too long
had left untapped the potential of their rich Delta areas and ``not
claimed our fair share of the prosperity that is America.''
   ``If we are successful, the country succeeds,'' Mabus said. ``We
cannot have a truly vibrant country if we have pockets of despair,
if there are places which do not fully share in the American
dream.''
   Mabus, along with Govs. Buddy Roemer of Louisiana and Bill
Clinton of Arkansas, signed an agreement to work together to
``promote friendly and working relations with foreign countries in
the areas of international trade, industry, technology and tourism,
education and culture.''
   Their pact also aims to improve conditions in the impoverished
agricultural flatlands along the river. The governors did not
specify how they would fight poverty and said the details would be
worked out later.
   ``Together we can do so much more. Our problems are bigger than
a single state,'' Roemer said.
   Political and business leaders and Japanese ambassador Nobuo
Matsunaga joined the governors for the barge trip from the port of
Rosedale to the main river channel, where the agreements were
signed.
   The governors said the agreements would not end competition
among the three states but represented a realization that big
investors decide first on a region and then a specific site.
   ``We have always assumed that if Mississippi won something,
Arkansas lost it,'' Clinton said. ``That is not so. States in good
shape are parts of regions in good shape.''
   ``We can do so much as a team. We are too poor to compete
individually,'' Mabus said.
</TEXT>
