<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EastGermany-Rabbi     05-13 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-East Germany-Rabbi,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Rabbi Bids East Berlin Jewish Community Farewell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. rabbi, who drew the ire of Communist
officials and Jewish leaders during his eight months as Jewish
spiritual leader in East Germany, said Friday he was leaving East
Berlin with ``mixed feelings.''
   Rabbi Isaac Neuman, 65, took over the post in September 1987,
after retiring as rabbi in Champaign, Ill.
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Neuman had criticized
East German news media coverage of recent events in Israel. He also
attacked leaders of East Berlin's Jewish community, saying they had
thwarted his work.
   The state-run media later attacked Neuman, saying East Germany
did not tolerate anti-Semitism.
   Neuman told East Berlin Jews Friday night he had had
disagreements with people within the community ``who had different
views about Judaism.''
   He said he hoped that those involved in the disputes had not
been hurt.
   Neuman, who said two weeks ago he was returning to the United
States on May 16, said Friday, ``I am leaving with mixed feelings.
Not everything was wonderful, but not everything was bad either.''
   Neuman was the first rabbi to take over the East German post in
more than 20 years.
   The East German Jewish community has less than 350 officially
registered members and about 100 people ``on the fringes,'' Neuman
said.
   Some estimates say there are as many as 2,500 other Jews in East
Germany who are non-practicing.
   East Berlin has the largest number of Jews, with other
communities in Halle, Leipzig and Dresden.
</TEXT>
