<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 2104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Pepsi-Soviet     05-13 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pepsi-Soviet,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Producers Wheel and Deal Soviet TV Ad Time out of Remote Farmhouse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLRAIN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The agents who made the deal that will
bring singer Michael Jackson to 150 million Soviet television
viewers via Pepsi Cola ads operate out of a 200-year-old farmhouse
on a dirt road here.
   The Jackson spots, to be broadcast next week, will be the first
paid American commercials on Soviet television.
   ``We're a very small outfit,'' said David Nussbaum of Global
American Television Inc., a big name for the little television
production company housed in the hills of western Massachusetts.
   Global American's founders, Pam Roberts and Ed Wierzbowski, seem
to have found an unlikely place for big-time wheeling and dealing
in their 1780 house with a half-finished addition and two young
children underfoot.
   But they had the inside edge: a long and trusting relationship
with the Soviet Union's primary TV network, Nussbaum said Friday.
The company's only full-time employee, Nussbaum is also helping
build the addition, watch the children, write scripts and negotiate
other commercial deals.
   ``We would rather be helping share ads for sweet drinks than
bombs,'' Nussbaum said.
   The company has worked with the government-controlled Soviet
network Gosteleradio since 1982 on such projects as ``Citizens
Summit,'' a talk show featuring Phil Donahue and his Soviet
counterpart, Vladimir Pozner, linked by satellite.
   Wierzbowski landed in Moscow on Friday and went immediately to
Soviet studios to begin editing Pepsi ads, including two featuring
Jackson. All the ads have already appeared on American television.
   Among other tasks, he must put the company logo and slogan
``Choice of a New Generation'' into Cyrillic script _ those
distinctive Russian letters _ and add a Soviet voice-over narration.
   The ads are to appear next Tuesday through Saturday on five
one-hour broadcasts of ``Pozner in America,'' in which the Soviet
commentator talks with Americans on such topics as U.S. family life
and attitudes toward Soviets.
   Roberts and Wierzbowski began their business with amateur
videotapes of protests at the Seabrook nuclear power plant in New
Hampshire and moved on to documentaries, including one on a uranium
plant strike in Tennessee.
   In 1982, they began traveling to the Soviet Union for
``Dialogue,'' a documentary on the visit of 40 Americans to
Siberia. That film gave them the idea for a live conversation
between Soviets and Americans that became ``Citizens Summit.''
   When Gosteleradio decided to air ``Pozner in America,'' it
turned to Roberts and Wierzbowski for help in choosing an
advertiser to defray the costs.
   ``They know us,'' Nussbaum said simply.
   He wouldn't reveal financial details of the deal, but the going
rate was reported to be $10,000 for a 30-second ad.
   ``The amounts of money we've gotten ... are not large amounts by
the standards of American markets,'' Nussbaum said. ``But the
Soviets will be receiving currency and that's what they want,
interest-generating currency with which to expand their programs.''
   Several U.S. companies that sell products in the Soviet Union
were approached, but Pepsi was the natural choice, since the
company pioneered in marketing there, Nussbaum said. The soft drink
has been sold there since 1974.
   A company spokesman said a Pepsi ad ran on Soviet television
during telecasts of the 1986 Goodwill Games, but that commercial
aired free of charge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
