<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz-Book     05-13 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Book,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary of State Assails Kiss-and-Tell Books as ``Distressing''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George P. Shultz on Friday attacked
kiss-and-tell books by former Reagan administration officials as
violating presidential trust and defended President Reagan as being
``very much in charge'' of the country.
   The U.S. secretary of state also implied that such books affront
``common human decency'' as well.
   Without identifying the books he had in mind, Shultz called them
``a disservice'' and said he found the disclosures ``very
disappointing.''
   Donald Regan, former treasury secretary and later chief of staff
for Reagan, has the latest book out about his years in the White
House. One of his most sensational disclosures was that first lady
Nancy Reagan, and also the president, consulted an astrologer.
   Regan also portrayed the president as a passive chief executive
who did not question him about economic policy while Regan was
treasury secretary.
   In an earlier book, former White House spokesman Larry Speakes
revealed that he attributed to Reagan quotes which Speakes himself
fashioned.
   Shultz was in Brussels to brief North Atlantic Alliance
ministers on his talks with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze.
   He told a news conference, ``Books that are written, especially
when an administration is in office, that essentially are gossipy
things, particularly about the first family, are very disappointing
and distressing to me.''
   He said a person who accepts a position close to the presidency,
with access to ``intimate discussion,'' should observe standards of
``common human decency'' and also preserve an atmosphere in which
the president can talk freely to his aides.
   He said that otherwise free discussion is inhibited.
   In response to a reporter's question, the secretary praised the
president and Mrs. Reagan, saying the administration had changed
the presidential agenda ``for the better'' and Mrs. Reagan had
worked hard to combat drugs.
   Shultz said, ``It's hard for me to see how anybody who takes
part (in discussions with the president) can come to any conclusion
other than _ on these basic issues that are presidential in nature
_ that the president is very much in charge. He has his views. He
expresses them. One of the reasons he is respected so much is that
he sticks to his positions.''
</TEXT>
