<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     05-13 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Planes Hit Iranian Cargo Ship With Missiles; 11 Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi aircraft fired Exocet missiles at
an Iranian cargo ship in the Persian Gulf and later damaged a
tugboat towing the stricken vessel, a London-based maritime agency
said Friday.
   The attack on the cargo ship injured 11 crewmen, one seriously,
said Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit.
   Iraq reported another attack by its warplanes on a ``large naval
target'' off the Iranian coast on Thursday afternoon, its ninth
such claim in the past two weeks. The latest claim appeared to
coincide with the attack on the tug, the Sea Sapphire.
   However, a gulf-based shipping source said he had received
information that the Iranian cargo vessel, the Iran Nahad,
``exploded'' during an attack about 1:20 a.m. Thursday and may have
been carrying arms.
   The source, who has shipping connections in the area but spoke
on condition he not be identified, also quoted his informant as
saying the tugboat was searching for survivors of the blast, but
was not itself attacked.
   There was no way immediately to reconcile the conflicting
reports. Iran does not divulge details of Iraqi raids on its
coastal waters.
   Lloyd's said that in the first attack at 1 a.m. Iraqi Exocet
missiles hit the 16,580-ton Iran Nahad, setting a fire that gutted
the crew quarters.
   Thirteen hours later, as the ship was being towed to Lavan
island, an oil terminal along Iran's central Gulf coast, Lloyd's
said, it was attacked for a second time.
   It did not indicate whether the Iran Nahad was hit again, but
said the Liberian-owned and Panamanian-flagged Sea Sapphire, which
was towing the vessel, ``sustained damage to the wheelhouse,'' and
would go to a United Arab Emirates shipyard for repair.
   Iraq, locked in a 7{-year-old war with Iran, attacks Iranian
tankers. Iran retaliates with attacks on neutral shipping. Its last
such attack was on a Saudi Arabian tanker on April 24.
   A U.S. Navy battle group led by the aircraft carrier Forrestal
sailed through the Suez Canal, en route to the Arabian Sea, where
it will operate in support of the U.S. escort operations in the
gulf.
   The 60,000-ton Forrestal becomes the fifth U.S. aircraft carrier
to serve in the Arabian Sea since the United States expanded its
naval presence in the gulf in July last year to furnish escort for
11 Kuwaiti oil tankers re-registered under the American flag.
   Three of those tankers are currently en route down the gulf in
the 31st convoy this year and the 53rd since the operation began.
   The Forrestal's Atlantic coast-based battle group, including
three destroyers, two frigates and two supply vessels, replaces a
Pacific coast group headed by the nuclear-powered carrier
Enterprise.
</TEXT>
