<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Kids     05-13 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Kids,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>7-Year-Old Who Missed Meeting Reagan Will Get Another Chance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old boy who has recovered from
serious automobile accident injuries missed out on a White House
meeting with President Reagan on Friday because of a mix up in time.
   But presidential aides will arrange for a make-up visit soon for
young Chris Dunning and his family of Alexandria, Va., Deputy Press
Secretary B.J. Cooper said.
   Reagan showed up 12 minutes late for a ``Safe Kids'' program in
the Rose Garden and explained it was because ``we were waiting for
one very special person, who apparently is not going to be able to
get here.''
   Safe Kids is an organization backed by the National Safety
Council and Children's Hospital here to conduct a national campaign
to fight preventable injuries to children.
   The Dunning boy was hit by a car while playing near his home in
August 1985.
   ``Suffering serious neck and leg injuries, Christopher could
easily have been paralyzed had any of the people who treated him
made the slightest mistake,'' Reagan told the group. ``But
fortunately, the paramedics had completed a pediatric trauma
course. And today, he is fully healed.''
   About the time the president was saying these words, Chris's
father, James Dunning, was telephoning Children's Hospital to
confirm the time that the family was supposed to be there for the
trip to the White House.
   He was told that the event already was going on.
   Cooper said the program, originally planned for 1:45 p.m., had
been changed to 11:45 a.m. and the Dunnings hadn't been told,
although other families who were to be present were notified.
   Kim Haddow, a spokeswoman for Safe Kids, confirmed that ``that
is what happened.''
   So, instead of going to the White House, young Chris went off to
the beach with friends, his father said.
   ``I don't think he actually realized what a big deal it was,''
said Haddow.
   He said the White House already had called to say that the
family would be getting an invitation to call on the president soon.
</TEXT>
