<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TimberConvoy     05-13 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Timber Convoy,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Logging Trucks Roll Through Western Montana in Protest Convoy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALISPELL, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convoy of logging trucks so long that
it took at least a half-hour to pass a given point rolled through
western Montana on Friday to protest U.S. Forest Service
regulations lumberjacks say are strangling the industry.
   The trucks began in Eureka, Mont., and proceeded along a
twisting, 200-mile stretch of road through this heavily timbered
area. Motorists pulled to the side of the road and waved in support
as the big trucks passed.
   By the time the trucks rolled through Arlee, the convoy
stretched for 15 miles. Seventy-three lumber trucks, interspersed
with a 100 to 150 support vehicles, were counted. More trucks
joined the convoy along the route.
   Most of the trucks carried slogans spray-painted on their logs,
including ``Save our American timber industry,'' ``Jobs not
wilderness'' and ``Donated to save a mill, not a grizzly.''
   In Kalispell, hundreds came to the curb and waved as the convoy
stopped traffic in the town of 10,000.
   It took the convoy 30 to 45 minutes to pass a given point on the
highway, roadside observers said.
   One logger, Ken Howard of Whitefish, said he hoped
environmentalists will ``back off a little bit after today's event
and let us keep working. They're killing us every day.''
   The protest was aimed at the appeals process that must be
followed in every sale of timber from land in the national forests.
Loggers say environmentalists now routinely file appeals, blocking
timber sales for months or years.
   The trucks traveled at 40 to 45 mph. Organizers said the intent
of the convoy was not to delay traffic needlessly, but the Montana
Highway Patrol warned motorists that the convoy would be impossible
to pass.
</TEXT>
