<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 2125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Minister     05-13 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Minister,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cabinet Minister Resigns After Being Criticized For Comments On
World War II</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An embattled Cabinet minister who said Japan was
not at fault for World War II resigned Friday after complaints at
home and abroad hurt Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's
administration.
   Seisuke Okuno, chief of the National Land Agency, handed in his
resignation late Friday afternoon, said officials in the governing
Liberal Democratic Party.
   Former Construction Minister Hideo Utsumi, 66, was named his
successor. Utsumi told reporters Japan should try to promote good
relations with China, Kyodo News Service reported.
   The affair comes four months before a scheduled visit by
Takeshita to China late this summer.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Yoshifumi Matsuda acknowledged
Thursday that Okuno's statements ``give very serious damage to our
heart-to-heart relations between the two peoples.''
   Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno, who tried to soothe China's
irritation during a visit to Beijing last week, said only, ``We
would like to try harder to promote friendly ties with neighboring
countries.''
   The 75-year-old Okuno, who headed the justice and education
ministries under previous administrations, was widely regarded as
the No. 3 man in the government after Takeshita and Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa.
   At a news conference, Okuno said he stepped down ``not because I
erred,'' but because his remarks had disrupted parliamentary
business.
   The announcement came three weeks after Okuno claimed Japan was
not an aggressor in World War II and had ``fought to protect itself
at a time when the white race had turned Asia into a colony.''
   China, South Korea and North Korea condemned the statements. In
Japan, opposition political parties united in calling for his
resignation. The largest opposition groups, the Japan Socialist
Party and the Komeito (Clean Government Party), were prepared to
submit a no-confidence resolution in Parliament, a Komeito official
said.
   News reports Friday said Takeshita, who avoided disputing
Okuno's remarks or taking action against him, wanted him to step
down voluntarily. Kyodo reported that he put the request to Okuno
in a meeting Friday morning.
   Opposition leaders hailed Friday's outcome as appropriate.
   ``Okuno's remarks violated the spirit of the ... Sino-Japanese
Peace and Friendship Treaty, so his resignation is proper,'' said
Yuichi Ichikawa, parliamentary policy head of the Komeito. ``It was
long overdue.''
   Okuno was the third politician in Takeshita's six-month-old
government to resign amid controversy.
   In February, Koichi Hamada, chairman of the lower house Budget
Committee, resigned after a five-day parliamentary stalemate
following an outburst in which he called an opposition legislator a
``murderer.''
   In November, days after Takeshita became prime minister, lower
house Justice Committee Chairman Hideyuki Aizawa stepped down after
he was charged with evading taxes. Both were ranking officials in
Takeshita's Liberal Democratic Party.
   China and Japan waged an eight-year war beginning in 1937 that
killed an estimated 571,000 Japanese and 1.3 million Chinese
soldiers and an untold number of civilians.
   The two countries signed a treaty in 1972 that says in part,
``The Japanese side is keenly aware of Japan's responsibility for
causing enormous damages in the past to the Chinese people through
war and deeply reproaches itself.''
   It was the hawkish Okuno's third major brush with controversy in
his political career. As Kakuei Tanaka's education minister, he
faced a no-confidence motion in the early 1970s after he called the
Japan Teachers Union a ``dissident group.''
   As justice minister a decade later under Prime Minister Zenko
Suzuki, he was criticized for urging revision of the constitution,
which renounces the use of war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
