<DOCNO> AP880513-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 2128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Amnesty     05-13 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Amnesty,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Chief Of Staff Granted Amnesty on Human Rights Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court gave Gen. Jose
D. Caridi, the army chief of staff, amnesty Friday for any human
rights violations he may have committed while serving under the
former military government.
   The case stemmed from charges of kidnapping, torture and murder
against Caridi and 11 other officers while he was an army colonel
at the Military Institute under former Gen. Santiago Omar Rivero.
Details of the charges were not available.
   Amnesty also was extended by the court action to the other
officers, who include three former generals.
   Under the ``due obedience'' law passed in June 1987, only top
commanders _ in this case Rivero _ can be prosecuted for ordering
violations of human rights during the ``dirty war'' against
leftists in 1976-83.
   The law was proposed by President Raul Alfonsin, whose civilian
government replaced the military regime in December 1983.
   It has resulted in amnesty for about 300 lower-ranking officers
accused of abuses. Court sources say only 20-30 officers, most of
them generals, face prosecution, court sources say.
   At least 9,000 people vanished during the ``dirty war'' and are
presumed dead, according to a government study ordered by Alfonsin
shortly after he took office. Rights groups say the number is
nearer 30,000.
   Five former junta members, including two presidents, were
convicted in 1985 and are serving prison terms ranging from four
years to life.
   Caridi, 56, became chief of staff in April 1987, a few days
after an unsuccessful military revolt at three Army camps. He
replaced Gen. Hector Rios Erenu.
</TEXT>
