<DOCNO> AP880513-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Emancipation     05-13 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Emancipation,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilians Commemorate 100th Anniversary of Abolition of Slavery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slavery was abolished 100 years
ago in Brazil and the country celebrated emancipation Friday with
speeches, concerts, protests and a national holiday.
   President Jose Sarney ordered the expropriation of 250 acres in
northeastern Brazil for the construction of a monument to the 17th
century rebel slave leader Zumbi.
   The Brazilian Symphony Orchestra in Rio put on a free open-air
concert in honor of black contributions to Brazilian culture.
   In cities across the country, all-black groups dressed in white
danced traditional African dances and put on exhibitions of
capoeira, a martial art created by black slaves centuries ago.
   Major Brazilian newspapers carried ads paid for by dozens of
corporations _ including foreign multinationals such as General
Motors and Olivetti _ in honor of emancipation.
   Pele, Brazil's great black soccer star, said in an interview
with the Rio newspaper Jornal do Brasil, ``I'm black and proud of
it. Color never was a problem for me.''
   But he added that blacks should ``try to attain an equality that
doesn't exist.''
   On Thursday night about 300 prominent black actors, musicians
and dancers shouting ``slavery never again'' gathered in downtown
Rio for a mass in celebration of the centennial.
   In Brasilia, the nation's capital, the Congress held a special
session honoring Brazilian blacks. Legislators praised South
African black rights leader Nelson Mandela and condemned that
country's apartheid regime.
   In the northeastern city of Salvador, considered the center of
black culture in Brazil, about 5,000 protesters held a ``march
against racism'' Thursday night and burned a picture of Princess
Isabel, who freed the slaves on May 13, 1888.
   Blacks and mulattoes make up about 80 percent of Brazil's 143
million people. However, they lag far behind whites in education
and earning power and black rights groups say the government
encourages inequality by promoting a false image of the country as
a ``racial democracy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
