<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrakeAdministrator     05-13 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drake Administrator,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Hospital Administrator Sentenced To 30 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Friday ordered the former
administrator of Drake Memorial Hospital to spend 30 days in jail
for falsifying the personnel file of Donald Harvey, the former
nurse's aide who has admitted killing 48 people.
   Former Administrator Jan Taylor was sentenced after he pleaded
no contest to falsifying a public document, a misdemeanor offense.
Taylor was indicted last year on four felony charges of tampering
with evidence for adding information to Harvey's file, but he
pleaded no contest to the misdemeanor count as part of a bargain
with prosecutors.
   Families of Harvey's victims were unhappy that Taylor, 50, was
able to avoid a trial that could have developed information for use
in their civil suits stemming from the killings.
   Harvey, 35, is serving three consecutive life terms in the state
prison at Lucasville after pleading guilty to killing 21 patients
when he worked as a nurse's aide at Drake, a hospital for long-term
care, from 1983 to 1987.
   Harvey used arsenic and cyanide to poison most of his victims,
often putting it in the hospital food he served them, authorities
said.
   Harvey also is serving a simultaneous life sentence for
admitting killing nine people at Marymount Hospital in London, Ky.,
while he worked there in 1970-71. The FBI is looking into Harvey's
claims that he also killed 18 people while working at the Veterans
Administration Medical Center in Cincinnati before he was hired at
Drake.
   Taylor was accused of putting in the personnel file that
Harvey's references had been checked out with previous employers.
Defense attorney R. Scott Croswell said the information was added
because Taylor believed it was his duty to update the file and make
it complete.
   Taylor, who did not hire Harvey, has said that after the
investigation of Harvey had begun, he noticed the information about
references was lacking and had another Drake employee check the
references and add them to the file.
   Precisely what the hospital had done to check Harvey before he
was hired is a matter of dispute in civil suits by victims'
relatives.
   Hamilton County Common Pleas Judge Robert Gorman gave Taylor the
maximum sentence of 180 days in jail, then suspended all but 30
days. He declined to fine Taylor, who could have received up to a
$1,000 fine.
   Gorman said he was giving Taylor a jail sentence because he was
a public figure held to a higher standard than private citizens in
such matters.
   ``This sentence is offered as a deterrent more than a
punishment, and it's a message to others who hold similar office,''
Gorman said.
   Taylor declined to talk to reporters as he left the courtroom.
Gorman said he can remain free for 30 days while he decides whether
to appeal the sentence.
   Relatives of some of Harvey's victims, who sat in the courtroom
Friday, said Taylor and other Drake officials should have stood
trial for their handling of the Harvey case.
   ``I don't really quarrel with the judge as much as I quarrel
with the prosecutor's office,'' said Michael Pike, whose father,
Joseph, 68, was killed by an injection of cleaning fluid last year.
   ``It's a slap in the face to everyone murdered out there,'' Pike
said. ``It's a slap in the face to the families.''
   The victims' families had fought the prosecutor's office to try
to get information obtained in the criminal investigation of
Harvey. The no-contest plea that resulted in the sentencing Friday
cannot be used against Taylor in the civil suits.
</TEXT>
