<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-13 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scattered Thunderstorms Hit East, High Winds in Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered rain and thunderstorms hit the East from the Florida
Keys to New York State on Friday, while a cold front brought strong
gusts to the West.
   Rain also fell over the Pacific Northwest. Sunny skies prevailed
over much of the rest of the nation.
   Thunderstorms developed across the Florida Keys and over western
Pennsylvania in the morning and extended into Ohio and New York
State. Youngstown, Ohio recorded one-third of an inch of rain in
the six hours ended 2 p.m. EDT.
   Showers also stretched from the South Carolina coast across
Georgia and northern Florida.
   A cold front from central Montana to southern Nevada whipped
strong winds over several states and sent temperatures falling
sharply in its wake.
   Livingston, Mont. recorded gusts to 64 mph, and blowing dust
reduced visibility to 3 miles. Winds gusted to 55 mph in Milford,
Utah.
   Wind advisories were posted for parts of the southern California
desert and for southeast Idaho.
   Behind the cold front, temperatures were in the 50s and 60s in
Idaho, well below Thursday's readings in the 80s and low 90s.
   At 3 p.m., temperatures around the nation ranged from 36 degrees
at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich. to 103 at Tucson, Ariz. The nation's
morning low morning was 22 at Gunnison, Colo.
   Rain and thundershowers were forecast Saturday over the northern
Plains and from eastern South Carolina into Florida. Scattered
showers were predicted for northern Maine and northern Washington
State.
   Highs were predicted in the 50s and 60s from New England across
the Great Lakes; in the 60s from the northern Rockies to the
northern Pacific Coast; in the 90s from western Kansas to western
Texas, and in the 90s to about 105 over inland southern California
and the desert Southwest. Highs in the rest of the nation were
forecast in the 70s and 80s.
</TEXT>
