<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CyanideTrial     05-13 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyanide Trial,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cyanide Tampering Jury Questioned; Attorney To Ask for Mistrial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for a woman convicted in the
nation's first death-by-product-tampering trial said Friday that he
will ask for a mistrial in the case.
   Federal public defender Thomas Hillier gave notice of his intent
to ask for a mistrial as jurors in the Stella Nickell case were
ordered back to court to answer questions about whether they were
improperly influenced in reaching a verdict. The formal motion for
a mistrial is expected to be filed next week.
   Hillier did not elaborate on his reasons for seeking a mistrial,
except to say that there was no way to know how the jury's
deliberations were affected by a juror who was privy to information
that was not presented to jurors during the trial.
   Suspicion over juror impartiality had increased since the
verdict Monday.
   Questions were raised when juror Laurel Holliday said an
anonymous phone caller had told her that Mrs. Nickell had failed a
lie-detector test, and later when it was revealed that Ms. Holliday
had filed a lawsuit of her own last year alleging that a product
had been contaminated.
   Under questioning by U.S. District Judge William Dwyer, however,
Ms. Holliday denied she had been improperly influenced in any way
in reaching her verdict.
   The jury took five days to convict Mrs. Nickell, 44, of Auburn,
of contaminating over-the-counter medicine capsules with cyanide.
They included two counts of spiking the capsules that killed her
husband, Bruce Nickell, 52, and a stranger, Susan Katherine Snow,
40, of Auburn, in June 1986.
   She faces possible life imprisonment at a June 17 sentencing.
Prosecutors said she killed her husband to collect $176,000 in life
insurance benefits.
   Her trial was the first under federal anti-tampering statutes
enacted after seven people died in Chicago in 1982 from
cyanide-laced Tylenol. No one was ever charged in that case.
   Ms. Holliday had said she received the anonymous phone call May
6, when jurors were still deadlocked 11-1 in favor of convicting
Mrs. Nickell. Ms. Holliday was the lone holdout.
   Ms. Holliday told Dwyer on Friday, however, that she had
dismissed the information about the lie-detector test from her mind
during deliberation and judged the case on the facts.
   She also said she did not mention her own lawsuit when she was
questioned during jury selection because she did not think it was
relevant.
   After listening to Ms. Holliday's testimony Friday, Hillier said
it raised ``very serious and troubling questions on her ability to
sit on this jury.''
   The other 11 jurors were also questioned. All of them said they
had been unaware during the deliberations of the phone call to Ms.
Holliday or the lie-detector test, and had no idea who could have
placed the call.
   Potential jurors had been asked whether they had ever been party
to a product-tampering case. But Ms. Holliday said she considered
her case one involving a manufacturing error.
   Ms. Holliday had sued Pepperidge Farm Inc. in 1987 after she
allegedly bit into a cracker in 1986 that contained an
aspirin-substitute pill. The matter was settled out of court for
$500, less than two months prior to Ms. Holliday's selection for
Mrs. Nickell's jury.
   ``I still don't see how that relates to Stella Nickell and how I
would determine guilt or innocence,'' Ms. Holliday said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
