<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zanzibar-Protest     05-13 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zanzibar-Protest,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses: Police Fire On Moslem Protesters; One Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on the island of Zanzibar
opened fire on rock-throwing Moslems demonstrating Friday against
criticism of polygamy under Islamic law and one person was killed,
witnesses said.
   The trouble started as the marchers approached State House, the
official residence of the president of this semiautonomous Indian
Ocean Island, said the witnesses, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The Moslems were demonstrating against Sofia Kawawa, head of
Tanzania's national women's organization, who this week criticized
a section of Islamic law which allows a man to have four wives.
   The protesters shouted ``God is great'' and cursed Mrs. Kawawa
as the marched.
   ``There was a commotion between police and the people when the
procession tried to reach State House,'' said one witness reached
by telephone. ``The marchers were stopped and told not to go any
farther.
   ``When they continued, police opened fire. One fellow has died
and several are injured,'' the witness said.
   About 250 police who ringed the presidential residence tried to
stop the procession and some in the crowd began throwing stones,
witnesses said.
   There was no estimate of the number of protesters.
   Another witness said the man who was killed was shot in the
chest and at least three other people were wounded. The witness
said he also saw police clubbing protesters.
   There were unconfirmed reports that the leader of the march,
Sheik Ali Yani, was arrested Friday evening.
   The twin islands of Zanzibar and Pemba together with the
mainland form the Republic of Tanzania.
   The protest march began shortly after the Moslems completed
their noon prayers. Nearly 12 hours after the rioting, the official
government media still had not reported the trouble.
   During a three-day seminar on women and development sponsored by
the ruling Chama Cha Mapinduzi (Revolutionary Party), Mrs. Kawawa
urged Tanzania to abandon all forms of discrimination against
women. She criticized, in particular, Islamic views on polygamy and
inheritance.
   Party chairman Julius Nyerere and President Ali Hassan Mwinyi
spoke in general against the denial of women's rights.
   Nyerere, the most powerful political figure in Tanzania,
deplored people who wrongly use religion to exercise and justify
injustice against women and said it would not be accepted.
   During Friday's prayers, Yani made a scathing attack against the
ruling party. He told his followers that the party had no power to
change the Koran and then led followers on a march toward State
House.
</TEXT>
