<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     05-13 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Candidates Killed, Sinhalese Extremists Blamed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen thought to be Sinhalese
extremists killed two more political candidates and wounded a third
despite government overtures to end such attacks, a military
official said Friday.
   All three targets were Sinhalese running for seats on provincial
councils in elections next month and all were from parties
supporting a July 1987 peace accord with Sri Lanka's Tamil minority.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
three separate attacks on Thursday appeared to be the work of the
People's Liberation Front.
   At least 15 candidates in the provincial elections have been
assassinated. All the killings have been blamed on the
Marxist-oriented Front, which is composed of Sinhalese who think
the Sinhalese-dominated government has been too lenient with Sri
Lanka's Tamil minority.
   On July 29 the government proclaimed a peace plan for ending a
bloody four-year guerrilla war by Tamil separatists, who claim the
Sinhalese majority discriminates against them. Efforts to make
peace with the Tamils caused a backlash among the Sinhalese.
   On Tuesday, President Junius R. Jayewardene announced that a
5-year-old ban on the Front's political activities was lifted.
   Minister of National Security Lalith Athulathmudali said he and
Front leader Rohanna Wijeweera signed a peace accord. Later,
letters issued in Wijeweera's name denied the underground group
reached any understanding.
   The agreement called for the Front to surrender all arms by May
29 and to cease all guerrilla activities immediately.
   In the Thursday attacks, W.K. Siripala, of Jayewardene's United
National Party was shot to death near Ranna, 42 miles south of
Colombo; K.S.L. Fernando, of the United Socialist Alliance, was
killed near Hapugalle, 67 miles south of Colombo, and A.S.
Abeywardene, a United National member, was shot and wounded near
Aluthgama, 36 miles south of Colombo.
   The Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
and the Sinhalese make up 75 percent.
   The peace accord with the Tamils was brokered by India, which
now has more than 50,000 soldiers in Sri Lanka to disarm Tamil
rebels.
   On Friday, Tamil rebels released Lance Cpl. Dilip Bali Shagakar,
an Indian soldier who had been held captive for more than two
months, in the northern village of Shastrikulankulam.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
