<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MultipleKillings     05-13 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Killings,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge To Hold Another Hearing Monday In Simmons Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLARKSVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge said Friday that he will grant
R. Gene Simmons' wish to set a quick execution date if he is
convinced that Simmons is mentally competent to waive his appeal of
the death sentence.
   Simmons, 47, was convicted Thursday of killing a man and a woman
during a 45-minute rampage Dec. 28 in Russellville. After he
surrendered, police found the bodies of 14 relatives on his
property at nearby Dover.
   He is scheduled to stand trial July 18 on those slayings. But
Circuit Judge John S. Patterson said he would hold a hearing Monday
on Simmons' competence and would set an execution date of before
July 18 if he concluded Simmons was not mentally incompetent.
   After he was convicted and the jury set a death sentence
Thursday, Simmons surprised the court by reading a statement
emphatically requesting a quick execution date.
   ``I want no action that will delay, deny, defer or denounce this
very correct and proper death sentence,'' Simmons said in a calm
voice.
   Simmons said that in his case, ``anything short of death would
be cruel and unusual punishment. ... I only ask for what I deserve.
Let the torture and suffering in me end.''
   Simmons' lawyers said they had tried to talk him out of making
the request but had eventually concluded that they had to accede to
his wishes.
   Patterson, who presided over Simmons' four-day trial, refused to
be specific about a sentencing date, except to say it would be
before July 18. State law says the execution date must be at least
30 days after a judgment is entered in a case, which in the Simmons
case is expected to take place Monday.
   The last execution in Arkansas was in 1964.
   John Bynum, who prosecuted Simmons, said Friday that there is no
automatic or mandatory appeal of a death sentence in Arkansas and
that the state would resist any outside group's attempt to block
the execution despite Simmons' stated wishes.
   Under Arkansas law, he said, a person can waive his right to
appeal. He said it would be his position, based on a hearing
conducted Thursday after the sentence was handed down, that ``Mr.
Simmons has knowingly and intelligently waived his right to
appeal.''
   ``My position is that if he demands an immediate execution, he
should be executed,'' Bynum said.
   Simmons was found guilty of capital murder, five counts of
attempted capital murder and first-degree false imprisonment from
the Dec. 28 spree. The jury deliberated less than 1{ hours before
finding him guilty and an additonal two hours before recommending
the death penalty.
   Patterson, following the recommendation, sentenced Simmons to
die by lethal injection and to 147 years in prison on the other
charges.
   The bodies found at the Simmons home included his wife, four
daughters, three sons, two spouses of children, three grandchildren
and a child officials said Simmons fathered by his oldest daughter.
All had been shot or strangled.
   Miss Kendrick, 24, shot at the law office where she worked,
reportedly had spurned Simmons' advances a year before the
shooting. Chaffin, 33, shot at an oil company, was described as a
chance victim.
   ``We're satisfied he's sane and competent ...,'' said Robert E.
Irwin, one of Simmons' attorneys. ``What would you say to people
who contend that you have an obligation to save his life, no matter
what?
   ``The death penalty is here. It's the law of the land. Mr.
Simmons believes what he did warrants the death penalty. He is a
supporter of that penalty.''
   Harris said Simmons didn't plead guilty because he felt like his
best chance of getting the death penalty was to mount a defense.
   Lew Neal, a psychiatrist who examined Simmons, said Simmons told
him that he would have killed himself Dec. 28 if one of his guns
hadn't malfunctioned.
</TEXT>
