<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Portugal-Fatima     05-13 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portugal-Fatima,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Pilgrims Converge on Shrine To Mark Anniversary of
Visions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FATIMA, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of pilgrims prayed at
the Roman Catholic Shrine of Fatima on Friday to mark the 71st
anniversary of the reported appearence of the virgin Mary to three
shepherd children.
   Pilgrims walked tens, sometimes hundreds, of miles to the shrine
in central Portugal to fulfill vows made in thanksgiving for the
recovery of a sick relative or in faith of a cure. Many approached
the basilica on their knees.
   Portuguese newspapers quoted church sources as saying Pope John
Paul II may make a brief visit to the sanctuary in August to
beatify two of the shepherds who died in their childhood.
Beatification is a step toward sainthood.
   The Pope visited Fatima in 1982 to give thanks for his recovery
from bullet wounds inflicted by Turkish assailant Mehmet Ali Agca
in Rome's St. Peter Square exactly one year before.
   A rebel Spanish priest tried to stab the pontiff at Fatima. He
was overpowered by security guards and was sentenced to six years
and six months in jail, then expelled from the country.
   The shrine is built near the site of a holm-oak tree where the
three children, then aged 10, nine and seven, said they saw Mary
appear in visions several times between May 13 and Oct. 13, 1917.
   Lucia, the eldest of the children and the only one still alive,
said Mary gave them a message, part of which the Vatican has kept
secret ever since.
   Another part of the message was said to be a description of the
coming horrors of World War II.
</TEXT>
