<1ST_LINE>r p AM-O'Connor-Veep     05-13 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-O'Connor-Veep,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Justice Says She Wouldn't Accept Vice Presidential
Nomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Supreme Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor
said Friday she would not consider running as a vice presidential
candidate on the Republican ticket.
   ``I've said since I went on the bench I'm in my last job,''
O'Connor said while making an appearance at a ground breaking
ceremony at the University of Nevada-Reno.
   O'Connor, 58, has been mentioned by some political speculators
as one of several possible running mates for Vice President George
Bush, the certain GOP presidential nominee.
   O'Connor was selected in 1981 to sit on the U.S. Supreme Court
and was President Reagan's first high court appointee.
   She was in Reno to help university, state and judicial officials
announce the start of construction of a $3.5 million building as
the site of a National Center for Judicial Education.
   The National Judicial College trains a majority of the nation's
judges. O'Connor attended classes there 14 years ago in preparation
for her job as a state judge in Arizona.
   ``The training I received at the National Judicial College must
have been all right,'' she told about 200 people gathered for the
ground breaking, ``because I seem to have progressed somewhat up
the rungs of the judicial ladder.''
</TEXT>
