<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Deposed President Would Support Aquino</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposed Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
said in an interview Friday he would support the government of
President Corazon Aquino if he were allowed to return to his
homeland.
   Marcos made the pledge in an interview with ABC News in which he
again expressed a wish to return to the Philippines for the funeral
of his mother, Josefa Edralin-Marcos, who died May 4 at the age of
95.
   Mrs. Aquino has rejected earlier pleas to allow his return,
saying he is a threat to national security.
   ``My mother is dead and I'd like to go home,'' Marcos said in
slow, somewhat slurred speech from his home in Honolulu.
   ``I will support the Aquino government to prevent any
adventurism or prevent any attempt at the takeover by the
communists,'' he said.
   ``There is nothing that Madame Aquino should fear from me,'' he
said. ``I mean well. And if I should be any obstacle, we will be
able to work it out.''
   Marcos fled to Hawaii after a civilian-military uprising toppled
his 20-year administration and brought Mrs. Aquino to power in
February 1986.
   Marcos supporters have been linked to several coup attempts
against the Aquino government.
   The Reagan administration barred Marcos from leaving Hawaii
without permission after the Aquino government claimed he had
chartered a plane in January 1987 to return home if a coup attempt
succeeded.
   About 8,000 people marched in Manila on Sunday in support of
allowing Marcos' return for the funeral, and more than 1,000
gathered Sunday in Honolulu for a memorial service.
</TEXT>
