<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Retorts to Jackson Accusation That He's Vague</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lead, ADDS 4 grafs to UPDATE with later appearance.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALY CITY, Calif (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner
Michael Dukakis on Friday dismissed Jesse Jackson's accusation that
he is too vague, pointing to his record as governor and saying that
Jackson's comparison of him with George Bush ``will come as a
surprise to the White House.''
   Hitting back at Jackson on another topic, Dukakis suggested his
Democratic rival's call for a big spending increase for education
``doesn't make any sense'' in the face of federal budget deficits.
   The Massachusetts governor also spoke to students at a high
school in this San Francisco suburb, warning against illegal drugs
and calling for increased public emphasis on education.
   His wife, Kitty, told students of her own 26-year dependency on
diet pills.
   As he began his California campaign, Dukakis came under fresh
attack from Jackson, who is making a last stand in that state's
June 7 primary.
   Jackson called Dukakis' anti-drug programs ``a farce,'' rejected
his education proposals as inadequate and said, ``Like Bush,
Dukakis almost brags about putting forth no plans.''
   Dukakis responded, ``It will come as a surprise to the White
House and Mr. Bush if my views on the world and my style of
political leadership has any similarity to his. One of the things I
have is a record. People don't have to guess about it.''
   He spoke favorably of a Massachusetts drug abuse education and
prevention program that he contended had reduced drug abuse among
students.
   Speaking to about 200 students at Jefferson High School in Daly
City, Dukakis called for more pay for teachers and said, ``That
means we've got to tax ourselves.''
   He later said he was not advocating a federal tax increase for
education. He said that states and local governments were putting
more tax money into education and that teachers should be a
priority.
   At the same time, he responded negatively to Jackson's call for
greatly increasing the federal education budget.
   ``You can't go around talking about $20 billion more for public
education out of the federal budget when you've got a $170 billion
deficit. That doesn't make any sense,'' he said. ``You've got to
pick your priorities and pick them carefully.''
   With a seemingly insurmountable lead in delegates, Dukakis began
campaigning in California, the state with the biggest delegate
prize, a week after Jackson entered the state.
   The Massachusetts governor stopped briefly in Portland, Ore.,
and was campaigning across California Friday and Saturday with one
more stop in Oregon where he faces Jackson in a primary Tuesday.
   He was endorsed by California state Controller Gray Davis, who
praised his commitment to protect the coastline against oil
drilling.
   Dukakis turned aside questions about a running mate, saying he
would not focus on that until after the California primary.
   When asked if he could choose someone who had supported aid to
the Nicaraguan Contras _ aid that Dukakis opposes _ the governor
said no single issue would be a disqualification.
   ``I'm not going to be looking for a clone of Mike Dukakis,'' he
said.
   Dukakis later called for a renewed commitment to education in a
speech to students at California State University-Long Beach.
   He offered a few details on his plan for a $250 million National
Teaching Excellence Fund, including spending to forgive college
loans if students become teachers, and a network of retired
teachers providing specialized classroom instruction in math and
science.
   ``We all know that the next president will inherit an ocean of
Republican red ink,'' Dukakis said. ``He and the Congress will have
to make hard choices on spending. ... And for me, the highest
priority is teaching.''
   For a second day, Dukakis jabbed at Reagan over disclosures the
president's wife consulted an astrologist in determining his
schedule. Dukakis said he had checked the horoscope for himself and
Attorney General Edwin Meese III, and in both cases, ``It said we
were going to be changing our positions.''
</TEXT>
