<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama 3rdLd-Writethru a0799 05-13 0857</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0799,0883</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Claims Talks With U.S. Collapsed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 19-24 ``Asked to...military officers'' with 8
grafs to UPDATE with later Noriega comment calling on U.S.
ambassador to leave country and refusal to talk with State
Department envoy. EDITS to tighten. Pickup 25th graf pvs
``Noriega's lawyers...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA NEGRITA, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega said
Friday that talks with the United States about his departure from
power have collapsed.
   At ceremonies in this rural town marking the anniversary of the
death of a revolutionary hero, Noriega also told The Associated
Press he could run for president in elections next year.
   ``Everything fell apart. Everything fell apart. Everthing
apart,'' Noriega repeated when asked about the talks between Panama
and the Reagan administration to try to resolve the Panamanian
crisis.
   Noriega is chief of Panama's defense forces and the power behind
the civilian government. He was charged in Miami in February with
taking at least $4.6 million in payoffs from Colombia's Medellin
cartel to protect cocaine shipments, launder money, supply drug
laboratories and shelter the gang's leaders from law enforcement.
   Reagan administration officials had said they were discussing
with Noriega the possibility of dropping the drug charges if
Noriega relinquished power.
   When asked in Washington about Noriega's remarks, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater replied, ``He says that all the time. He
said `fall apart' or something similar before. ... We are still
talking. We are still negotiating.''
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III on Friday presented Reagan with
arguments against dismissing drug charges against Noriega,
according to U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner of Miami, who obtained one
of the indictments.
   Kellner told reporters he met Meese twice this week to argue
against such a move and that Meese told him ``he also opposed''
dismissal and ``would convey my thoughts to the president.''
   ``He told me he did that today,'' Kellner added.
   Kellner said it ``would send the wrong message'' to Americans
because the government is cracking down on drug traffickers and
users.
   ``How do we continue ... going after the little fish when the
big fish can walk away?'' Kellner asked.
   U.S. Customs Service Chief William von Raab, whose agency's
investigative efforts contributed to the drug indictments against
Noriega, also said on Friday that Noriega ``should be prosecuted.''
   Noriega visited La Negrita, 90 miles from Panama City, where
Victoriano Lorenzo, a populist revolutionary, was executed by
Colombian authorities on May 15, 1903.
   Although Panama did not gain independence from Colombia until
six months later and although Lorenzo was not fighting for
independence, he is considered a precursor and martyr of Panamanian
nationalism.
   Noriega did not address the crowd of several hundred peasants
and other supporters from nearby towns. Instead, he listened to
three speeches by local authorities denouncing ``Yankee
aggression.''
   As he descended the platform, Noriega was asked if he could run
for president in elections scheduled for next May.
   ``Legally, yes,'' he answered with a broad smile, surrounded by
an adulatory crowd.
   Asked if he was actively considering running for president,
Noriega merely laughed.
   On hand was a ``dignity battalion'' of about 100 men. They had
vintage rifles and were dressed in blue jeans, T-shirts printed
with ``not one step backward,'' and red-and-white baseball caps
saying ``I don't sell out my country.''
   Several such battalions have been formed in recent weeks as the
U.S.-Panamanian crisis deepened and authorities warned of the
danger of a U.S. invasion.
   ``Here, there, the Yankees will die,'' chanted the crowd.
``Against the aggression, popular militias,'' they also chanted.
   Accompanying Noriega, who was dressed in a camouflage combat
uniform, were acting chief executive Manuel Solis Palma, several
Cabinet ministers and more than a dozen military officers.
   Later Friday, during a meeting in Rio Hato, 60 miles southwest
of Panama City, Noriega said of State Department envoy Michael
Kozak: ``Mr. Kozak is here. I have not talked with Mr. Kozak.''
   ``The dignity of Panama is not negotiable while there are
foreign troops on our territory, humiliating our soil, while there
is economic aggression, as long as there are threats, as long as
there is psychological war ... as long as (U.S.) Ambassador Arthur
Davis does not get out.''
   He spoke with journalists during a meeting with representatives
of local governments from around the country.
   Noriega's lawyers plan to appear in court to request dismissal
of the drug charges in about a month. They contend the charges are
politically motivated.
   Noriega and Panamanian government officials contend there simply
is nothing to negotiate with Washington.
   The United States still recognizes Eric Arturo Delvalle, now in
hiding, as Panama's legitimate president. Noriega dismissed him
Feb. 26, the day after Delvalle tried to fire the general.
   In New York, Panamanian opposition leader Ivan Romero, who was
expelled from his country May 6, told The Associated Press in an
interview that he plans to return to Panama on Monday to continue
his struggle against the government.
   Romero, secretary-general of the Christian Democratic Party,
said Friday he was arrested, beaten with a rock, questioned and
held overnight in prison May 6 before being forced onto a plane to
Miami.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
