<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Taiwan 1stLd-Writethru a0620 05-13 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Taiwan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0620,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cooperation In Handling Of Hijacking Sign Of Warming Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADD 2 grafs at end UPDATING with Taiwanese charges
recommended against hijackers</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Taiwan-Hijack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The swift cooperation between China and Taiwan in
handling the hijacking of a jet from the mainland is the latest
sign that tensions are easing between the rival governments.
   Taiwan on Friday returned the hijacked Boeing 737 to China hours
after it landed at a Taiwanese military base with 118 people aboard.
   The Nationalists in Taipei and the Communists in Beijing have
been bitter enemies since they fought a bloody civil war in the
1930s and 1940s. The Nationalists fled to the island province of
Taiwan in defeat in 1949. Each side continues to call itself the
legitimate ruler of all of China.
   Contact between Chinese on the two sides of the 100-mile wide
Taiwan Straits was forbidden by both governments for decades, and
the two sides technically remain at war. But since about 1980,
China has made peace overtures, and Taiwan has begun to ease its
stubborn resistance to all links with the mainland.
   Unofficial contacts between the two sides have increased due to
China's decade-long pursuit of an ``open-door'' policy and Taiwan's
lifting of martial law last fall.
   The greatest step in re-establishing ties came in October when
Taipei loosened a 38-year-old ban on travel to China and began
allowing those with relatives on the mainland to return for family
reunions.
   Since then, more than 65,000 Taiwanese have come to China and
another 75,000 have received permission to make the trip, Taiwan's
Interior Ministry reported last week.
   Indirect mail contact also has been established, with the
International Red Cross relaying mail from Taiwan to the mainland
and correspondence in the other direction going through Hong Kong.
   China's Minister of Posts and Telecommunications in April again
urged that direct mail contact be established.
   Indirect trade is flourishing, also with Hong Kong as an
intermediary. Such trade totalled at least $1.51 billion last year,
up 58.7 percent from 1986.
   Merchants on Taiwan, who in the past surreptitiously invested in
businesses in their mainland ancestral towns, have begun openly
putting millions of dollars into mainland enterprises. China's
official Xinhua News Agency said last week that 36 Taiwanese
businesses had invested a total of $28.5 million in Xiamen, a
leading southeastern port.
   Both the Nationalists and the Communists seek reunification, but
only on their own terms. China says Taiwan's capitalist system
could remain untouched under the same ``one-country, two systems''
reunification plan that will be put into effect when Hong Kong, a
British colony, returns to China in 1997.
   Under that program, China says Hong Kong will be able to keep
its capitalist system for at least 50 years following reunification.
   The first signs of softening between the governments came in
1986, when the pilot of a Taiwanese airliner flew his plane to
Canton.
   Representatives of the Communist and Nationalist authorities met
in Hong Kong to arrange the return of the plane in their first
official contact since 1949. It took nearly three weeks to reach an
agreement.
   A desire to avoid a repeat of the 1986 negotiations may have
been behind Taiwan's swift handling of Thursday's hijacking.
   Taiwan granted political asylum to the two young hijackers but
quickly refueled the plane and allowed it to return across the
Taiwan Straits to Xiamen, where the flight originated.
   The head of China's national airline, CAAC, who earlier
requested the return of the plane, crew and hijackers, sent a
message to the Civil Aeronautic Bureau of Taiwan thanking it for
its cooperation. He made no mention of the two air pirates left
behind.
   Taiwanese officials said Friday morning they ``allowed'' the
plane to leave and said it was flying to Hong Kong. It actually
flew directly to China.
   On Saturday, Taiwanese military officials said the Taiwan
Garrison Command recommended that two hijackers _ Zhang Qingguo,
27, and Long Guiyun, 26 _ be prosecuted for the air piracy.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
command recommended Friday that the Taipei District Court charge
the two with endangering flight safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
