<2ND_LINE>AM-Air-Space America,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flying Ribbon-Cutting For Aerospace Exposition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aerial acrobats filled the skies here Friday at
the opening of the country's first large-scale international
aerospace exposition, Air@Space America '88.
   Vice President George Bush, Gov. George Deukmejian and Mayor
Maureen O'Connor praised the 10-day event at Brown Field as a
showcase for American aviation and space know-how.
   A stunt pilot warmed up the crowd of several thousand with
climbs, dives and rolls, then flew his 1940 Waco biplane
upside-down, eight feet off the ground, and cut a red ribbon
stretched across the runway with the plane's tail.
   A Navy precision parachute team and flyovers by the B-1 bomber
and World War II-vintage aircraft followed.
   The air and trade show, patterned on the biennial expositions at
Paris and Farnborough, England, opened with an invitation-only
preview for dignitaries and representatives of more than 300
aviation and electronics companies.
   Representatives from 48 foreign countries also were invited as
prospective customers for the exhibitors, which include aerospace
and defense companies such as General Dynamics, Hughes Aircraft,
Martin Marietta and Teledyne.
</TEXT>
