<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 2203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Taiwan-Hijack 2ndLd-Writethru a0831 05-13 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-Hijack, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0831,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Garrison Command Recommends Charges Against Hijackers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf ``Military officials...'' with one graf to
UPDATE with maximum death penalty for charges. Pickup 3rd graf pvs
``Lawmakers of...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Taiwan Garrison Command recommended
that two Chinese hijackers, already granted political asylum here,
be prosecuted for forcing a Chinese jetliner to Taiwan, officials
reported Saturday .
   Military officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
command recommended Friday that the Taipei District Court charge
Zhang Qingguo, 27, and Long Guiyun, 26, with endangering flight
safety. The maximum sentence for committing such a crime is the
death penalty.
   Lawmakers of the governing Nationalist Party said in a statement
issued Friday, ``They (the hijackers) had noble goals, but their
methods were mean.'' The two young workers commandeered the Boing
737 shortly after it took off Thursday evening with 118 people
aboard from communist China's coastal city of Xiamen in Fujian
province. The two men made the pilot fly to a military air base in
central Taiwan.
   After more than five hours in Taiwan, authorities allowed the
plane to return to Xiamen early Friday morning with everyone aboard
except the two hijackers, who were quickly granted asylum. No one
was hurt.
   Government spokesman Shaw Yu-ming said Friday the two hijackers
were allowed to stay because they would have faced ``their doom''
if sent back home. While denouncing hijacking, he called their
motives ``simple and noble.''
   The Nationalist government, which fled to Taiwan from the
Chinese mainland after losing a civil war to the communists in
1949, still claims to be the rightful ruler of all China and
remains technically at war with Beijing.
   A group of nine legislators, however, condemned the two
hijackers for threatening the lives of passengers aboard the plane
and urged the government to treat them as criminals and put them on
trial.
   It was reported earlier that authorities and lawmakers here were
concerned that the quick granting of asylum would tarnish Taiwan's
image.
   The incident was the first hijacking of a Chinese commercial
airliner to Taiwan.
   ``We would have been sending them to their doom if we turned
them back to the communists,'' Shaw said.
   ``They have risked their lives to seek freedom and democracy. We
must respect their wishes and offer them protection.''
   In a television interview, the air pirates triumphantly detailed
their do-or-die mission.
   Zhang, a worker at an arsenal in south China's Yunnan province,
told the official Chinese Television Service he and his companion,
Long, a steelworker from neighboring Guizhou province, used a toy
pistol and a bottle of fake explosives to force the plane to Taiwan
late Thursday.
   ``We would have committed suicide if we failed,'' Zhang said in
the televised interview. ``We never planned to return (to China).''
   In 1983, six Chinese hijacked a Chinese airliner to South Korea
and spent less than a year in jail there before resettling in
Taiwan, where they received a hero's welcome and financial support.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
