<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cyprus-Lebanon     05-13 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyprus-Lebanon,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cyprus Turns Back Lebanese After Car Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Friday turned back 13
Lebanese who arrived from Beirut, in line with toughened security
checks after a car bomb explosion killed three people and wounded
15 in the Cypriot capital.
   President George Vassiliou said police would take ``greater
steps to check foreigners'' who enter Cyprus following the
Wednesday blast, which police said was planned by two Lebanese men
and was a bungled attack on the Israeli Embassy.
   The 13 were among 53 passengers, mostly Lebanese, who were
aboard the regular Middle East Airlines Flight 261 that landed at
Larnaca Friday.
   Buland Sadek, Cyprus station manager for the Lebanese national
airline, said police told him the 13 were declared not welcome and
ordered to return to Lebanon. Their passports were not given entry
stamps and they later flew back to the Lebanese capital aboard the
same plane when it made its return flight.
   An immigration department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said entry was refused because the 13 had ``not enough
reason for staying in Cyprus.''
   Yasser Arafat, leader of the Palestine Liberation Organization,
sent a message to Vassiliou denouncing the bombing.
   A government announcement said Arafat's message also expressed
condolences for the victims.
   The explosion brought angry demands for strong action against
Middle East terrorism on this Mediterranean island nation.
   Vassiliou said counter-terrorist units would be reinforced,
``particularly with a view to follow up the activities of Arab
visitors.''
   The local PLO office issued a statement shortly after the blast
denying involvement and denouncing ``this ugly crime.''
   Earlier, an anonymous caller telephoned the American television
network NBC in New York claiming responsibility for the blast in
the name of the notorious anti-Arafat Palestinian terrorist leader
Sabri al-Banna, better known as Abu Nidal.
   Police kept the explosives-laden car from parking in front of
the embassy, and it exploded on a bridge 200 yards away, killing
the driver and two Cypriot passers-by.
</TEXT>
