<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Jet Crash,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Royal Air Force Jet Crashes Near Village, No Injuries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWGALE, Wales (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Royal Air Force training jet crashed
Friday less than 300 yards from this village, which escaped a
similar crash two years ago, the RAF and police said.
   The instructor and trainee pilot parachuted to safety and no
injuries were reported.
   Lawmakers called for an inquiry of the incident in which a Hawk
training jet that had taken off from a nearby RAF base at Brawdy
crashed after developing engine trouble.
   Barbara Jones, a resident of the village, witnessed the crash.
   ``I saw the plane shaking uncontrollably,'' she said. ``The next
second it hit a field and plowed through a hedge before exploding.
Another few hundred yards and it would have hit our village.''
   In July 1986, a U.S. Air Force Phantom jet crashed into the sea
off Newgale during the base's annual air display. Two U.S. airmen
died.
</TEXT>
