<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MOVEAnniversary     05-13 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MOVE Anniversary,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poets Call for Justice, Neighbors Hope its Over on MOVE
Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poets lit candles and released 11 balloons
Friday to mark the moment three years ago that police bombed a
rowhouse held by the radical group MOVE in a fiery battle that left
11 people dead.
   Meanwhile, police girded against the possibility of violence by
MOVE members in the now-rebuilt neighborhood devastated by 1985
fire. Barricades manned by police officers were erected at either
end of one street.
   At a memorial service, about 50 people listened to poetry about
the battle. At 5:27 p.m. about 40 lit candles at the exact time
police dropped the bomb to dislodge a rooftop bunker. The bomb
touched off a fire that destroyed 61 houses.
   Lamont B. Steptoe released 11 white balloons and his voice
echoed off nearby Independence Hall as he recited a poem in which
he said, ``The fire has never gone out _ there will always be a
fire for us.''
   The tone at the ceremony was decidedly bitter, with participants
criticizing the long-awaited report of a grand jury that
investigated the event for two years. The grand jury last week
blasted blasted Mayor W. Wilson Goode and other city officials for
``morally reprehensible behavior'' but recommended no criminal
charges.
   ``Justice has to be served before you can forgive, I think,''
said Bob Small, who read some of his poetry. ``It's like they had
the Nuremberg trial, then found the Nazis innocent.''
   At Osage Avenue, the site of the shootout and fire, 5:27 p.m.
came and went with few people noticing the time. Children rode
bikes and scooters in the narrow street and a number of people sat
in front of rowhomes rebuilt two years ago.
   A MOVE member not involved in the battle was released from
prison Friday after serving time for her role in an earlier
confrontation with police, and there was concern that MOVE members
would gather on the street as they had done for the last two years
on May 13.
   Earl Watkins, sitting in front of his rebuilt house almost
directly across from the site of the old MOVE house, said he hoped
they would not show.
   ``This is my prayer that nothing happens tonight _ in fact I'm
hoping that this is the end of it anyway,'' said Watkins, 76.
   ``We went through all that mess and then every year we have to
put up with this,'' Watkins said, gazing down the street at the
barricade where a TV truck had pulled away. ``I think this is the
end of it _ I think it will be if the media let it go.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
