<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0800 05-13 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0800,0515</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Hebert obit. An AMs separate moved as a0749 on Baker.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Chet Baker</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chet Baker, 59, an American jazz
trumpeter famed for his 1950s appearances with Gerry Mulligan, died
Friday after falling from the second floor of his Amsterdam hotel.
   Famed for the thin, cool tone of his trumpet playing, Baker set
the the standard for what jazz buffs knew as the ``cool school.''
   In 1952, he was working with Charlie Parker on the West Coast
when he joined Mulligan, a baritone saxaphonist, and the rest of
his piano-less quartet.
   In 1953, Baker topped the Metronome trumpet poll and started his
own quartet. His work became more assured and outgoing. In 1955 he
took a group to Europe that showed high promise. Then his career
started to suffer, from narcotics, arrests, headlines and a
backlash against the fact he'd been overrated at the beginning.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Michael Blecker</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLLEGEVILLE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Blecker, a former president
of St. John's University, died Thursday of cancer at age 57.
   Blecker attended North Country Day School in Winnetka, Ill. He
received a bachelor's degree in history from Harvard University and
entered St. John's Abbey in 1955.
   He was ordained June 4, 1960, took advanced study and succeeded
the Rev. Colman Barry in 1971 as the university's ninth president.
He served as president for 11 years.
   Blecker resigned from St. John's in 1982 to become president of
the Graduate Theological Union in Berkeley, Calif. While there, he
helped complete the Flora Lamson Hewlett Library, one of the four
largest theological libraries in the country.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Art Collier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Art Collier, a regional sales executive for
United Press International and former sports director for an
Atlanta television station, died Thursday. He was 57.
   Collier was in charge of sales for the news service in Georgia,
Alabama and Mississippi. He also had been sports editor of UPI
Newstime, a cable TV operation, and division manager of UPI's
Atlanta bureau. He had worked for UPI since 1978.
   From 1964 to 1972, he was sports director of WQXI-TV, now
WXIA-TV. He also worked for the Georgia Network and WRNG Radio, and
did play-by-play of Georgia Tech football games from 1968 to 1970.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Sidney Hebert</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW IBERIA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sidney ``Cap'' Hebert, a well-known jazz
musician and a founder of one of the first Dixieland bands in Cajun
Louisiana, died Friday at the age of 87.
   Hebert, whose melodic phrasing and mellow tones were reminiscent
of the Bix Beiderbecke style, played trumpet and piano.
   He helped found The Louisiana Six, one of the first Dixieland
bands in Acadiana. The band, organized in the early 1920s, was
built around three Hebert brothers and one sister.
   The group played mostly in south Louisiana dancehalls, before
nightclubs became popular and cut an album long before recordings
became popular.
   After retiring from his musical career, Hebert continued to play
at the annual New Iberia Sugarcane Festival.
</TEXT>
