<DOCNO> AP880513-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 2258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CourtMartial     05-13 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Court Martial,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third Trial Barred In Lindsey Scott Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginia's attorney general Friday said
that an ex-Marine cleared by a military jury in the 1983 rape and
attempted murder of another soldier's wife cannot be tried in state
court for the offense.
   Attorney General Mary Sue Terry, responding to an inquiry from
Prince William County Commonwealth's Attorney Paul Ebert, said that
bringing former Cpl. Lindey Scott to trial in state court would
amount to double jeopardy.
   Scott, 32, of Louisville, Ky., was convicted in a court-martial
in 1983, but the verdict was overturned on appeal. He was found
innocent at a second court-martial Feb. 19 after more than four
years in prison.
   He was discharged from the Marines after his acquittal.
   Earlier this week, Ebert, whose jurisdiction borders Quantico
Marine Corps Base, where the alleged attack took place, said he was
unconvinced of Scott's innocence, and he asked Terry if he could
prosecute Scott.
   After Ebert questioned Scott's innocence, John Leino, one of
Scott's defense attorneys, charged, ``Apparently, they're going for
the best two out of three.''
   ``Here we are months after the trial and the state prosecutor of
Prince William County wants to take a shot at him,'' he said.
``Who's next, Manhattan South?''
</TEXT>
