<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HostageOfficer 3rdLd-Writethru a0836 05-13 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostage Officer, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0836,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Found Dead After Standoff</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with autopsy result that
officer killed one of two captors, other died of self-inflicted
wound; PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `The officer ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PD8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD GREEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A policeman held hostage for eight hours
by two robbery suspects escaped unharmed Friday after he grabbed a
gun and killed one of his drug-impaired captors, police said.
   The second suspect later killed himself, state Medical Examiner
Dr. Larry V. Lewman said after autopsies on the two men.
   Officer Larry Strayer, 43, a seven-year veteran of the force,
was unharmed, police said.
   ``Please get me out of here,'' the officer said at one point
during his ordeal. ``They indicated this is the last time I can
talk on the radio. If anybody rushes the door, I'm dead.''
   The dead men were identified as Michael Richard Ager, 37; and
Albert Wesley Reinhart, 42, both of Tacoma, Wash.
   Lewman said Reinhart was shot three times by Strayer, dying from
wounds to his chest and lungs. Strayer shot Ager once in the leg,
and Ager later died of a self-inflicted gunshot wound to the chest,
Lewman said.
   The officer was taken hostage about 8 p.m. Thursday when he went
to the Portland Rose Motel to question the men about the robbery of
a nearby supermarket earlier in the evening. The men demanded
Dilaudid, a form of morphine, and safe passage out of the motel.
   At 4 a.m., Strayer seized a gun from his captors, firing about
five times and wounding at least one of them before escaping, said
police spokesman Henry Groepper.
   The men's drug problems may have made it easier for Strayer to
flee, Groepper said.
   ``The individuals ... apparently had a strong need for drugs,''
he said, and were ``very irritable.''
   ``I think the time just wore them out.''
   Gunshots were heard inside the motel room on two occasions after
the officer escaped, but there was no exchange of gunfire with
officers outside, Groepper said.
   After lobbing tear gas into the room and getting no response,
police sent a remote-controlled, camera-equipped robot device into
the room and discovered the bodies at about 10:30 a.m.
   Reinhart was arrested April 22 on robbery, theft and weapons
charges and unauthorized use of a motor vehicle, said Multnomah
County sheriff's spokesman Jim Davis. Reinhart posted bail on the
firearm charge May 4 and the remaining charges were dropped because
there was no complainant, Davis said.
   Ager was arrested May 2 on robbery and weapons charges and
unauthorized use of a motor vehicle. The charges against him also
were dismissed, Davis said.
   During the 14{-hour standoff, authorities closed a two-mile
stretch of Interstate 5 and nine blocks of Barbur Boulevard, a
major roadway. Traffic was backed up for miles during the morning
rush hour, and several businesses on Barbur were unable to open
Friday morning.
   Strayer was checking a tip that two suspicious men were staying
at the motel, located near a grocery store that was robbed about 7
p.m. He was admitted to the motel room by one man, Groepper said.
   Groepper said other officers brought a witness from the store
robbery who identified the man as a suspect. But as the officers
were handcuffing him, another man emerged from the bathroom and
pointed a gun at police.
   He said the gunman took Strayer hostage and forced the other
officers out of the motel room.
   Groepper said Strayer was unavailable for interviews.
</TEXT>
