<1ST_LINE>s w BC-Reagan-Books Adv15   05-13 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Reagan-Books, Adv 15,0268</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 15, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Reagan Shelf</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Reagan-Writ Large</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are Reagan administration figures or
family members who have written books about the president:
   Martin Anderson, former assistant to the president for policy
development, ``Revolution,'' 1988.
   T.H. Bell, former education secretary, ``The Thirteenth Man,''
1987.
   James S. Brady, press secretary, editor of ``Ronald Reagan, a
Man True to His Word,'' quotations and maxims, 1981.
   Anne M. Burford, former Environmental Protection Agency
administrator, ``Are You Tough Enough?'' 1986.
   Patti Davis, daughter of Ronald and Nancy Reagan, ``Home
Front,'' a novel that is a thinly disguised autobiography, 1986.
   Michael K. Deaver, former deputy White House chief of staff,
``Behind the Scenes,'' 1987.
   Alexander Haig, former secretary of state, ``Caveat: Realism,
Reagan and Foreign Policy,'' 1984.
   Jeane Kirkpatrick, former U.N. ambassador, ``The Reagan
Phenomenon and Others Speeches on Foreign Policy,'' 1982; and ``The
Reagan Doctrine and U.S. Foreign Policy,'' 1985.
   Henry Haller, former White House chef, ``The White House
Cookbook,'' 1987.
   Michael Reagan, adopted son of Ronald Reagan and actress Jane
Wyman, ``On the Outside Looking In.'' 1988.
   Donald Regan, former White House chief of staff and treasury
secretary, ``For the Record: From Wall Street to Washington,'' 1988.
   David Stockman, former director of the Office of Management and
Budget, ``The Triumph of Politics: Why the Reagan Revolution
Failed,'' 1986.
   Larry Speakes, former presidential spokesman, ``Speaking Out,''
1988.
   James G. Watt, former interior secretary, ``The Courage of a
Conservative,'' 1985.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 15</NOTE>
