<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-13 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0515</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales fell 0.6 percent in April, the
first setback in six months, with the decline blamed on an early
Easter, bad weather and a bigger federal tax bite for some people.
   The Commerce Department reported Thursday that consumers spent a
seasonally adjusted $131.6 billion at retail stores last month, a
drop of $815 million from the revised March figure.
   Economists said they weren't concerned by the weakness,
especially because sales in March were revised upward to show an
increase of 1.7 percent. That was the fastest sales advance since
last August and almost twice the originally estimated 0.8 percent
gain for the month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation paranoia has gripped the financial
markets, which only a few months back were preoccupied with the
threat of a recession. But some economists say the specter of
rising prices is highly exaggerated.
   These economists maintained Thursday that unlike the in 1970s,
when price spirals became ingrained, the economy of the 1980s has
been reshaped by fundamental changes that have restrained costs and
wages, two key components of inflation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has
urged the House to follow the Senate's lead and pass major
legislation to give banks new securities underwriting powers.
   Greenspan said Thursday that the Federal Reserve favored the
approach taken by the Senate, which in late March approved
legislation that would repeal most restrictions of the
Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act. That statute bars a mingling of
the banking and securities industries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. banks are undercapitalized and
underregulated and have failed to write down approximately $28
billion in uncollectable foreign loans, according to the General
Accounting Office.
   In its report released Thursday, the GAO, an investigative arm
of Congress, found fault with federal regulators such as the Office
of the Comptroller of the Currency, the Federal Reserve Board and
the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. for creating a lenient
classification system for developing country debt.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen of the nation's airlines face fines
totaling nearly $6.5 million for a variety of alleged violations of
safety and security rules, the Federal Aviation Administration
reports.
   Chicago-based United Airlines could face a fine of $1,262,100,
the biggest of the proposed penalties, the FAA indicated Thursday.
The next highest proposed fine is against Hawaiian Airlines,
$1,169,000, followed by Continental, $982,130; Eastern Airlines,
$893,500; Braniff, $518,000; American Airlines, $421,250, and
Northwest Airlines, $371,000.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has
proposed a new method of regulating interstate telephone rates and
estimated the plan could save consumers $1.6 billion over the next
four years.
   The FCC plan, announced on Thursday, calls for scrapping current
limits on the profits American Telephone & Telegraph Co. and local
phone companies can earn on the interstate portion of their
businesses and setting caps on prices the companies can charge. The
companies could opt for price caps or for current regulation.
</TEXT>
