<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. said it set up a committee of
three independent directors to hold talks with its two suitors,
Bank of New York Co. and Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA.
   But Bank of New York maintained Thursday it had no intention of
sweetening its hostile $1.08 billion bid, and was not holding any
negotiations with Irving.
   Irving disclosed the special committee in a filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission on Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A substantial number of workers at a
General Electric Co. defense plant here will be laid off because of
a drop in orders from the Pentagon, the company has announced.
   Arthur Glenn, vice president of GE's Defense Systems Division,
refused Thursday to say exactly how many workers would be laid off
or when.
   But GE officials informed the state it would lay off about 900
workers over the next 18 months due to a decrease in
defense-related orders, according to a state economic affairs
official.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Aerospace PLC has acted to protect itself
from the pound's recent surge by contracting some of its Airbus
jetliner work to Textron Inc. of the United States.
   The $700 million agreement, announced on Thursday, calls for
Textron to manufacture wing parts at its factory in Nashville, Tenn.
   British Aerospace said the contract was denominated in dollars,
which would reduce its risks from further rises in the pound that
could make its Airbus work too costly.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds have risen to
the highest level in 15 months in the government's latest auction.
   The average yield in Thursday's auction was 9.17 percent, up
from 8.51 percent at the last auction on Feb. 4. It was the highest
rate since 30-year bonds averaged 9.28 percent on Feb. 18, 1986.
   A total of $8.5 billion in bonds were sold out of bids totaling
$21.7 billion as the Treasury completed the third debt auction this
week, raising $26 billion to replenish government coffers.
</TEXT>
