<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryAuction     05-13 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Auction,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields on 30-Year Bonds Hit 15-Month High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds rose in the
government's latest auction to the highest level in 15 months.
   The average yield was 9.17 percent on Thursday, up from 8.51
percent at the last auction on Feb. 4. It was the highest rate
since 30-year bonds averaged 9.28 percent on Feb. 18, 1986.
   The bonds will carry a coupon interest rate of 9[ percent, with
each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,954.20.
   A total of $8.5 billion in bonds were sold out of bids totaling
$21.7 billion as the Treasury completed the third debt auction this
week, raising $26 billion to replenish government coffers.
   The refunding auctions, held quarterly, provide the main source
of financing for the $2.5 trillion national debt.
</TEXT>
