<DOCNO> AP880513-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Levolor Bjt   05-13 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Levolor, Bjt,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Feud Casts Shadow On Blinds Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Levolor Lorentzen Inc., which pioneered the
manufacture of decorator window mini-blinds, may be up for sale
because of a rift among family members who own the 77-year-old
Parsippany-based company.
   The privately-held company has hired an unidentified broker to
evaluate its worth and marketability, according to a company
spokesman.
   ``There's a family dispute. The family dispute does not affect
day-to-day operations,'' said the spokesman, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   The problem apparently centers on the stake controlled by Jane
Lorentzen, the widow of one of the company founder's three
children. She holds between 40 percent and 49 percent of Levolor's
stock, said Levolor's general counsel, Bohdan Porytko.
   The other major shareholders are Chairman Eric Lorentzen _ who
has majority voting control _ and his sister, Karen Lynam. They and
Jane Lorentzen's husband H. Peter Lorentzen, who was vice chairman
and died three years ago, are the offspring of company founder Hans
K. Lorentzen.
   Porytko would not comment in detail on the family squabble, but
did say Jane Lorentzen had approached other stockholder family
members ``to discuss what could be done to make the shares held by
(Peter Lorentzen's) estate more liquid.''
   Family discussions, after the broker's evaluation, could lead to
a number of options, he said. Porytko would not rule out sale of
the Jane Lorentzen stake to other family members or the company's
sale to an outsider.
   According to an industry source who spoke on condition of
anonymity, several home furnishing concerns have examined the
possibility of buying Levolor, but have dropped the idea.
   Eric Lorentzen could not be reached for comment Thursday and did
not return a telephone message.
   But in a statement last week, he said:
   ``My father who founded the company, Hans K. Lorentzen, would
state that everything is for sale at the right price except my wife
and children. It should be pointed out, given that philosophy, that
the company has remained in the Lorentzen family for 77 years.''
   Levolor has become one of the most recognized brand names in the
so-called ``alternative window covering'' business with its
colorful and fashionable mini-blinds, replacing the image of
old-fashioned wide, dusty Venetian blinds.
   Through marketing that captured the imagination of designers,
interior decoration magazines and consumers, Levolor has taken a
major portion of the more than $1.2 billion wholesale market for
``hard'' window coverings with its 1-inch mini-blinds, half-inch
micro-blinds, vertical blinds and pleated blinds.
   The company did a ``brilliant job of marketing, of developing, a
product consciousness as well as a brand consciousness,'' said
Donald Hogsett, business editor of the trade publication Home
Textiles Today.
   Levolor claims as its innovations an early device that better
lowers and raises blinds evenly and a plastic wand to operate the
slats.
   In fact, the company derives its name from the leveling device,
``Lev;'' a wheel symbol representing it, ``o;'' and the first three
letters of the family name, ``lor.''
   Porytko said 1987 sales were between $200 million and $300
million. The company has been valued at $100 million, but Porytko
disputes the figure.
   Levolor's 3,000 employees work at 20 locations nationwide. Its
major buyer is Sears, Roebuck and Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880513-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0800EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Ford-Shareholders     05-13 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford-Shareholders,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Looking for 30 Percent Contribution to Earnings From
Financial Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. is building its financial services
division as well as it core automaking business and is seeking a
major acquisition in the electronics industry, Ford Chairman Donald
Petersen said.
   The No. 2 automaker has about $10 billion in cash reserves and
has been seeking a major acquisition for some time, but Petersen
said he's in no hurry.
   ``We've become quite impressed by how many more poor
acquisitions have been made than good ones'' by other companies,
Petersen told reporters after the company's 33rd annual
shareholders' meeting on Thursday.
   Petersen estimated Ford's Financial Services Group eventually
would contribute as much as 30 percent of corporate profits due to
expansion and acquisitions. He did not give a time frame, however.
   The financial services division, which includes Ford Motor
Credit and First Nationwide, currently contributes about 18 percent
to Ford's earnings.
   At General Motors Corp., financial services contributed 42
percent of 1987 earnings, but GM spokesman Terry Sullivan said the
figure was higher than usual because of very low automotive
earnings.
   By contrast, General Motors Acceptance Corp., the subsidiary
which contains GM financial service businesses, contributed about
26 percent of GM's earnings in 1985.
   Petersen also said Ford would reduce its equity in Hertz. He
said the company bought the auto rental and leasing firm as ``a
defensive move.''
   ``Hertz could have been acquired by a company that would not
continue the close relationship with Ford'' in buying Ford cars, he
said after the meeting.
   Ford spokesman Tom Foote said Ford owns at least 90 percent of
Hertz, with Hertz management holding the rest of the company.
   Petersen said Ford has raised its forecast of 1988 auto industry
sales, imported and domestic, to 15.3 million _ 10.2 million cars
and 5.1 million trucks _ from 15 million forecasted earlier.
   ``We think the general economy is going on quite well,''
Petersen said after the meeting, adding ``there's every reason to
believe our economy will continue its modest growth in 1989.''
   Attendance at Friday's annual meeting was the lowest in Ford's
history, coinciding with a year in which Ford's earnings were the
highest in automotive history.
   Ford earned $4.6 billion in 1987 and another record $1.6 billion
in the first quarter of 1988.
   It also was the first meeting since Henry Ford II's death and
the first meeting since Ford's son, Edsel Ford II, and his nephew,
William Clay Ford Jr., were elected to Ford's board of directors in
January.
   Henry Ford II died in September at age 70. Edsel Ford II, 39, is
general sales manager of the Lincoln-Mercury Division. William Clay
Ford Jr., 30, is chairman and managing director of Ford Switzerland.
   The two young Fords and William Clay Ford Sr., vice chairman of
the board, represent the Ford family's 40 percent voting interest
in the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880513-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0805EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Halliburton-Gearhart     05-13 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Halliburton-Gearhart,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials: Halliburton To Acquire Gearhart In Stock, Cash Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Halliburton Co. has agreed to acquire
Gearhart Industries for about $275 million in cash and stock, the
oilfield services companies have announced.
   But a Houston-based oil service company, challenging the merger
plan, has doubled its position in Gearhart senior debt notes, and
the businesses face other hurdles in the plan.
   Energy Service Co. has acquired $37.2 million in principal
amount of the 8|-percent senior subordinated notes issued by
Gearhart, officials said. That raises Ensco's ownership of senior
notes to $66.7 million in principal amount, which represents a
majority of that debt series class, officials said.
   The additional debt notes acquired ``gives us a controlling
position in that class of Gearhart debt,'' said Cris Gaut, Ensco's
chief financial officer. The Halliburton-Gearhart merger plan
``wasn't a done deal,'' Gaut said.
   The acquisition was contingent on final agreements with Gearhart
creditors, and approval by Gearhart shareholders and federal
regulators.
   U.S. Justice Department officials said they were reviewing the
plan.
   In the plan, Gearhart common and preferred shareholders would
receive less than proposed in an earlier offer, so that Halliburton
can increase the payout to holders of Gearhart debt and redeemable
preferred stock.
   Halliburton, under the definitive agreement, would exchange
.02917 of a share of its own stock for each outstanding share of
Gearhart common stock and three series of Gearhart preferred stock.
   Target date for completing the merger is Aug. 31, according to
Chairman Marvin Gearhart.
   Halliburton closed Thursday at $32.37{ a share, up 87{ cents on
the New York Stock Exchange. Based on that price, the stock swap
would be worth about 94 cents per share of Gearhart, which closed
at about 87{ cents a share, down 6.25 cents, on the NYSE.
   In a tentative agreement announced Feb. 24, the initial exchange
ratio was for .03575 shares of Halliburton for each Gearhart share.
   Officials said the exchange ratio was lowered in order to
increase the amount paid to holders of certain Gearhart senior
debt, subordinated debt and redeemable preferred stock. These debt
and securities holders would receive about $230 million in cash.
   In late February, the companies first announced merger plans.
The much-smaller Gearhart is based in Fort Worth and provides
wireline and geophysical services to the oil industry that aid in
the location of petroleum deposits.
   It posted a loss of $3 million in the year ended Jan. 31 on
revenue of $297.3 million. Gearhart had a $337 million loss in its
previous fiscal year.
   Dallas-based Halliburton provides oilfield services and also is
involved in construction, engineering and insurance. Halliburton
posted a first quarter profit of $31.8 million, or 30 cents a
share, on revenue of $1.04 billion.
</TEXT>
