<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Navistar-WisconsinSteel     05-13 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Navistar-Wisconsin Steel,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navistar Deal To Sell Off Wisconsin Steel Called `Sham'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navistar International Corp.'s sale of its
money-losing Wisconsin Steel unit in 1977 was part of a strategy to
leave the steel business, not an attempt to avoid pension
obligations to workers, a company attorney says.
   But lawyers for two plaintiffs in a lawsuit against the
Chicago-based manufacturing concern said Thursday they would prove
Navistar misled Wisconsin Steel's buyer into believing the company
could be profitable.
   The long-awaited U.S. District Court trial that began Thursday
is considered an important test case to determine whether _ and to
what extent _ a company can be forced to honor pension-plan
obligations to workers.
   Navistar faces two lawsuits resulting from the ill-fated 1977
sale of Wisconsin Steel to Envirodyne Inc., a Los Angeles-based
engineering company with no previous steel-making experience.
   The South Side Chicago steel mill went bankrupt eight years ago,
putting 3,500 employees out of work and leaving the Pension Benefit
Guaranty Corp., the federal insurer of pensions, with the tab for
unpaid pension benefits.
   In the bench trial before U.S. District Judge James Moran, the
pension insurer is seeking $140 million from Navistar to cover the
unpaid benefits plus interest.
   And Wisconsin Steel creditors, led by an Envirodyne unit, the
EDC Holding Co., have filed a separate lawsuit seeking triple
damages of nearly $475 million from Navistar.
   That suit alleges fraud and racketeering in the sale of the
steel company in 1977, when the company had a string of five years
of financial losses.
   Navistar attorney Philip Beck said in his opening argument that
Wisconsin's steel demise was the result of ``a combination of
external factors,'' including a six-month strike against Navistar,
a Wisconsin steel customer, immediately before the mill collapsed
in 1980, and the effects of two successive harsh winters.
   And he denied that Navistar, known as International Harvester
Co. in 1977, intended to dupe Envirodyne in the sale _ for which it
lent Envirodyne $50 million of the $65 million acquisition price.
   Rather, Beck said, the sale was part of Navistar's move out of
the steel business in order to concentrate on its core
farm-equipment and truck-manufacturing businesses.
   But pension-insurer attorney William O. Bittman said company
officials ignored recommendations from their investment bankers,
Lehman Bros., that the sale was financially questionable because
Envirodyne lacked the experience and funds to turn the steel
company around.
   He said company officials were aware at the time that the deal
might lead to lawsuits if the steel company went bankrupt, but went
ahead with the sale to Envirodyne in order to avoid $167 million in
losses it faced by liquidating Wisconsin Steel.
   ``I think Navistar sold Wisconsin Steel to a buyer that they
knew did not have the experience or the financial wherewithal to
run the steel division in an economic way,'' Bittman said in an
interview Thursday.
   Navistar has already reached a $14.8 million out-of-court
settlement with 2,700 former employees of the steel company.
   The case adjourned late Thursday until Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
