<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ChryslerContract     05-13 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler Contract,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Skilled Trades Workers Reject Chrysler Pact; Leaders Meeting in
Chicago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. skilled trades workers rejected a
United Auto Workers contract that was ratified despite their vote,
and union officials scheduled a meeting to determine the reason for
the rejection.
   The two-year contract, covering 66,000 hourly and salaried
workers, was ratified Wednesday by 54 percent of those voting. But
skilled trades workers, more than 10,500 of Chrysler's UAW
employees, voted against ratification.
   The skilled trades rejection has no effect on the overall
ratification, but could lead to new negotiations solely on skilled
trades issues.
   The problem is that skilled trades workers, like salaried
workers, are covered both by the main contract and by a separate
pact the deals only with skilled trades issues, such as
apprenticeships.
   Skilled trades and salaried workers cast one vote each that
covers both pacts.
   So at a meeting in Chicago today called by UAW President Owen
Bieber and UAW Vice President Marc Stepp, union leaders must
determine whether the skilled trades' rejection was based on issues
in the main pact, such as economics, or issues in their separate
contract.
   ``The agreement has been accepted'' despite the skilled trades
rejection, ``and we are going to review the skilled trades
situation according to our procedures,'' UAW spokesman Frank Joyce
said Thursday.
   If the rejection was based on issues contained in the main
contract, then neither new negotiations nor a new skilled trades
vote will occur, union sources said.
   Union officials who asked not to be identified said they
believed the rejection was economic. That means the meeting would
be the only action on the rejection and skilled trades workers will
have to live with the contract.
   The meeting includes those delegates on the UAW's 140-member
national Chrysler council who represent skilled trades workers.
There is at least one skilled trades delegate for each of
Chrysler's nearly 50 UAW local unions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
