<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GELayoffs     05-13 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-GE Layoffs,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Layoffs Announced at Defense Systems Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state official said 900 workers will
be laid off from the General Electric ordnance systems plant here
over the next 18 months because of cutbacks in defense contracts.
   But a company executive, Defense Systems Division Vice President
Arthur Glenn, said GE has not yet decided how many workers will be
laid off or when, although he predicted ``a significant number'' of
layoffs was coming because of forecasts of a troubled future.
   ``The market we serve we thought, up to a year ago, to be at
least on a sustaining basis and somewhat of a growth basis,'' said
Glenn, blaming the sudden turnaround on anticipated government
cutbacks.
   ``As pressure gets tough on defense budgets, government
customers have to make difficult decisions,'' he said at a news
conference in a GE building.
   A Dukakis administration official who asked not to be identified
said GE executives had told the state 900 workers would be fired
beginning in July because of an expected decrease in
defense-related orders.
   The surprise announcement by the largest employer in this city
of 52,000 people came only three months after GE had promised
stable employment at the Pittsfield businesses this year.
   The company had laid off more than 1,000 workers last year when
it closed its transformer plant because of losses in the highly
competitive market.
   The ordnance systems division, which employs 4,700 of the 6,700
employees at the GE operations in Pittsfield, makes guidance
systems for Trident II ballistic missiles systems, components of
the Bradley fighting machine, which carries infantrymen, various
high-speed guns and other military products.
   Neither managers nor union officials answered their telephones
Thursday afternoon.
   GE employs the same number of workers in its Pittsfield defense
systems and plastics plants as it did in 1983, when the company
began expanding the ordnance systems division with 1,400 new
employees. It announced the shutdown of the transformer
manufacturing plant in November 1986 after months of rumors about
the closing.
</TEXT>
