<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0263</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market ran up a broad gain today,
inspired by falling interest rates and a steady dollar in foreign
exchange.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 20.89 to 1,988.89
by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 3 to 1 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 917 up, 293
down and 504 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 72.42 million shares at
midmorning.
   As the dollar strengthened against leading foreign currencies,
prices of long-term government bonds rose as much as $5 for each
$1,000 in face value in the credit markets.
   Analysts said investors around the world were encouraged by the
successful completion late Thursday of the Treasury's three-day
auction of $26 billion in bonds and notes.
   Brokers also noted that there were no unpleasant surprises in
the Labor Department's report this morning that the producer price
index of finished goods rose 0.4 percent last month.
   In addition, Japan reported a continued narrowing of its
international trade surplus. The Commerce Department is due to
report next week on the latest monthly U.S. trade balance.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Exxon, up ~ at 44~;
General Electric, up ] at 39], and Ford Motor, up } at 48.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
climbed 1.30 to 145.08. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .70 at 297.31.
