<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most grain and soybean futures opened slightly
lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade as slack export demand
and forecasts for weekend rains lent a bearish tone to the markets.
   Weather continues to be the dominant market factor as the winter
wheat crop nears maturity and the growing season begins in earnest
for corn and soybeans.
   Market analysts predicted a fairly quiet session, citing
traders' reluctance to go out on a limb by establishing new
positions before the weekend.
   ``Just because of uncertainty about the weather forecast, I
think people will stand aside and then pick it up again after the
weekend,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst in Chicago with Research
Department Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to { cent lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.01 a bushel; corn was unchanged
to 1 cent lower with May at $1.96 a bushel; oats were \ cent lower
to { cent higher with May at $1.55 a bushel; soybeans were
unchanged to 3 cents lower with May at $7.04 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
to lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .02 cent to .50 cent higher with June at 73.57
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .33 cent higher
with May at 80.70 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to .15
cent higher with June at 52.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .12 cent to .25 cent lower with May at 54.35 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Thursday.
</TEXT>
