<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Up 9.5 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose on the London Stock Exchange
Friday, spurred by new buying on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed up 9.5
points, or 0.5 percent, at 1,781.8.
   Volume was a modest 372.9 million shares, compared with
Thursday's 340.8 million shares.
   Dealers said the market was encouraged by Wall Street's strong
start and Tokyo's better finish Friday. By the end of the London
session, the Dow Jones industrial average was more than 20 points
higher.
   In addition, several equity analysts said the market seems to be
on a sound technical footing and looked fundamentally healthy.
Share prices have shown ``remarkably good resilience'' since
Wednesday's 35.8-point drop, one dealer said.
   ``The sentiment is such that the market doesn't want to rush
ahead too terribly fast, nor give up its recent gains,'' he said.
   Fears of rising interest rates that were prevalent in the market
earlier in the week have dissipated, one analyst said.
   Institutional buyers were spotted in the market Friday, helping
to boost sentiment and encourage other players to step in off the
sidelines.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed at 1,428.6, up 11
points.
   The Financial Times 500-share index rose 6.63 points to close at
1,010.23.
</TEXT>
