<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1532EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AtlantaBanks Bjt   05-13 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atlanta Banks, Bjt,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta Banks Respond To Race Bias Charges With Loan Pool</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta's banking community, acting to counter
reports of racial bias in its lending practices, on Friday
announced a series of programs to provide $65 million in
low-interest, low-cost loans to low- and moderate-income borrowers
on the city's predominantly black south side.
   Although denying that racial bias has played a part in lending
decisions, D. Raymond Riddle, president of First Atlanta Corp.,
said, ``In (racial) matters, Atlanta is like Caesar's wife, it must
be above suspicion.''
   Also, one of the organizers said he hoped the programs will
forestall federal investigators.
   U.S. Justice Department officials have said they will look into
the allegations of racial bias, but James C. Mynatt, spokesman for
the newly created loan pool, said he hoped an investigation would
not now be needed.
   Bankers said the loan project, which includes subsidies for
police officers to live in the target neighborhoods, is the first
of its kind in the nation.
   Included in the programs are promises to extend banking hours in
the targeted neighborhoods and to aggressively market the
availability of the money.
   The decisions, some of which bankers said had been in the works
for about a year, were applauded by Atlanta politicians who had
been angered by newspaper reports suggesting area lending
institutions included racial considerations in making loan
decisions.
   Fulton County Commission Chairman Michael Lomax, who is black,
praised the nine banks and savings and loans that ``stepped forward
aggressively and met the challenge that the problem has provided to
the community.
   ``This is the Atlanta tradition at work: black and white, public
and private. This problem has been transformed into an opportunity.
What's been done here today is an important first step,'' said
Lomax, whose own problems getting a home improvement loan were
detailed in news articles.
   The reports in The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution
indicated that white neighborhoods receive five times as many home
loans as black neighborhoods with the same income level.
   ``Race relations in our city not only set the standard for the
South, but for the United States, and the entire free world,''
Riddle said at a news conference announcing the lending programs.
   ``And indeed the banks here have set standards that are
worldwide standards in race relations, as well as industry
standards in profitability and soundness,'' he said.
   The programs include:
   _A $20 million loan pool from nine banks and savings
institutions, with low interest rates in targeted working-class
neighborhoods. The pool will be managed by the newly created
Atlanta Mortgage Consortium.
   The pool would make 30-year, fixed-rate loans for 97 percent of
appraised value, with no private mortgage insurance required.
Interest rates would be from half a point to 1{ points below market
rates, with no discount points charged.
   _A $25 million commitment for low-interest loans from Citizens
and Southern National Bank to include $10 million for home-purchase
loans and $15 million for home-improvement loans, at low interest
rates and low closing costs, to families with incomes of $35,000 or
less.
   _A $10 million commitment for low-interest loans from First
National Bank of Atlanta at low interest rates and low closing
costs, for home-purchase and home-improvement loans to families
with incomes of $30,000 or less in specific working-class
neighborhoods.
   _A similar $10 million program from Trust Company Bank, which
also is making the largest commitment to the loan pool.
   The programs include lower loan costs and more flexible
qualifying procedures.
   Bankers said they would work with attorneys and others involved
in the loan process to attempt to hold down those costs as well, to
make entry into the market easier.
   In addition, First Atlanta and C&S each announced plans to set
aside up to $15,000 a year for the ext five years to help subsidize
housing costs for police officers who choose to live in specified
areas. Joe Patterson, a spokesman for First Atlanta, said the banks
would adopt specific neighborhoods and pay up to $200 per month to
encourage police officers and their families to live in the areas.
   The consortium will consider a similar program, Mynatt said.
   Other participating lenders include Bank South N.A., Citizens
Trust Bank, First American Bank of Georgia, First Union National
Bank of Georgia, Fulton Federal Savings and Loan Association and
Georgia Federal Bank.
   The banks will begin taking applications for the new loans May
21.
</TEXT>
