<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AdvertisingExcesses     05-13 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Advertising Excesses,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Groups Seek Worst Ads</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also ran on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of consumer-interest groups is
calling on the public to nominate the year's worst advertising.
   Each year the groups issue what they call the ``Hubbard''
trophies, an effort to draw attention to advertising they consider
misleading or irresponsible.
   The fourth annual Hubbard trophy ceremonies will be held next
month, and the organizers are calling on the public to send in
nominations. The deadline is June 10.
   Ads from newspapers or magazines, and tapes or detailed
descriptions of broadcast ads, can be sent to Hubbard Awards, 1501
16th St., N.W., Washington, D.C., 20036.
   The trophies are named for Harlan Page Hubbard, a 19th century
advertising pioneer who designed campaigns for snake oils and
patent medicines.
   Coordinating the event is the Center for Science in the Public
Interest.
   Other participating groups include the American Association of
Retired Persons, Consumer Affairs Committee of Americans for
Democratic Action, Aviation Consumer Action Project, Center for
Auto Safety, Coalition on Smoking or Health, Consumer Federation of
America, National Consumer's League, National Council on
Alcoholism, National Women's Health Network and the Safe Energy
Communications Council.
