<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SothebysOffer     05-13 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Sothebys Offer,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sotheby's Shares Priced at $18</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sotheby's Holdings Inc. said its shareholders plan
to sell 22 percent of their stock to the public for $18 a share,
cheaper than originally planned.
   The sale to the public of shares in Sotheby's, the world's
largest art auctioneer, was supposed to have taken place last year
but was postponed after the collapse of world stock markets on Oct.
19.
   Sotheby's has been controlled by U.S. property developer Alfred
Taubman since 1983.
   Initially, Sotheby's said it would sell 7.2 million shares, with
limited voting rights, for between $23 and $26 a share. It later
said it would sell 5.5 million shares at $18 to $21 each.
   The sale of 5.5 million shares at $18 each is expected to raise
a total of $99 million.
   The company said 2.9 million shares are being offered in New
York and 1.5 million are being sold in London, simultaneously at an
undetermined date. The remaining 1.1 million shares will be sold on
the international market at another time.
   The newly issued shares carry one vote each, while the shares
retained by the current holders are entitled to 10 votes each. As a
result, the current shareholders will retain 97 percent of the
voting rights, but the new ones will be entitled to elect 25
percent of the board of directors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
