<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-13 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Skyrocket On Dry Weather Outlook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices skyrocketed Friday and grain futures also
advanced after the National Weather Service predicted a month of
drier-than-normal growing conditions.
   On other markets, precious metals were higher; cattle futures
rose while pork futures were mixed; energy futures were slightly
higher; and stock-index futures advanced.
   Soybean futures, which had posted strong gains in five of the
six previous sessions, leaped as much as 14 cents a bushel on the
Chicago Board of Trade and set new contract highs across the board.
   The National Weather Service said in its 30-day outlook that the
Ohio River valley, central Mississippi River valley and the
Mississippi Delta region would all be drier than normal.
   The large speculative firms Refco Inc. and C&D Commodities led
the trading, analysts said.
   ``They were using that forecast as an excuse to rally the
(soybean) market,'' said Jon Horton, an analyst at Research
Department Inc. in Chicago. ``It's still a bull market, so
everyone's back in it on the long side.''
   Some private forecasters also reduced their predictions for rain
over the weekend, said Mickey Luth, soybean analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The soybean market is particularly sensitive to weather concerns
because of indications that the U.S. soybean stockpile is dwindling
and a large crop is needed to meet expected demand.
   Some analysts have called the recent soybean speculation
excessive but Luth questioned that opinion.
   ``Who knows? From an overall balance sheet point-of-view, maybe
the soybeans should have been up here anyway,'' he said.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents to 4} cents higher with the contract for
delivery in May at $3.06 a bushel; corn was } cent to 1\ cents
higher with May at $1.97 a bushel; oats were { cent to 2 cents
higher with May at $1.57\ a bushel; soybeans were 9 cents to 14
cents higher with May at $7.19{ a bushel.
   The surge in soybean futures supported expectations for higher
inflation, which helped boost precious metals futures prices,
analysts said.
   Platinum futures led group, which had been flagging in reaction
to a government report issued early Friday that said wholesale
prices had risen a moderate 0.4 percent in April. The
inflation-sensitive metals markets had expected a greater increase.
   ``Better buying emerged late in the session as soybean and some
other markets firmed,'' said Stephen W. Platt, an analyst in
Chicago with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``That mitigated the effects
of the Producer Price Index for April and tended to fuel
inflationary expectations that have been building recently.''
   Platinum settled $6.70 to $7.20 higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, with July at $550.30 a troy ounce.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold settled $1.50 lower
to 40 cents higher with June at $453.70 a troy ounce; silver was
4.8 cents to 5.8 cents higher with May at $6.632 a troy ounce.
   Cattle futures gained due to strong cash prices while pork
futures finished mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Advances in the cattle pit were limited by position-evening
ahead of Monday's seven-state cattle-on-feed report, which is
expected to show fewer feedlot placements during April compared to
last year and a nearly equal number of April marketings, analysts
said.
   Support for the hog and pork belly contracts stemmed from
expectations that cash markets will remain firm as hog slaughters
experience a seasonal decline, said Philip Stanley, an analyst in
Chicago with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.
   Live cattle settled .15 cent to .65 cent higher with June at
73.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .48 cent
higher with May at 80.77 cents a pound; hogs were .13 cent lower to
.43 cent higher with June at 53.55 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .35 cent lower to .38 cent higher with May at 54.40
cents a pound.
   Most energy futures prices inched higher in lackluster trading
on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 4 cents lower to 4
cents higher with June at $17.49 a barrel; heating oil was .15 cent
to .30 cent higher with June at 47.47 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .15 cent lower to .42 cent higher with June at 52.34
cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures posted substantial gains on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for June delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled 3.75 points higher at 257.55.
</TEXT>
