<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Trade     05-13 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Trade,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Continues To Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus fell to $6.75 billion in
April, the 12th consecutive monthly decline, the Finance Ministry
said Friday.
   The surplus in Japan's worldwide trade during April declined
from $7.54 billion a year ago and from $7.46 billion in March, the
ministry said.
   Japan's trade surplus with the United States also continued to
fall, dropping to $4.13 billion in April from $5.13 billion a year
earlier.
   Ministry officials attributed the steady decline mostly to the
rise in value of the yen, which makes Japanese products more
expensive overseas and tends to make imports less costly in Japan.
   ``In the background of this trend is, of course, the yen's
appreciation for more than two years,'' a ministry official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Still, however, surveys show that much of the savings from
cheaper exports has not been passed on to consumers.
   Imports surged 31 percent from the previous year's level to a
record $15.67 billion for the month, while exports rose 15 percent
to $22.42 billion, the ministry said.
   Officials said manufactured goods accounted for a record 49.9
percent of imports in April, surpassing the previous record of 48.8
percent set in February.
   Officials noted an increase in imports of manufactured goods
from newly industrialized Asian countries such as Taiwan and South
Korea, attributing the rise to improved quality and price
competitiveness.
   The reduction in the trade imbalance with the United States was
encouraging to the Japanese government, which has been under
pressure from the United States to reduce its large trade surplus.
   Exports to the United States fell 1.2 percent from the previous
year to $7.34 billion, while imports shot up 39.7 percent to $3.21
billion, the ministry said.
   Imports of a wide range of U.S. products increased. Textile
materials surged 62.1 percent to $67.6 million, while imports of
business machines climbed 51.2 percent to $158.9 million.
Audio-video products shot up 288.1 percent to $15 million, and car
imports accelerated by 325.9 percent to $34.7 million.
   Japanese trade figures are calculated on a customs-clearance
basis, which includes transportation and insurance costs in imports
but not in exports. If the costs were added to both, Japan's trade
surplus would be higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880513-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 2038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LoanRaids     05-13 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Loan Raids,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British, California Companies Raided In Loan Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint U.S.-British investigation of companies
that allegedly fail to deliver promised loans and reap fees from
their clients prompted raids in Great Britain and California,
authorities said.
   British and U.S. officials said Thursday's raids were among
their largest cooperative campaigns against white-collar crimes in
recent years.
   They said the targets were part of an alleged scheme bilking
clients out of tens of millions of dollars a year by charging fees
to help them get loans that are never made.
   ``It's one of the most successful loan schemes there has been,''
Sgt. Nigel Lane of Scotland Yard told The Boston Globe. ``The whole
fraud is designed to cross boundaries to capitalize on problems of
jurisdiction.''
   The Globe reported six weeks ago that First Boston Charter Corp.
in Boston and other companies around the world allegedly would
promise to help clients get low-cost loans, charge them large fees.
The companies then allegedly passed the applications among
themselves, making new promises and charging more fees.
   The Globe said none of the clients it interviewed got the loan
or recovered the fees paid.
   Shortly after the articles appeared, First Boston Charter was
evicted from its offices in Boston, and the Globe said two
executives of First Boston Charter were seen at one of the
companies raided Thursday in California.
   Thursday's actions began with simultaneous raids in London and
Lincolnshire, about 130 miles north of London.
   Police in Lincolnshire searched offices of United Kingdom Loans
& Insurance Services Ltd. and arrested its top executive, Lawrence
W. Hill, and Scotland Yard officers raided Westminster & London
Investments Ltd. in London and arrested David Morgan.
   Lane said both were arrested on ``suspicion of criminal
deception'' and released.
   Eight hours later, FBI agents raided a suite of offices in
Irvine, Calif., while others raided the offices of Euro-Kredit N.A.
in Newport Beach, Calif.
   The Globe said the suite in Irvine housed three companies: Zuger
Ltd., Charter Federal Ltd., and Mercantile General Corp.
   The newspaper said agents saw Paul J. Gilbert, who had been a
top First Boston Charter executive, and Marc W. Anderson, president
of First Boston Charter, at the Zuger office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880513-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 1730EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Economy 1stLd-Writethru   05-13 0820</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0847</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Fueled Moderate Boost in Wholesale Prices in April</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: new throughout to UPDATE with market activity; no pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices rose a moderate 0.4 percent
in April despite the biggest jump in energy prices in more than 15
months, the government said Friday.
   The April increase in the Producer Price Index was down from a
0.6 percent March advance, leading many analysts to conclude that
worries over inflation had been overstated by the March increase.
   They said if the volatile energy and food sectors were removed,
the April price advance was a minuscule 0.1 percent.
   ``It is hard to make a real scare story that inflation is taking
off based on these kinds of numbers,'' said David Wyss, an
economist with Data Resources Inc.
   For the first four months of the year, wholesale prices have
risen at an annual rate of 2.9 percent, not much changed from the
2.2 percent increase for all of 1987.
   ``The earlier fears that inflation was taking off were
substantially overstated,'' said Jerry Jasinowski, chief economist
of the National Association of Manufacturers. ``This report
confirms that most of the price increases we have been getting
recently have been in oil. There is no reason to believe that OPEC
will be able to enforce control over oil markets enough to keep
energy prices rising.''
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater called the report
``good news. Producer price inflation remains low.''
   The report sparked a rally in the bond markets as investors
concluded there will be no additional pressure on the Federal
Reserve to drive interest rates higher to dampen demand.
   Prices of long-term government bonds rose as much as $5 for each
$1,000 in face value to yield 9.17 percent. On Thursday the
bellwether 30-year issue's yield jumped to its highest point this
year at 9.22 percent.
   The Fed recently moved to make credit less available to the
banking system because of fears the economy was overheating. That
tightening prompted the nation's major banks to boost their prime
lending rate from 8.5 percent to 9 percent on Wednesday, the first
increase since last October's stock market crash.
   Other economists, however, insisted that the April price report
contained some troubling signs that price increases will be
accelerating in the months ahead.
   ``It would be a mistake to look at this report and say
inflationary pressures have abated,'' said Michael Evans, head of a
Washington forecasting firm. ``I don't think this relief is going
to last.''
   Energy prices, which had posted sharp declines from September
through February, accounted for half of the increase in the overall
index in April, rising 3.1 percent, the biggest jump since a 3.2
percent rise in January 1987.
   Gasoline costs advanced 0.7 percent, while home heating oil shot
up 5.2 percent. Natural gas, which had declined in price in five of
the last six months, rose 4.3 percent.
   Analysts blamed the price pressures on rising world crude oil
prices in late April. But since that time, oil prices have
retreated somewhat, leading some economists to predict the April
price surge will be temporary.
   Food costs rose 0.4 percent in April, down from a 0.7 percent
March increase, as a sharp 16.3 percent drop in the price of eggs
and smaller declines in the price of fruit, fish and beef offset
price increases for pork, chicken, vegetables and coffee.
   The financial markets took the economic news in stride. On Wall
Street, the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 22.55 points to
close at 1,990.55.
   Brokers noted that there were no unpleasant surprises in the
producer price index and instead drew inspiration from falling
interest rates and a steady dollar.
   The dollar finished slightly higher in domestic dealings but
fell against the British pound, which has been gaining ground
despite central bank intervention to stem its rise.
   In another economic report Friday, the government said total
business sales surged 1.9 percent in March, the biggest advance in
more than a year, while business inventories were up a modest 0.3
percent.
   Analysts said the combination of rising sales and small declines
in inventories should translate into continued strong industrial
production in the months ahead.
   The Labor Department gave these additional details on its PPI
report for April:
   _New car prices fell 0.5 percent in April, a big turnaround from
a 1.0 percent increase in March.
   _Capital equipment costs were up a moderate 0.2 percent, half
the increase of the previous month.
   _Children's clothing prices gained 0.6 percent, while men's
clothing costs gained 0.1 percent, the same as the gain recorded
for women's apparel.
   The April increase brought the overall wholesale price index to
106.9. This means a selection of wholesale goods costing $100
during a 1982 base period would have cost $106.90 last month. This
index itself is not adjusted for seasonal variations, as are other
figures in the report.
</TEXT>
