<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-13 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher; Gold Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Precede BC-LONDON</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished slightly higher against most
major currencies Friday in dull trading, as no significant
developments emerged to move the currency market and the British
pound stole the spotlight from the dollar.
   Gold prices edged higher in New York after falling in London.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a bid price for gold of
$451.10 a troy ounce at around 4 p.m. EDT, up from $450.90 late
Thursday.
   Traders said the dollar's fractional rise against most
currencies except the pound was mostly due to technical market
factors with participants balancing their positions in anticipation
of the weekend.
   ``There was really nothing going on; it looked like they were
just buying (pounds),'' said Joseph Cally, a currency trader for
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The pound surged in European trading earlier in the day, despite
reported central bank intervention to stem its rise.
   A report from the Bank of England late Thursday indicating that
the central bank would prefer higher interest rates led currency
traders to conclude that the British government was limiting its
intervention against the pound's rise. That sentiment was
reinforced by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's apparent continued
opposition to massive intervention in the foreign-exchange markets.
   ``The market feels safe pushing for higher sterling,'' said
Nigel Green, an assistant director at EBC-Amro Bank in London.
``They feel free from intervention.''
   The Bank of England did come into the market to sell pounds
several times Friday, dealers reported, but they said the
intervention was not heavy.
   Late in the day in London, the pound was quoted at $1.8910, up
from $1.8823 late Thursday. Later in New York the pound fetched
$1.8903, more than $1.8833 late Thursday.
   The most significant economic news of the day, the government's
report that U.S. wholesale prices rose a moderate 0.4 percent in
April, failed to shake the currency market out of its lethargy,
dealers said.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar rose 0.31 Japanese yen to a closing 124.70 yen. Later, in
London, it fell back to 124.68 yen. By the end of trading in New
York, the dollar was quoted at 124.77 yen, up from 124.53 yen late
Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.6835 West German marks, up from 1.6816;
1.4005 Swiss francs, up from 1.3987; 5.7107 French francs, up from
5.7005; 1,251.50 Italian lire, up from 1,251.00; and 1.2333
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2300.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.6830 West German marks, up from 1.6813; 1.4000 Swiss
francs, up from 1.3987; 5.7063 French francs, up from 5.7020;
1.8855 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8850; 1,249.00 Italian lire, down
from 1,250.50; and 1.2336 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2298.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $449.00 a troy ounce,
down from $451.50 late Thursday. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold
closed at a bid price of $450.00, up from $449.50 on Wednesday. The
Zurich market was closed Thursday for Ascension Day.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.61 to close at a bid of
$451.67.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
rose to $452.20 a troy ounce from $451.90 late Thursday.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.52 a troy ounce, down from
Thursday's $6.56.
   On the New York Comex, silver for current delivery rose to
$6.632 a troy ounce from $6.574.
</TEXT>
