<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OilForecast     05-13 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Forecast,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Expects Lower Prices Than Previously Predicted; Higher
Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government forecasters again have lowered
their prediction of oil prices and sharply raised their
expectations for imports this year.
   In the quarterly publication ``Short Term Energy Outlook,''
analysts of the Energy Information Administration said crude prices
for the rest of this year and next should run $15 to $18 a barrel,
a reduction of $1 to $2 from their January predictions.
   The average for this year should be about $16 as opposed to
$17.30 predicted in January, the forecasters said in the April
edition made available Friday.
   L%anwhile, imports of crude should rise 11 percent compared with
last year, from 4.57 million barrels per day to 5.06 million
barrels, the forecasters said. In January, the EIA, a
semi-independent arm of the Energy Department, predicted that crude
imports for 1988 would rise 2.6 percent to 4.71 million barrels per
day.
   Counting refined products, net petroleum imports this year
should increase 8.7 percent, from 5.77 million barrels per day to
6.27 million barrels. The January prediction was for a 4.1 percent
increase to 6.04 million barrels per day.
   Overall petroleum use should rise 1.8 percent this year, from
16.55 milion barrels per day to 6.85 million barrels, the
forecasters said. Earlier, they had predicted a 0.8 percent
increase to 16.66 million barrels. That would mean the import share
of the market would rise from 35 percent to 37 percent instead of
36 percent.
   Much of the predicted increase in consumption already has
occurred as a result of colder-than-normal temperatures in January
and February and as higher-than-expected demand by the chemical
industry.
   The revisions in forecasts included a boost in expected gross
national product this year, adjusted for inflation, of 2.2 percent
over last year. January's ``Outlook'' envisioned a 1.8 percent
increase.
   Similar upward revisions were made in several categories in the
January forecasts as it became clear that the October stock market
crash did not mean a slowdown in economic activity.
</TEXT>
