<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Intelsat     05-13 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Intelsat,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Investigators Probe Alleged Kickbacks at Intelsat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has subpoenaed records of Ford
Aerospace Corp. in what federal law enforcement sources said Friday
was an investigation of allegations that consultants of Ford
Aerospace and Hughes Aircraft Co. paid kickbacks to former
officials at the Intelsat satellite consortium.
   Documents relating to consultants hired by Ford Aerospace from
1973 to 1978 were subpoenaed in April by the U.S. attorney's office
in Washington, Ford Aerospace spokeswoman Susan Pearce said.
   The U.S. attorney's office is presenting evidence to a federal
grand jury, said the government sources, speaking on condition they
not be named.
   The sources said the investigation focuses on payments made by
Hughes and Ford Aerospace to consultants with ties to former
Intelsat director general Richard Colino and his former deputy,
Jose L. Alegrett.
   Pearce said the company has no reason to believe it was involved
in any improprieties and that it has ``cooperated fully'' with the
investigation. She said an internal inquiry by the company has
revealed no wrongdoing by Ford Aerospace or its employees.
   Colino pleaded guilty last year to siphoning kickbacks out of
construction and financing contracts for Intelsat's new Washington
headquarters. He is serving a six-year federal prison term.
   Colino's attorney, Nathan Lewin, said his client had disclosed
all he knew about wrongdoing at Intelsat.
   Alegrett lives in Venezuela. His Washington attorney, Mark
Shaffer, was not in his Washington office Friday afternoon,
according to a secretary.
   Intelsat legal counsel Arnold Weiss said Colino and Alegrett
were fired by Intelsat in December 1986 and that ``we're not
aware'' that any people currently with the consortium are involved
in ``whatever matters are under investigation'' by the U.S.
attorney's office.
   Ford Aerospace and Hughes Aircraft, a subsidiary of General
Motors Corp., are the two main suppliers of satellites to the
International Telecommunications Satellite Organization.
   Ford is completing a $600 million contract to build 15
satellites for Intelsat, while Hughes has an $875 million contract
for new satellites. Intelsat channels international telephone,
video and data communications on a system of satellites.
   In a civil suit filed against Colino last year, Intelsat accused
him of arranging for the agency to pay half a million dollars to
Ford Aerospace to have the company study Intelsat's satellite
needs. As part of the agreement, Ford was to pay $125,000 to
Ingetel S.A., a Chilean consulting firm, the lawsuit said.
   The pending suit said Ingetel agreed to kick back to Colino and
an associate $100,000. Colino and the associate, according to
Intelsat, provided Ingetel confidential traffic data developing by
Intelsat, which Ingetel used with few changes in a report to Ford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
