<DOCNO> AP880513-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 0618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Brazil-Banks     05-13 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brazil-Banks,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Brazilian Constitution Limits Interest Rates for Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the surprise and dismay of many
bankers and economists, the Brazilian congress has voted to limit
interest rates to 12 percent annually under the nation's new
constitution.
   The 559-member congress, sitting as a constituent assembly to
rewrite the constitution, approved the measure Wednesday night
despite protests by economic experts that the limit was unworkable.
   The article says banks may not charge on any financial operation
more than 12 percent a year plus ``monetary correction'' for
inflation, which this year is estimated will reach 600 percent.
Banks now charge as much as 100 percent a year interest in addition
to monetary correction.
   The congress also voted to bar banks from activities outside the
financial market, such as selling insurance or operating travel
agencies.
   The measure drew sharp criticism from government officials and
the financial community.
   Finance Minister Mailson da Nobrega said he was ``stupefied'' by
the legislators' decision.
   Rep. Antonio Delfim Netto, a former finance minister who voted
against the measure, told his colleagues on the congressional
floor, ``if we can't control the price of a can of sardines, why do
we have the pretension to control interest rates?''
   Former Central Bank President Fernao Bracher called the measure
``generous, but extremely harmful.'' He predicted the interest
ceiling would lead to a consumer spending boom, hyperinflation and
capital flight.
   The author of the amendment, Rep. Fernando Gasparian, a wealthy
farmer and businessman, told the newspaper Jornal do Brasil of Rio,
``my amendment is neither poetic nor leftist. The banks are digging
into everyone's pocket... And because of this, many farmers are
going under.''
   The constitution is Brazil's eighth and will replace the
authoritarian document handed down in 1969 by a military regime
that ruled from 1964 to 1985. The new constitution is expected to
be ready late this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
