<DOCNO> AP880513-0300 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-13-88 2117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Koppers     05-13 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koppers,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Hears Koppers, Beazer Injunction Arguments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court heard arguments
Friday on a temporary injunction suspending a $1.7 billion hostile
takeover attempt of Koppers Co. by British industrialist Brian
Beazer and the investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   After hearing both sides of the issue, the three-judge panel of
the U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeal will rule later whether U.S.
District Court Judge Manuel Real in Los Angeles was correct to
order the injunction in April because of antitrust questions.
   The injunction effectively put on hold a $60-per-share hostile
tender offer for the Pittsburgh-based Koppers by the Beazer group.
The offer has been extended week-to-week and now has a May 18
deadline.
   Koppers contends that competition could be weakened in the
Southern California aggregate market for sand, gravel and hard
stone for construction if properties owned there by Koppers and
Beazer are combined.
   Attorney John Bodner Jr. said appointment of a trustee to
oversee the aggregate portion of the company while competition and
other questions are resolved would be ``very difficult if not
impossible.''
   While Koppers has an aggregate facility in Irwindale, he said
most of the personnel connected with it work in Long Beach,
Pittsburgh or other Kopper offices.
   Bodner also said that Koppers is involved in ``high secret,
sensitive negotiations'' relating to increasing its reserves of
sand, gravel and hard stone. And the Beazer group has a similar
business, almost as big as Koppers, he said.
   ``The competitors would love to know what we're up to,'' he
said, predicting that if the takeover was allowed some employees
would feel obligated to discuss those matters with the new owners.
   ``They will learn it the instant they acquire us,'' Bodner said.
   Mark Leddy, an attorney representing the Beazer group, called
the injunction ``extraordinary and unprecedented'' and said it
should be thrown out.
</TEXT>
